{ Welcome to this Lifetime Repertoire on the London System. The London has a somewhat divided opinion among chess players. Once upon a time, during the times when Garry Kasparov was the World Champion, the London had the reputation of a coffeehouse opening. However, in modern times, this reputation, deservedly so has truly changed. With the former conventional lines heavily analyzed out, the modern generation, led by the World Champion Magnus Carlsen started to look for newer, fresher avenues. In today’s times, the London has formed a part of mainstream chess opening and is part of the repertoire of almost every top player.  Aside from the general reputation, there are a few chess factors to consider. The divided opinion largely stems from the classical setup of London where the arising positions remain closed and lack dynamic play. For example, growing up as a @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  player, Sahaj was only aware of  2.Nf3  Nf6  3.Bf4  c5  4.e3  Nc6  5.c3  Qb6  variation where White's position is already lacking play, the line after  6.Qb3  c4  7.Qc2  would allow  7...Bf5!  and give Black a great position.   However, the London has risen to popularity in the last few years due to the variety of setups at White's disposal. For example:  1@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.Nf3  Nf6  3.c3  was the main choice of GM Le Quang Liem's  LTR on the London System. This change in move order does not obstruct White's  plans, but it does delay the ...c5-push since White has an extra option of  capturing on c5 and pushing b4.   2@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.Bf4  Nf6  3.e3  c5  4.c3  Nc6  5.Nd2  . This move order ensures that  5...Qb6  is not a problem for White since we can answer with  6.Qb3  and now Black does not have the idea of  6...c4?!  7.Qc2  Bf5??  since White can just capture  8.Qxf5  .  Please note that if White had gone 5. Nf3  instead, then the resulting position would allow Black to capture on b2 and take the a1-rook.   3@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.Nf3  Nf6  3.Bf4  c5  4.e3  Nc6  5.Nbd2  . This is the recommendation of IM Alex Banzea's London System as well as this repertoire, albeit with a different move order.  4@@EndBracket@@ Finally, @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.Bf4  Nf6  3.e3  c5  4.Nf3  Nc6  5.Nbd2  is the recommendation for this repertoire. We will explain the move order in the next informational.  These different move orders ensure that White does not become too predictable in the first few moves. But one might wonder, why is it that White tries different move orders at all? Well, this is because the mainline of the London system is more pleasant to play for White: @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.Bf4  Nf6  3.e3  e6  4.Nf3  c5  5.Nbd2  Nc6  6.c3  .  Like the Italian in 1. e4, the different move orders and approaches help White reach this main position. This is one of the bigger benefits of playing London - the mainline tends to favor White in practical play. This is largely because of Black's undeveloped bishop on c8. In QGD positions, Black is able to play ...b6-Bb7 and eventually take ...dxc4 to activate the bishop, but since our pawn is on c3 instead of c4 -  Black's bishop has little to do and remains passive for a long period.   On the other hand, White's light-squared bishop will be perfectly placed on d3, where it controls the longest open diagonal in the position. We believe this to be one of the most attractive points of London. This is why choosing the right move order is a critical task since it is in White's best interest to go for the mainline.    About the course This repertoire is aimed at players who are looking to gain a deep understanding of London. Even though this course is not massive in size. Some chapters have long trainables. We should clarify that most trainables that go beyond move 20 do not necessarily need to be trained, since it is unlikely for it to occur in your games.   The purpose is therefore to understand and deepen your knowledge of the given position. In  London setups, we have noticed that similar ideas can be used in different positions, and it is possible that even though you might not get the same position as the trainable, you end up using the idea. The repertoire contains 17 Theoretical Chapters and 3 Non-Theoretical ones. The theoretical chapters contain a chapter introduction that explains the setup and our approach against it. The non-theoretical chapters are 1@@EndBracket@@ Practice Your Move  Orders. 2@@EndBracket@@ Thematic Ideas. 3@@EndBracket@@ Model Games.   How you should study the course The conventional approach of going chapter by chapter is perfectly fine always. But if the student is interested to learn openings that are trending / more likely to happen in games, we recommend the following chapters: Chapter 2 Chapter 3 Chapter 5 Chapter 9 Chapter 10 Chapter 12.   Of course, other chapters are important too - but learning these chapters should be enough for the majority of your games.  Regarding the non-theoretical chapters, we advise firstly looking at Practice Your Move Orders as this will ensure that you are getting the setup right. Secondly, we strongly advise going through Thematic  Ideas since that chapter covers an in-depth look at how to identify strategic elements of the London. Lastly, the Model Games chapter is quite useful for those looking to learn from the greats of London.   While writing this course, We found six players whose games were quite instructive, these are: 1@@EndBracket@@ Magnus  Carlsen, 2@@EndBracket@@ Levon Aronian, 3@@EndBracket@@ Gata Kamsky, 4@@EndBracket@@ Arjun Erigaisi, 5@@EndBracket@@ Nihal Sarin and 6@@EndBracket@@ Raunak Sadhwani. Arjun and Nihal are Srinath’s present students,  while Raunak has worked with Srinath in the past. Raunak started working on the London and added it as part of his repertoire in 2020, on Srinath’s suggestion. We highly recommend going through their games to increase your understanding of London further.    Thank you for buying this course. Let's get started!    Sahaj & Srinath, 17 October 2022 }
