1. d4 d5
{ •  1...Nf6  After the first 10 chapters, we start looking at the other lines.  2.Bf4  g6  3.Nf3  Bg7  4.e3  O-O  5.Be2  The King's Indian and Grunfeld-related chapters are covered in Chapter 12.   •  1...Nf6  2.Bf4  b6  3.Nc3  Bb7  4.f3  The Queens Indian setup is covered in Chapter 11.   •  1...Nf6  2.Bf4  e6  3.e3  b6  4.Qf3  An important little nuance, with improvement over the Pragg-Carlsen game, also covered in Chapter 11.   •  1...Nf6  2.Bf4  c5  3.d5  is covered in Chapter 13, and features several fresh new, interesting approaches from White. For instance  3...b5  4.e4  is almost new; @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pp1ppppp/5n2/2pP4/5B2/8/PPP1PPPP/RN1QKBNR b KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3...d6  4.Nc3  is strong and precise; @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pp1ppppp/5n2/2pP4/5B2/8/PPP1PPPP/RN1QKBNR b KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3...e6  4.Nc3  White gets nice positions here.   •  1...f5  2.Bf4  is covered in Chapter 14, and I was surprised to learn that the London is one of the most effective and easy-to-play lines against the Dutch defense. It is quite simple to play, and also leads to a healthy advantage!   •  1...e6  2.Bf4  c5  3.e3  Qb6  4.Nf3  This and all the other sidelines are covered in Chapters 15 and 16. We'll see the positions after  4...Qxb2  5.Nbd2  also in different parts of the repertoire. Such coverage ensures that we gain a healthy understanding of the setups even when play deviates from the concrete lines we are familiar with.   •  1...e5  ,  1...c5  ,  1...b6  and the Modern Defence which starts with  1...g6  2.e4  are covered in Chapter 16. }
2. Bf4
{ The next five chapters are dedicated to the lines after 2...Nf6 and the imitating bishop. }
2... c5
{ •  2...Bf5  3.e3  e6  4.Nc3  The imitating bishop is covered in Chapter 6.   •  2...Nf6  3.e3  e6  4.Nf3  c5  5.Nbd2  Nc6  6.c3  The London mainline is covered in Chapter 10.   •  2...Nf6  3.e3  c6  4.c4  The Slav Defense related setups are covered in Chapter 7.   •  2...Nf6  3.e3  Bg4  4.Qd3  is covered in Chapter 8.   •  2...Nf6  3.e3  Bf5  4.Bd3  is covered in Chapter 8.   •  2...Nf6  3.e3  e6  4.Nf3  Bd6  5.Ne5  is covered in Chapter 9. }
3. e3 Nc6 4. Nf3
{ This is the setup we are aiming for in this London Lifetime Repertoire. It is important to hold back the development of the c2-pawn to c3. This is because, in most Chapters, the pawn will go to c4 directly. }
4... Nf6 5. Nbd2
{ One of the mainline positions of the London. This is rich, and fresh and offers a lot of very interesting prospects. The first five Chapters of this repertoire are dedicated to this. }
5... Qb6
{ •  5...Bg4  6.h3  is covered in Chapter 3.   •  5...Bf5  6.Bb5  is also covered in Chapter 3.   •  5...cxd4  6.exd4  Bg4  This is covered in Chapter 5, and we'll get a very good appreciation of playing in different structures.   •  5...Nh5  6.dxc5  The Hypermodern approach is covered in Chapter 4. }
6. dxc5
{ This is one of the most important positions in the London System. This is covered in several Chessable courses for Black and therefore is one of the most important lines to know. We have a deep novelty out here which we are excited about because I think it's going to win us quite a few points. But we have saved it for the students of this course first! }
6... Qxb2 { 6...Qxc5  7.a3  is covered in Chapter 1. } 7. Rb1
{ Finally, this is covered in Chapter 2. } *

