[White "Quickstarter Guide "]
[Black "1...d5, 2...c5 with 5...Qb6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 c5 3. e3 Nc6 4. Nf3
{ The second most popular choice in this position. There are two reasons for going this move order. Firstly, White completely avoids the dynamic variation that arises after  4.c3  Qb6  5.Qb3  c4  6.Qc2  e5!  @@StartBracket@@which is also the main choice for Black against London in The Cheeky Chigorin course@@EndBracket@@, the positions that arise after  6...e5  have been extremely challenging since Black's initiative is more than enough for the material deficit.Secondly, the idea is to delay c2-c3 until Black has committed e7-e6 so that Black is not able to play ...Bf5 anymore. This is relevant since, in some variations with ...Bf5, White goes for c2-c4 ideas, thereby saving a tempo. }
4... Nf6
{ 4...Qb6?  Is close to a blunder since we have a powerful resource  5.Nc3!  Nf6  6.Nb5!  Followed by either Nc7 or Bc7 and Black is lost.   5...Qxb2??  6.Nxd5  is simply losing. }
5. Nbd2
{ Simple developing move. Once again, we will delay c3 until Black has committed ...e6. }
5... Qb6 6. dxc5 Qxc5
{ This is the second most popular move after  6...Qxb2  ,  and for good reason. Even though Black objectively equalizes, Black will definitely have to play extremely precisely and suffer from lack of space for the entirety of this variation. }
7. a3 { Planning b4 followed by c4 next. } 7... Bg4
{ The most popular move in this position. Black's main idea is to go for ...e5 next. }
8. c4 { 8.b4?  Allows  8...Qc3  9.Rb1  Ne4!?=  with equality. } 8... e5
{ Otherwise ...Bg4 is pointless.  8...e6?!  9.b4!  Qb6  10.c5!  Qd8  11.h3  Bxf3  12.Nxf3±  And White has pretty much everything one can hope for. The idea should be to develop the pieces on the kingside via Bd3-O-O and continue with Qc2 or Qe2 and admire the strength of The Mighty London Bishop! }
9. Bg5 e4 { Logical follow-up. } 10. b4 Qd6
{ Only move.  10...Qe7?!  is not as great because of  11.cxd5!  exf3  12.gxf3  Bd7  13.dxc6  Bxc6  14.Bc4±  And White is just a pawn up. }
11. h3 { Kicking the bishop away from the diagonal. } 11... Bh5 12. g4 Bg6 13.
Nh4
{ Mission accomplished, we can now put pressure on the e4-pawn via cxd5 and Nxg6 exchange. }
13... Be7 14. Bg2 Ne5 { Threatening to rupture our castling via ...Nd3+. } 15.
cxd5 { White does not care about ...Nd3 and focuses on the e4-pawn. } 15... Qa6
{ Looks dangerous, but Black's threat of ...Nd3+ can just be met with Kf1. }
16. Nxg6 hxg6 17. Qe2 Nd3+ 18. Kf1
{ With a good advantage thanks to the extra pawn. } *

