[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 c5 3. e3 Nc6 4. Nf3
{ The second most popular choice in this position. There are two reasons for going this move order. Firstly, White completely avoids the dynamic variation that arises after  4.c3  Qb6  5.Qb3  c4  6.Qc2  e5!  @@StartBracket@@which is also the main choice for Black against London in The Cheeky Chigorin course@@EndBracket@@, the positions that arise after  6...e5  have been extremely challenging since Black's initiative is more than enough for the material deficit.Secondly, the idea is to delay c2-c3 until Black has committed e7-e6 so that Black is not able to play ...Bf5 anymore. This is relevant since, in some variations with ...Bf5, White goes for c2-c4 ideas, thereby saving a tempo. }
4... Nf6 5. Nbd2 Qb6 6. dxc5 Qxb2
{ The most popular move. White should presume that Black is under preparation whilst facing this due to the dynamic nature of the position. }
7. Rb1
{ Logical response. Black has three choices. A@@EndBracket@@  7...Qxa2  B@@EndBracket@@  7...Qa3  C@@EndBracket@@  7...Qc3  . }
7... Qc3
{ The most popular move, and rightfully so. This is the best response for Black, as it does not allow White to play c2-c4. }
8. Bb5 { We continue with our normal plan. } 8... g6
{ Once again, when Black plays ...g6 the nature of the position is going to be more dynamic. }
9. e4
{ Extremely dynamic. White does not wait for Black to develop and strikes immediately.   9.Ne5  I have mentioned this before, but it is important regardless to understand why this move does not work with the queen on c3.  9...Bd7!  And now we longer have the idea of c2-c4. }
9... dxe4 { Logical response. However, it is quite dangerous. } 10. Be5
{ The idea behind the previous move since White is able to play Nxe4 in the near future. }
10... Qa5 { Black does not allow Nxe4. } 11. O-O
{ Releasing the pin and sacrificing the f3-knight for the sake of activity. }
11... exf3 12. Bxc6+ { This is by far the most testing out of all. } 12... bxc6
13. Qxf3 Nd5 14. Bxh8 Qxd2 15. c4 { Only move. } 15... f6
{ We are following the game between Le Quang Liem vs Wesley So 2021 1-0 where White played  16.Rfe1  and ended up in a bad position. However, Wesley committed a few small errors that gave Liem attacking chances early on and White won the game. }
16. Rfd1 Qf4 { 16...Qc3  would transpose in this variation after Qxf3. } 17.
cxd5 Qxf3 18. gxf3 cxd5 19. c6
{ With the idea to counter  19...Be6  with  20.c7  threatening Rb8+ next. More in-depth analysis on this line can be found here. }
*

