1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 c5 3. e3 Nc6 4. Nf3
{ The second most popular choice in this position. There are two reasons for going this move order. Firstly, White completely avoids the dynamic variation that arises after  4.c3  Qb6  5.Qb3  c4  6.Qc2  e5!  @@StartBracket@@which is also the main choice for Black against London in The Cheeky Chigorin course@@EndBracket@@, the positions that arise after  6...e5  have been extremely challenging since Black's initiative is more than enough for the material deficit.Secondly, the idea is to delay c2-c3 until Black has committed e7-e6 so that Black is not able to play ...Bf5 anymore. This is relevant since, in some variations with ...Bf5, White goes for c2-c4 ideas, thereby saving a tempo. }
4... Nf6 5. Nbd2 Qb6 6. dxc5 Qxb2
{ The most popular move. White should presume that Black is under preparation whilst facing this due to the dynamic nature of the position. }
7. Rb1
{ Logical response. Black has three choices. A@@EndBracket@@  7...Qxa2  B@@EndBracket@@  7...Qa3  C@@EndBracket@@  7...Qc3  . }
7... Qc3
{ The most popular move, and rightfully so. This is the best response for Black, as it does not allow White to play c2-c4. }
8. Bb5 { We continue with our normal plan. } 8... e6
{ The most popular response. This line is quite critical. } 9. O-O
{ Simple development. } 9... Be7
{ Only move.  9...Bxc5?  is a bit too soon.  10.Be5!  Qa5  11.c4!±  And White gets a clearly better position. }
10. e4 O-O 11. e5 { The point behind e4. } 11... Nd7 12. Nb3
{ Threatening to trap the queen via Bd2. } 12... Qb4 13. Nfd4
{ 13.Nbd4  Qxc5  14.c3  Qxc3  15.Rb3!?  This is an interesting idea that can be investigated further. }
13... Nxd4 14. Nxd4 Qxc5 15. Re1 a6 { Kicking the bishop away. } 16. Bd3 g6 17.
Nb3 Qb4 18. g3 b5 19. h4
{ And once again, White should have decent attacking chances with h5. It is very easy to make a mistake as Black in these positions. More in-depth analysis on this line can be found here. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide "]
[Black "1...d5, 2...c5 with 5...Bg4"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 c5 3. e3 Nc6 4. Nf3
{ The second most popular choice in this position. There are two reasons for going this move order. Firstly, White completely avoids the dynamic variation that arises after  4.c3  Qb6  5.Qb3  c4  6.Qc2  e5!  @@StartBracket@@which is also the main choice for Black against London in The Cheeky Chigorin course@@EndBracket@@, the positions that arise after  6...e5  have been extremely challenging since Black's initiative is more than enough for the material deficit.Secondly, the idea is to delay c2-c3 until Black has committed e7-e6 so that Black is not able to play ...Bf5 anymore. This is relevant since, in some variations with ...Bf5, White goes for c2-c4 ideas, thereby saving a tempo. }
4... Nf6 5. Nbd2 Bg4 6. h3
{ Simple. We see the pin, we remove the pin. This move is relatively less popular than its counterpart,  6.c3  . I don't think that it is a bad move at all, but I don't particularly enjoy the position after  6...e6  7.Qb3  Qc8  with pawns on c5 and e3 since we cannot develop Bd3 anymore. Although, top players have been implementing this setup as White with a fairly decent score.   The text move, on the other hand, is rarely played. At the time of writing, there are 38 games total in this position - 6. c3 had about 500. This is one of the reasons I find this to be more attractive than 6. c3 since it is less likely that your opponent would be prepared for something like this.  Black has two choices: 6... Bh5 and 6... Bxf3, unsurprisingly, they both lead to extremely different positions. }
6... Bxf3 7. Nxf3 e6 8. Be2
{ Clever move. White delays c3 so that in future we can go c4 straight without losing a tempo. }
8... Bd6 9. dxc5 Bxc5 10. O-O O-O 11. a3
{ With the idea of pushing c2-c4. White could not do it immediately since Black had  11.c4  d4!  This is why inserting 11. a3 is important since now White always has the idea of b4. }
11... Bb6 12. c4 dxc4 13. Bxc4 Qxd1 14. Rfxd1 Rfd8 15. Ne5
{ It may seem like the position is extremely drawish, but this is far from the case. In fact, in such situations White is only playing or two results. The reason why White is preferred over Black is because White has two bishops, and since the pawns are on both flanks, the bishop has a natural advantage over the knight due to its long range. }
*

