1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 c5 3. e3 Nc6 4. Nf3
{ The second most popular choice in this position. There are two reasons for going this move order. Firstly, White completely avoids the dynamic variation that arises after  4.c3  Qb6  5.Qb3  c4  6.Qc2  e5!  @@StartBracket@@which is also the main choice for Black against London in The Cheeky Chigorin course@@EndBracket@@, the positions that arise after  6...e5  have been extremely challenging since Black's initiative is more than enough for the material deficit.Secondly, the idea is to delay c2-c3 until Black has committed e7-e6 so that Black is not able to play ...Bf5 anymore. This is relevant since, in some variations with ...Bf5, White goes for c2-c4 ideas, thereby saving a tempo. }
4... Nf6 5. Nbd2 cxd4
{ As a London player, I have always felt comfortable with this exchange. I believe that the c5-pawn is considerably more important to Black in comparison to the e3-pawn. This approach is universal to chess. When we exchange pawns, we always tend to consider what is being exchanged, however, it is always what remains on the board. }
6. exd4 Bg4
{ We looked at a similar position previously where Black opted for immediate ...Bg4. The difference now is that Black has already committed ...cxd4, this is why we can go for the normal plan with c3-Qb3 as we can play Bd3 where the idea of ...c5-c4 is not possible. }
7. c3 e6 8. Qb3 Qc8 9. Bd3
{ Once again, I'd like to reiterate that if Black did not exchange ... cxd4, Bd3 would simply not be possible. Our bishops are now placed perfectly, controlling the two most important diagonals in the position. Personally speaking, I have always felt that Black should not allow this structure. }
9... Be7 10. O-O
{ The development is complete. I believe that in such positions it is important to understand 'how to not turn this into an equal position'. So, let's first understand how Black can potentially equalize this position. The answer is simple, if both bishops were traded off the board, White's advantage would diminish, for the most part, there are exceptions.   This is possible through two ideas: ...Bh5-Bg6 & ... Qd7-Bd6. The former is something we cannot stop, unfortunately, but it is important that we take on g6 and not the other way around, the reason is that after ...hxg6 White can launch a kingside attack via h4-g3-Ng5 and try to push h5. The latter, on the other hand, we can stop. In most cases, whenever Black goes ...Qd7, we can play Ne5! and recapture with dxe5, which keeps the bishop on the board and also kicks the f6-knight from its ideal square, leaving Black with one less defensive resource.   If Black chooses to exchange the dark-squared bishop through another idea, for example, ...Bd8-Bc7 or ...Rd8-Bd6  @@StartBracket@@after castling@@EndBracket@@, we can still go for Ne5 and follow the same idea. }
10... O-O
{ The most popular move. We should be looking to create attacking possibilities on the kingside. }
11. h3 Bh5 12. Rfe1
{ Committing a move like h3 is generally not a good thing since it blocks the possibility of a piece occupying the square, but in this case it does not matter since Black's bishop can only go to g6, after which we will take and push h4. }
12... Bg6 13. Bxg6 hxg6 14. h4 { Let's get ready to rumble! } 14... Qd7 15. Ng5
Bd6 16. Bxd6 Qxd6 17. Ndf3
{ Both bishops are off the board, and yet Black's is far from equalizing. White's idea is simple: g3-Kg2-Qd1-Ne5 and try to push h5 at the right moment. A more in-depth analysis to understand this better is provided here. }
