[White "Quickstarter Guide "]
[Black "1...d5 with 2...Bf5"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 Bf5
{ Black gets the bishop out early. The reader should note that there is a small difference in comparison to the variation with  2...Nf6  3.e3  Bf5  as in that variation the knight has committed itself to ...f6. The majority of the lines here will transpose to that chapter, but there are some cases where it does not. I will explain this shortly. }
3. e3 { Keeping in line with the repertoire. } 3... e6
{ The smart choice. By going with this move order, Black eliminates the choice of  4.Bd3  for now. The reason is that after  4...Bxd3  5.cxd3  c5!  And Black equalizes the position. @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/ppp1pppp/8/3p1b2/3P1B2/4P3/PPP2PPP/RN1QKBNR b KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Nf6  4.Bd3  transposes to the 2... Nf6 3. e3 Bf5 Chapter. }
4. Nc3
{ I came across this move after going through a few different ideas. I think this is by far the most interesting out of all. The idea is simple, by going Nc3 we control the e4-square and are now threatening to go g4 next. }
4... Nf6 { Stopping g4. } 5. Bd3 Bg6
{ 5...Bxd3  6.cxd3  directly transposes to the Chapter with 2. Bf4 Nf6 3. e3 Bf5 }
6. h4 Bd6 7. h5 Bxd3 8. Qxd3
{ Capturing with the pawn is now less preferred because of  8.cxd3  Bxf4  9.exf4  Nc6  because of the isolated doubled pawns. }
8... h6 9. O-O-O Nc6 10. Kb1 Qe7 11. f3 { Grabbing space on the kingside. }
11... Bxf4 12. exf4 O-O-O 13. Nge2
{ With the idea of g4 next. The square on e5 is out of reach for now but still remains an ideal spot for one of the knights. The position is equal, but White has a slight pull due to more space. }
