[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide "]
[Black "1...d5 with 2...Nf6 and 3...Bf5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 Nf6 3. e3
{ We are delaying the development of the f3-knight for two reasons:   1@@EndBracket@@ The knight may develop to e2 in some positions.   2@@EndBracket@@ Sometimes White purposefully delays developing the g1-knight to gain queenside play. }
3... Bf5
{ The idea behind this move is similar to  3...Bg4  .  Black intends to get the bishop out before playing ...e6. Another important note is that unlike the line with 3... c6, Black has smartly kept the pawn on c7 to push ...c5 once the development is complete.  For a long time, I tried to make @@StartFEN@@rn1qkb1r/ppp1pppp/5n2/3p1b2/3P1B2/4P3/PPP2PPP/RN1QKBNR w KQkq - 1 4@@EndFEN@@  4.c4  work here but I did not like the lines with  4...e6  5.Nc3  Bb4!?  and even though this is played regularly at the top level, I believe I have found something much better. }
4. Bd3
{ The solid approach. White offers the trade of the light square bishops. }
4... Bxd3
{ The most popular response, and rightfully so. This is where we include the sideline which works really well for White. }
5. cxd3
{ The point. Doubled-pawns are generally considered to be bad, but that is usually not the case. It is 'isolated doubled-pawns' which is the real issue. In this case, capturing with the c-pawn opens up a file for White which can be used to put pressure on the c7-pawn. Furthermore, moves like ...c5 don't seem as dangerous since we have an extra pawn on the d-file. Lastly, the pawn on d3 makes sure that Black will never be able to play ...Ne4 and we will be going for the e3-e4 break when the time is right! }
5... e6
{ 5...g6  makes no sense.  6.Qb3!  b6  7.Nc3±  and White is clearly better. In a few moves, don't be afraid to throw e4 once development is complete. }
6. Nc3 c6
{ Logical, Black aims to meet Qb3 with ...Qb6, and prepare for ...Bd6 at the same time. }
7. Nf3 Bd6 8. Bxd6
{ This may seem a bit strange at first, but the pawn structure is slightly different from the variations with 4... Bg6. We now have a pawn on d3 instead of c2, and Black does not have doubled pawns on the g-file anymore. The approach, therefore, is different. In these types of structures, the main focus is on getting e4 as quickly as possible. }
8... Qxd6 9. Qb3 Qc7
{ Makes sense as Black intends to challenge the queen with ...Qb6 soon.  9...Qe7  seems counterproductive since the queen is not doing anything besides protecting the b7-pawn. The knight on b8 will also struggle to develop.  10.Rc1  O-O  11.O-O⩲  Sooner or later, Black will play ...Qc7 and it will transpose to the mainline. }
10. O-O O-O 11. e4 { Increasing the tension in the center. } 11... Qb6 12. Qc2
{ 12.Qa3  would have allowed  12...a5!  followed by ...Qb4 next. } 12... Nbd7
13. Rac1 Rac8 14. Qd2
{ Getting out of the way and planning to reroute to the kingside. White remains slightly better, something like:  14...c5  Is not possible anymore because of  15.e5!  Now ...cxd4 is not dangerous anymore since there is no pin!  15...Ng4  16.dxc5  Qxc5  17.d4  Qb6  18.h3  Nh6  19.g4±  Restricting the knight where it will stay for a long time. White is clearly better. }
