3... Bf5
{ The idea behind this move is similar to  3...Bg4  .  Black intends to get the bishop out before playing ...e6. Another important note is that unlike the line with 3... c6, Black has smartly kept the pawn on c7 to push ...c5 once the development is complete.  For a long time, I tried to make @@StartFEN@@rn1qkb1r/ppp1pppp/5n2/3p1b2/3P1B2/4P3/PPP2PPP/RN1QKBNR w KQkq - 1 4@@EndFEN@@  4.c4  work here but I did not like the lines with  4...e6  5.Nc3  Bb4!?  and even though this is played regularly at the top level, I believe I have found something much better. }
4. Bd3
{ The solid approach. White offers the trade of the light square bishops. }
4... Bxd3
{ The most popular response, and rightfully so. This is where we include the sideline which works really well for White. }
5. cxd3
{ The point. Doubled-pawns are generally considered to be bad, but that is usually not the case. It is 'isolated doubled-pawns' which is the real issue. In this case, capturing with the c-pawn opens up a file for White which can be used to put pressure on the c7-pawn. Furthermore, moves like ...c5 don't seem as dangerous since we have an extra pawn on the d-file. Lastly, the pawn on d3 makes sure that Black will never be able to play ...Ne4 and we will be going for the e3-e4 break when the time is right! }
5... e6
{ 5...g6  makes no sense.  6.Qb3!  b6  7.Nc3±  and White is clearly better. In a few moves, don't be afraid to throw e4 once development is complete. }
6. Nc3 Bd6
