[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide "]
[Black "1...Nf6 with 2...b6"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4
{ The Queen's Indian setup. Black achieves this through ...e6-b6-Bb7-Be7-O-O and eventually Black throws ...c5. As a London player, one should avoid a direct transposition into any mainstream opening. I believe I have managed to do exactly that.   In the Queen's Indian chapter, we will be looking at: A@@EndBracket@@  2...b6  B@@EndBracket@@  2...e6    2...b6 is direct, and will be a smaller chapter in comparison to 2... e6 where we will be looking at the idea of 3... b6 directly and 3... c5 before Black goes for ...b6. }
2... b6
{ This move is not as popular, but still possible when facing QID players. Black intends to get the bishop out quickly and delays the development of the f8-bishop. }
3. Nc3
{ Taking action Jobava-Rapport London System style. White intends to push e4 and take control of the center. This move is not as popular. Generally speaking, White goes for  3.e3  . }
3... Bb7 4. f3
{ Continuing the idea of getting e4 as quickly as possible. This move also provokes ...d5 which blocks the fianchetto bishop on b7. }
4... d5
{ 4...e6  This is also possible.  5.e4  d5  6.Nb5  directly transposing into the variations with 4... d5. }
5. e4 { We will push the pawn anyways for the sake of active play. } 5... dxe4
{ Capturing the pawn seems most logical. } 6. fxe4
{ Black should be careful here to not take the bait with ...Nxe4. } 6... Nxe4
{ Risky choice. } 7. Qf3 Nd6 8. Bb5+
{ If not for this move, the idea with 4. e4 would not be possible. The idea is to provoke ...c6 which blocks the bishop on b7. }
8... c6
{ 8...Nxb5??  will drop an exchange.  9.Qxb7  Nxc3  10.Qxa8+-  with a winning position. }
9. Bd3
{ Mission accomplished. The bishop on b7 is now restricted by its own pawn. }
9... c5
{ Is also possible. The instinct would argue to play  10.Bb5+  in this position but Black can defend with  10...Nd7  since the idea of  11.Bc6  is not as strong anymore. }
10. Ne4 { Not allowing Black to get comfortable. } 10... Qd7 11. O-O-O
{ We are now threatening dxc5 and Bxd6. Both of them seem quite dangerous. Black's only chance of survival in this position is move the c-pawn. }
11... c4 12. Nxd6+ exd6 13. Qe2+ Be7 14. Bxc4
{ Material is now balanced. However, Black's pieces are far from active. }
14... O-O 15. Nf3
{ The idea is to go Rhe1 or Rhf1 next. Both choices give White a clear advantage. The pawn on d6 is isolated and will be a target in the future. If Black ever pushes ...d5, it will allow the aggressive Ne5 where it targets the f7-pawn. }
