1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4 e6 { This is the main move order for Queen's Indian players. }
3. e3 b6 { The main system for Queen's Indian. } 4. Qf3
{ The same idea. White provokes either ...d5 which would permanently restrict the b7-bishop or ...Nc6 which is not ideal either as the pawn is still on c7. }
4... d5 5. Nc3 { Preparing for castling next. } 5... Bb7
{ This is most logical. We should not be afraid of moves like  5...Bb4  because of  6.Nge2⩲  and we continue the development normally. }
6. O-O-O a6 { Preparing for a queenside attack. We should act fast here! } 7.
g4 Bd6
{ 7...b5  can be answered with  8.g5  Ne4  9.Nxe4  dxe4  10.Qg3±  attacking the c7-pawn. The pawn on e4 could become a weakness in the future. The idea should be to develop via Bg2-h4 and Ne2 or Nh3 depending on the position. }
8. Nge2 { Preparing to recapture with the knight. } 8... O-O
{ This seems very risky since White already has a decent attack on the kingside. }
9. g5 Nfd7 10. h4
{ With a winning position. The idea is to go for Bxd6-Nf4-Bd3 and look for a sacrifice on the h7-pawn. If that does not work, then perhaps h5-g6 should finish the job. }
