[Black "1...Nf6 with 2...e6 and 3...b6 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4 e6 { This is the main move order for Queen's Indian players. }
3. e3 b6 { The main system for Queen's Indian. } 4. Qf3
{ The same idea. White provokes either ...d5 which would permanently restrict the b7-bishop or ...Nc6 which is not ideal either as the pawn is still on c7. }
4... Nc6
{ Black does not wish to block the bishop and aims to go ... Bb7 anyways in the next move. As mentioned earlier, this move is never ideal since Black's pawn is still on c7, which makes developing on the queenside very hard for Black. }
5. Nc3 Bb7 6. O-O-O
{ The discovered attack is not dangerous since the b7-bishop hangs. Therefore, we can simply develop. }
6... Bb4
{ This is the most popular move in this position. However, as mentioned earlier, this falls right into our plans since we are planning on developing the knight to e2 anyways. }
7. Nge2 O-O 8. e4
{ Improving the center and blocking the view of the b7-bishop. } 8... d5
{ This is more or less forced now if Black wants to have any control in the center.  8...Ne7  poses no threats and White can carry the attack with  9.h4!± }
9. e5 Nd7 10. a3 { It is time to kick the bishop. } 10... Bxc3
{ 10...Be7  is also possible.  11.h4!±  With the idea of Qg4-Ng1-Ng3 or simply just g4-Qg3-g5-h5 and go for the break with g6, in both cases - White has a massive attack. Black currently does not have a clear plan, this is largely because of the passive c7-pawn. }
11. Nxc3 Ne7 12. Bd3 { Developing the bishop. } 12... c5 13. Qh3
{ Putting pressure on the h7-pawn. } 13... Ng6 14. Bxg6 hxg6 15. Qg4
{ With the idea of h4-h5. White's attack is too strong and Black has no counterplay in return. }
