[Black "1...Nf6 with 2...c5 and 3...b5 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4 c5
{ The aggressive approach. This line has been trending recently and you should expect this move order regularly in your games. }
3. d5
{ This line was mentioned initially by FM Daniel Barrish on Chessable. I think that this move is objectively the best for this position. The reason is that firstly, we avoid the sharp line after the mainstream  3.e3  Qb6  followed by ...Qxb2, which was also mentioned and analyzed by myself in Agadmator's London Course.   Secondly, and perhaps a more important point is that this setup is a much better version compared to Benoni/Benko structures that arise after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  Nf6  2.c4  c5  3.d5  b5  or  3...e6  .  The benefit we have in comparison to the Benko/Benoni structure is that we have not committed c4, which is one of the main targets in Benko and this is why ...b5 is played. In this case, we will not be playing c4 at all and would rather go for Nc3-e4 ideas instead. }
3... b5
{ Is liked by the computer most. But I feel that practically this is not the best decision as Black ends up in sharp positions where precise play is required. }
4. e4
{ At the time of writing, this move only has 3 games where White has scored 2.5. Black needs to play extremely precisely in order to not end up in a worse position. }
4... Nxe4
{ The only realistic response.  4...Bb7  for example, immediately gives White a substantial advantage after  5.Bxb5  Nxe4  6.Ne2±  White is clearly better thanks to piece activity. The follow-up should be to go castle and Nbc3. }
5. Qf3
{ Kicking the knight away and aiming to take the b5-pawn.  5.Bxb5??  allowas  5...Qa5+-+ }
5... Qa5+ { Only move. } 6. Nd2 Nxd2 7. Bxd2 Qb6 8. a4 b4 9. h4
{ A pretty clever idea aimed against the development via ...g6-Bg7. } 9... Ba6
{ Seems most logical. The Bishop becomes a menace on the c4-square, as shown in other lines. Therefore, Black attempts to solve this problem ahead of time. }
10. c3
{ Keeping the idea of opening up the queenside.  10.c4!?  Also seems appealing and can be explored further should the mainline becomes exhausted. }
10... g6 { Black keeps the tension and focuses on development. } 11. cxb4 cxb4
12. Be3
{ The point behind cxb4. Black's queen is now forced to go to a less comfortable square. }
12... Qf6 13. Qxf6 exf6 14. Nf3
{ Black has managed to keep the king safe for the most part, but the endgame will not be kind either since the pieces are completely undeveloped and lack any kind of coordination. }
14... Bxf1 15. Kxf1 Bd6 16. Bh6
{ We do not allow castling as that would solve Black's problems. White is also threatening Bg7 next. }
16... Rg8 17. Nd2
{ With ideas of Nc4. White can activate the h1-rook via Rh3 at some stage and the a1-rook has a choice between Rc1 or Re1, depending on the position, at the moment - both seem quite desirable. }
