[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide "]
[Black "1...f5, Dutch Defense #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5
{ The Dutch. This is a long-term rival of The London System since this is the only 'viable' setup that does not allow a proper London setup. The lines inside the Dutch are always unconventional due to the nature of the opening, therefore, the reader should be prepared for this.   This is not limited to this repertoire. I have played against Dutch and employed it a few times as Black and the positions are always tricky. However, I believe I have found a simple yet active approach against this where we will keep the London bishop on its favorite square on f4. }
2. Bf4
{ Keeping in tune with the repertoire. Before entering the variations, the reader should understand the setups that Black can employ against this. I will explain this in points:   1@@EndBracket@@ The setup with ...e6. In this case, Black will develop normally via ...Be7-O-O and eventually get the bishop out with ...b6-Bb7 and not push ...d5 and rather go for ...d6 instead. The other setup is the 'Stonewall' dutch with ... e6-d5. This setup is dubious for Black since our London bishop is already out.   2@@EndBracket@@ The setup with ...g6. In this setup, Black aims to go ... Bg7-O-O-d6-Nbd7 and eventually go for the ...e5 push. The approach against this is going to be sharp. We are not allowing this setup to complete and in most cases would strike with h4-h5 at the first opportunity.  3@@EndBracket@@ The setup with ... d6. This is the tricky one. Not because of the lines, but rather the transpositions that come with it. The flexible nature of this setup allows Black to choose between ... e6 and ...g6 and this is what can be complicated. However, the reader should keep in mind that this is going to transpose one or the other.   Let's dig in! }
2... Nf6
{ 2...e6  I realize that it is far too early for clickables. But this line will transpose into the ...e6 setup mentioned on move 3. The direct transposition arises after:  3.e3  d5  4.Nf3  Nf6  5.c4  Please refer to the variation with 2...Nf6 3.e3 e6 to go further into this variation. }
3. e3 g6
{ This makes more sense than 2...g6 since the knight on f6 already protects the h5-square. However, it does not stop us from launching an attack. }
4. h4 h6
{ The difference. If not for this move, then we can push h5 anyways as we have seen in the previous variation. }
5. Nc3
{ Getting the knight into action. We are purposefully delaying the development of the g1-knight for the moment because it restricts the view of the d1-queen. }
5... d6 6. Qf3 c6
{ This was tried in the game Sjugirov,S @@StartBracket@@2650@@EndBracket@@ vs Nepomniachtchi,I @@StartBracket@@2729@@EndBracket@@ 2017 1/2-1/ 2. The idea is to get the queen out to a5 to create queenside play. }
7. Bc4
{ This move pretty much refutes ...c6 since the bishop on c4 can defend on the queenside as well as keep the pressure along the a2-g8 diagonal. }
7... d5 8. Bd3
{ Bringing the bishop back to d3 where it can remain active. Since now ...d5 is committed, Black has basically no queenside attacking chances as there is no time! Right now, we are threatening Qg3. }
8... Be6 9. h5 { We have seen this motif before. } 9... g5
{ Is also possible. } 10. Be5
{ Keeping the pressure.  10.Bxb8  looks tempting but allows for  10...g4  11.Qf4  Qxb8  12.Bxf5⩲  and even though the position is still better, I prefer the main move. }
10... Qc8 11. Bxf6 exf6 12. Nge2
{ White will win the pawn anyways via Ng3-Nxf5. } *

