[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide "]
[Black "1...e6 with 2...c5"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 e6
{ This can become a tricky move order against London. Black intends to delay ...Nf6 and use the extra move to gain activity on the queenside. Of course, it goes without saying that lines will transpose if and when Black plays ...Nf6. }
2. Bf4 c5
{ This is the clever move order since we cannot push d5 anymore. However, there is a drawback too. Since Black has committed ...e6 the possibility of getting the bishop out to f5 or g4 is not possible anymore.   2...d5  This is also possible, and there is a big chance of transposition since ...Nf6 is very likely.  3.e3  Nf6  4.Nf3  transposes to either 4... Nd6 5. Ne5 or 4... c5 5. c3, which is mainline in London.   2...Nf6  transposes to 1... Nf6 2. Bf4 e6 3. e3. }
3. e3 { Logical move. } 3... Qb6
{ The tricky move once again. Black takes advantage of the extra move and goes for the b2-pawn.  3...Nf6  will transpose after  4.Nf3  Here if Black plays  4...d5  5.Nbd2  Nc6  6.c3  transposes directly into the London Mainline Chapter. }
4. Nf3
{ Staying true to the roots. I should mention that this idea is the backbone of this repertoire since we play it against one of the most popular and trending variations with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.Bf4  c5  3.e3  Nc6  4.Nf3  Nf6  5.Nbd2  . Of course, the position is slightly different but the ideas remain largely similar. }
4... Qxb2 5. Nbd2 Nf6
{ Black focuses on development.  5...d5?  This move is an attempt to transpose the position into the mainline but here White has a plethora of choices that provide a winning advantage.  6.Rb1  Seems the simplest.  6...Qxa2  7.Bxb8  Rxb8  8.Bb5+  Damaging Black's castling.  8...Kd8  9.Ne5  Targeting the f7-pawn.  9...Nh6  10.Ndc4!  +-  And the queen is trapped on a2! }
6. Rb1 Qc3
{ We have reached a very similar position in comparison to Chapter 8 with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pppp/5n2/3p4/3P1B2/8/PPP1PPPP/RN1QKBNR w KQkq - 2 3@@EndFEN@@  3.e3  c5  4.Nf3  Qb6  5.Nbd2  Qxb2  6.Rb1  Qc3  .  The difference between these two positions is only that Black's pawn is on e6 instead of e7 and the d7-pawn is on d5. While in that position we went for Bb5+. In this case, we will go for Bd3 instead. }
7. Bd3 { The idea is to push e4. So, we are provoking ... d5. } 7... d5 8. dxc5
{ Crucial move. We do not want Black to play ...c4 and kick our bishop. } 8...
Nc6
{ This move transposes into a slightly better version of Chapter 2. In that position, our bishop was on b5 but here it is on a much better square on d3. }
9. O-O Qxc5 10. Nb3
{ This also is perhaps one of the reasons why the bishop is superior on d3, had it been on b5 then Nb3 was simply not possible! }
10... Qa3 11. Nbd4 Nxd4 12. exd4
{ With a clearly better position. White plans to go Ne5 in the next move and threaten Bb5+. Black, therefore, has to play ...a6 at some stage. We can then launch an attack on the kingside via h4-h5. }
