[Black "Introduction to 6...Qxc5"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1b1kb1r/pp2pppp/2n2n2/2qp4/5B2/4PN2/PPPN1PPP/R2QKB1R w KQkq - 0 6"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ Hello everyone! In this chapter, we will be looking at the recapture with @@StartFEN@@r1b1kb1r/pp2pppp/1qn2n2/2Pp4/5B2/4PN2/PPPN1PPP/R2QKB1R b KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Qxc5  . This variation is considered to be the worse capture out of the two. We will be covering @@StartFEN@@r1b1kb1r/pp2pppp/1qn2n2/2Pp4/5B2/4PN2/PPPN1PPP/R2QKB1R b KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Qxb2  in the next chapter.   The idea here remains quite simple. Black's queen on c5 is slightly misplaced, it is a well-known principle of opening to not bring the queen out too early and this chapter is an example of this. White's plan revolves around playing a3-b4-c4 or a3-c4-b4 depending on the move order.   Once the pawn has reached c4, Black will have the choice of capturing the pawn or simply leaving it. If Black captures, it is obvious to recapture with the bishop or knight and White will have fantastic activity. If Black chooses to not capture, White will plan to go c4-c5! to further gain space on the queenside.   The main variation with @@StartFEN@@r3kb1r/pp2pppp/2n2n2/2qp4/2P2Bb1/P3PN2/1P1N1PPP/R2QKB1R b KQkq c3 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8...e5  with the idea of ...e4 is an exception where White keeps the pawn on c4 to maintain tension around the e4-pawn. }
6. -- *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1) 1...d5 2.Bf4 c5 with 6...Qxc5"]
[Black "7...a5 8.c4 e6"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 c5 3. e3 Nc6 4. Nf3
{ The second most popular choice in this position. There are two reasons for going this move order. Firstly, White completely avoids the dynamic variation that arises after  4.c3  Qb6  5.Qb3  c4  6.Qc2  e5!  @@StartBracket@@which is also the main choice for Black against London in The Cheeky Chigorin course@@EndBracket@@, the positions that arise after  6...e5  have been extremely challenging since Black's initiative is more than enough for the material deficit.   Secondly, the idea is to delay c2-c3 until Black has committed e7-e6 so that Black is not able to play ...Bf5 anymore. This is relevant since, in some variations with ...Bf5, White goes for c2-c4 ideas, thereby saving a tempo. }
4... Nf6
{ 4...Qb6?  Is close to a blunder since we have a powerful resource  5.Nc3!  Nf6  6.Nb5!  Followed by either Nc7 or Bc7 and Black is lost.   5...Qxb2??  6.Nxd5  is simply losing. }
5. Nbd2
{ Simple developing move. Once again, we will delay c3 until Black has committed ...e6. }
5... Qb6 6. dxc5 Qxc5
{ This is the second most popular move after  6...Qxb2  ,  and for good reason. Even though Black objectively equalizes, Black will definitely have to play extremely precisely and suffer from lack of space for the entirety of this variation. }
7. a3 { Planning b4 followed by c4 next. } 7... a5
{ Weakening Black's queenside. Time to punish! } 8. c4 e6 9. Rc1 Qb6 10. cxd5
exd5
{ 10...Nxd5?!  allows  11.Nc4  Qd8  12.Bg3  Be7  13.Bd3  O-O  14.O-O+-  And very soon Black will run out of moves. White, on the other hand, can continue with Qc2-Rfd1 and there will be a tactic waiting soon enough :@@EndBracket@@ }
11. Qb3 Qxb3 12. Nxb3
{ Followed by 13. Bb5. It should be clear why ...a5 was a bad move. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1) 1...d5 2.Bf4 c5 with 6...Qxc5"]
[Black "7...g6 8.b4 Qb6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 c5 3. e3 Nc6 4. Nf3
{ The second most popular choice in this position. There are two reasons for going this move order. Firstly, White completely avoids the dynamic variation that arises after  4.c3  Qb6  5.Qb3  c4  6.Qc2  e5!  @@StartBracket@@which is also the main choice for Black against London in The Cheeky Chigorin course@@EndBracket@@, the positions that arise after  6...e5  have been extremely challenging since Black's initiative is more than enough for the material deficit.   Secondly, the idea is to delay c2-c3 until Black has committed e7-e6 so that Black is not able to play ...Bf5 anymore. This is relevant since, in some variations with ...Bf5, White goes for c2-c4 ideas, thereby saving a tempo. }
4... Nf6
{ 4...Qb6?  Is close to a blunder since we have a powerful resource  5.Nc3!  Nf6  6.Nb5!  Followed by either Nc7 or Bc7 and Black is lost.   5...Qxb2??  6.Nxd5  is simply losing. }
5. Nbd2
{ Simple developing move. Once again, we will delay c3 until Black has committed ...e6. }
5... Qb6 6. dxc5 Qxc5
{ This is the second most popular move after  6...Qxb2  ,  and for good reason. Even though Black objectively equalizes, Black will definitely have to play extremely precisely and suffer from lack of space for the entirety of this variation. }
7. a3 { Planning b4 followed by c4 next. } 7... g6 8. b4 Qb6 9. c4 Bg7
{ Developing move that threatens a sneaky discovered tactic with ...Nh5.  9...dxc4??  10.Nxc4  Qd8  11.Qa4!  +-  Followed by Rd1 and White is crushing. }
10. c5 Qd8 11. b5
{ An important intermezzo.  11.Rc1  a6  Although White is comfortable here. It is much better to have the b4-pawn on b6, since it grabs more space and controls the critical c7-square. This is why inserting b5 is essential. }
11... Na5 12. Rc1
{ As mentioned earlier, this is a much better version in comparison to playing Rc1 straight since a6 will always be met with b6, in some cases, White can also try just taking bxa6 followed by c6. Either way, there is no doubt that White has more space on the queenside. This is a good time to complete our development on the kingside. }
12... O-O 13. Be2 a6 14. b6 Bd7
{ Smart move. Black uses prophylaxis against  15.Nb3  which can now be met with Ba4.   14...Bf5?  Looks extremely logical and active. But is in fact, close to a blunder since it allows  15.Nb3!  Nxb3  16.Qxb3+-  It may not seem like it at first. But White is already winning, the reason is simple, White has tremendous space on the queenside that poses a deadly threat of c5-c6. The next few moves will be O-O, Nd4, Bc7, c6 which seems inevitable. Black can always go Rc8-Rxc7, and this is probably the only way to avoid losing immediately. In any case - White has an easy game ahead.   14...Bg4  Meets the same fate.  15.Nb3!  Nc6  We already know what happens with ...Nxb3, so let's take a look at this instead.  16.Nfd4!  Challenging the knight since it blocks c5-c6 ideas.  16...Bd7  Only move.   16...Bxe2  17.Qxe2  Rc8  18.Nxc6  Rxc6  19.O-O!+-  White can now threaten either 20. Nd4 or 20. Na5 and it's clearly winning.   Don't rush with  19.Nd4  yet since Black can go  19...Qxb6  20.Nxc6  Qxc6  and even though White is clearly better there, there is no reason to allow it.  17.Bc7  Qe8  18.O-O  With the idea of taking 19.Nxc6 followed by 20. Na5 or 20. Nd4 and White has a fantastic position. }
15. O-O Rc8 16. Nd4
{ Preparing for N2b3 in the near future. It should be noted that  16.Bc7?  allows  16...Rxc7  17.bxc7  Qxc7⩱  With the idea of e7-e5, Re8 and Black has 0 weaknesses in the position, not to mention that sooner or later Black will be able to capture the isolated c5-pawn. In a general sense, it should be noted that initiative should take preference over material. This position is a good example of this since White is up in material, but it is Black who is better. }
16... Re8 { Threatening ...e5. } 17. Be5 { Dominance. } 17... Nc6 18. f4
{ 18.Nxc6  with the idea of 19. Nb3-d4 is also possible, but this just seems crushing.   18...Nxe5??  is obviously a blunder, but London players should always know what to do when the bishop is gone ;@@EndBracket@@  19.fxe5  Ne4  20.Nxe4  dxe4  21.e6!  There are other ways to win here too. But this seems the most effective.  21...Bxe6  22.Nxe6  Qxd1  23.Bxd1  fxe6  24.Bb3+-  --  followed by  25.Bxe6  and White is completely winning. }
