Nd3+ 16. Kf1 O-O 17. Bxf6 Qxf6 18. Nf5 Bxf5 19. gxf5 Qxf5
{ 19...Ne5  will transpose after  20.Nxe4  Qxf5  . } 20. Nxe4 Ne5 21. d6 Bh4
22. Kg1
{ With the idea of Ra2 to protect the f2-pawn. It should be noted that @@StartFEN@@2r2rk1/pp3ppp/3P4/4nq2/1P2N2b/P3P2P/5PB1/R2Q2KR w - - 2 22@@EndFEN@@  23.Ra2  is not just important to protect the f2-pawn, but also to defend against the threat of .... Rc8-Rc4 which can now be met with  23...Rc4  24.Qd5!  If the Rook stays on a1, then after  @@StartFEN@@5rk1/pp3ppp/3P4/3Qnq2/1Pr1N2b/P3P2P/5PB1/R5KR b - - 2 22@@EndFEN@@  24...Nf3+  25.Bxf3  Qxd5  26.Nf6+  Bxf6  the a1-rook will be left hanging. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2) 1...d5 2.Bf4 c5 with 6...Qxb2"]
[Black "Introduction to 6...Qxb2"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1b1kb1r/pp2pppp/2n2n2/2Pp4/5B2/4PN2/PqPN1PPP/R2QKB1R w KQkq - 0 6"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ In this chapter, we will be looking at the most ambitious and precise response from Black. This opening has become popular in recent times. However, with most well-researched openings, the drawback remains that Black must memorize many variations and must be precise in order to not end up in trouble.   White's plan here is to kick the queen away with Rb1 and follow it up with the idea of Bb5 and O-O. Once this is done, White needs to break open the position with either e3-e4 or c2-c4 break. This will provide an extremely dynamic position where White carries the attack.   The variation with ...Qc3 and ...e6 is the most popular move, where White should break with e4 and eventually play e5 as well. This brings a french-like structure where White is a pawn down but maintains sufficient compensation in the form of activity and development. On the other hand, the variation with ...g6 structures remains the most critical. This move was recommended by GM Surya Shekhar Ganguly and GM Sam Shankland in their respective LTRs.   I have chosen the most testing variation of 9. e4 where I have provided 3 different alternatives to choose from. Even though the arising positions are equal, Black would need to memorize 20+ moves, which can be a challenge. }
6. -- *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2) 1...d5 2.Bf4 c5 with 6...Qxb2"]
[Black "7...Qxa2 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 c5 3. e3 Nc6 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Nbd2 Qb6 6. dxc5 Qxb2
{ The most popular move. White should presume that Black is under preparation whilst facing this due to the dynamic nature of the position. }
7. Rb1
{ Logical response. Black has three choices. A@@EndBracket@@  7...Qxa2  B@@EndBracket@@  7...Qa3  C@@EndBracket@@  7...Qc3  . }
7... Qxa2
{ Definitely the worst of the three. Capturing this pawn makes little sense in this case since it is not important to the position. More importantly, Black has bigger problems in this position in terms of the lack of development and of course, the king is in the center. }
8. Bb5 { Simple developing move that puts pressure along the a4-e8 diagonal. }
8... Bd7 9. O-O a6 10. Ra1 Qb2 11. Nb3
{ It is no surprise that the queen is now in danger of getting trapped, a common theme in such situations. }
11... Qc3 { Otherwise, the queen would be trapped. } 12. Bxc6 Bxc6 13. Be5 Qb4
14. Bd4
{ It may not seem like it at first, but Black is completely lost. This is largely due to Black's misplaced queen that is now under White's radar. Right now, we are threatening c3 followed by Ra5 which inevitably traps the queen. }
14... Nd7 { Controlling the e5-square. } 15. c3 Qb5 16. Ra5 Qc4
{ Black has successfully guarded the e5-square. In Hindi, there is a saying that loosely translates to 'to gain something, one must lose something'. The question is, what did the knight give up? }
17. Nfd2 Qd3 18. e4
{ The e4-square! The queen is now trapped. White can follow up with Nc1. } *

