1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 c5 3. e3 Nc6 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Nbd2 Qb6 6. dxc5 Qxb2
{ The most popular move. White should presume that Black is under preparation whilst facing this due to the dynamic nature of the position. }
7. Rb1
{ Logical response. Black has three choices. A@@EndBracket@@  7...Qxa2  B@@EndBracket@@  7...Qa3  C@@EndBracket@@  7...Qc3  . }
7... Qa3
{ The second most popular move. This is slighly inferior to ...Qc3 because in some cases we will have the idea of c2-c4 push. }
8. Bb5 e6 9. c4 Be7 10. Ne5 { No time to waste! } 10... Bd7 11. O-O Nxe5
{ Desparate attempt to simplify matters, but this is generally never a good idea. }
12. Bxe5 Rd8 { Overprotecting the d7-bishop in pursuit of castling. } 13. cxd5
Bxb5 14. Rxb5 Qa6 15. Bxf6
{ We are ready to sacrifice material for the sake of destroying opponent's castling. }
15... Qxb5
{ Biting the bait.  15...Bxf6?  Seems the most logical in a practical game, but is the worst capture out of the three.  16.Qb3  Rxd5  17.Ne4  O-O  18.Rxb7+-  With a completely winning position thanks to the extra pawn on c5. }
16. Bxe7 Kxe7 17. d6+ Kf8 18. Qc1
{ If Black's rook on h8 was on a8 instead, Black would be pushing for the win. It is extremely important to understand why this sacrifice works. Simply put - Black's rook on h8 is not joining the party anytime soon, which gives White substantial initiative. }
18... b6
{ Perhaps the only move. Otherwise White can continue with the plan of Ne4-Rd1 and the advanced pawn on d6 will become a monster. }
19. c6 Rxd6 20. c7 Ke7 21. Ne4 Rc6
{ 21...Rc8?  allows  22.Nxd6  Kxd6  23.Rd1+  Ke7  24.Qc3+-  With a winning position. }
22. Qa3+ Rc5 23. Nxc5 Qxc5 24. Qb2 { Of course we don't trade. } 24... Qxc7 25.
Qxg7 Rd8 26. Qxh7 Qc4 27. Qb1
{ White has an extra pawn, but the drawback is that Black's pieces are no longer passive. White should try to active the f1-rook and aim to push the h-pawn when possible. }
