1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 c5 3. e3 Nc6 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Nbd2 Qb6 6. dxc5 Qxb2
{ The most popular move. White should presume that Black is under preparation whilst facing this due to the dynamic nature of the position. }
7. Rb1
{ Logical response. Black has three choices. A@@EndBracket@@  7...Qxa2  B@@EndBracket@@  7...Qa3  C@@EndBracket@@  7...Qc3  . }
7... Qa3
{ The second most popular move. This is slighly inferior to ...Qc3 because in some cases we will have the idea of c2-c4 push. }
8. Bb5 g6
{ This has been tried many times by Aleksey Sarana in recent games. The nature of ...g6 is going to be more dynamic than ...e6 due to the dynamic placement of the fianchetto bishop. We have to respond accurately to attain advantage.8...Qxc5 will transpose to the mainline with ...Qc3. }
9. Ne5 { Not giving any time for Black to continue their development. } 9...
Bd7
{ This is a good moment to understand the big difference between Qa3 and Qc3. Had the queen been on c3, Black would have comfortably equalized. However, since the Queen is on a3, it allows an extra dynamic resource which demolishes Black's chances. }
10. c4 dxc4
{ This position arised in Korchmar,V - Sjugirov,S 2020 that ended in Black's favour. However, White missed a simple recapture that would have won the game almost instantly. }
11. Ndxc4 Qxc5 12. Nxd7 Nxd7 13. O-O
{ Black's position is a lot more hopeless than it seems. Let's see what happens if Black continues with a 'normal' development move. }
13... Bg7 14. Na5 { Immediately finishes the game. } *

