7... Qc3
{ The most popular move, and rightfully so. This is the best response for Black, as it does not allow White to play c2-c4. }
8. Bb5 { We continue with our normal plan. } 8... Qxc5
{ These types of moves are generally considered to be bad. But regardless it is important to know how to correctly punish them! }
9. O-O { Development is complete, White is ready to throw c4! } 9... e6
{ This would be the most logical. Although it makes ...Qxc5 a bit awkward since Black could have reversed the move order and have an extra choice of capturing the c5-pawn with the bishop. }
10. c4
{ Breaking the center. White's follow-up could be to go Nb3-Nbd4 and put pressure on the c6-knight. }
10... dxc4 11. Nxc4 Be7 12. Nd6+ Bxd6 13. Bxd6
{ Black's castling is halted, for now. } 13... Qd5 14. Ba3 Qxd1 15. Rfxd1
{ Even in the endgame, Black's misplaced king will be a huge problem to solve. }
15... Bd7 16. Be2 O-O-O 17. Rdc1
{ Shifting the focus to the queenside. Threatening Ne5 next.  17...Kb8  Seems most logical but allows  18.Ba6!  Na5  19.Ne5+-  And the f7-pawn falls, White is completely winning. }
