[White "2) 1...d5 2.Bf4 c5 with 6...Qxb2"]
[Black "7...Qc3 8.Bb5 Qxc5 #6"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 c5 3. e3 Nc6 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Nbd2 Qb6 6. dxc5 Qxb2
{ The most popular move. White should presume that Black is under preparation whilst facing this due to the dynamic nature of the position. }
7. Rb1
{ Logical response. Black has three choices. A@@EndBracket@@  7...Qxa2  B@@EndBracket@@  7...Qa3  C@@EndBracket@@  7...Qc3  . }
7... Qc3
{ The most popular move, and rightfully so. This is the best response for Black, as it does not allow White to play c2-c4. }
8. Bb5 { We continue with our normal plan. } 8... Qxc5
{ These types of moves are generally considered to be bad. But regardless it is important to know how to correctly punish them! }
9. O-O { Development is complete, White is ready to throw c4! } 9... g6 10. c4
dxc4 { 10...Bg7?  Loses the pawn on d5 with  11.Nb3+- } 11. Ba4
{ Clever move. White wants to go Rb5 next to kick the queen away from c5 into the corner where it can be trapped. }
11... Bg7 { Black ignores the idea. Big mistake! } 12. Rb5 Qa3 13. Nxc4 Qxa2
14. Nfd2
{ The queen is completely immobilized. It is now just a matter of finding the right way to attack the queen and it will be trapped. Right now, the threat is to go Ra5. }
14... Nd7 15. Rd5
{ Brilliant move. The idea is to play Bxc6-Ra5 to trap the queen. } 15... Bc3
16. Bb3 Qa6 17. Ne4 Bb4
{ 17...Bg7  Loses immediately because of  18.Ncd6+!  exd6  19.Nxd6+  Kf8  20.Nxc8  Rxc8  21.Rxd7+-  With a mate to follow. }
18. Bh6
{ Keeping the king in the center. I analyzed this move to show how White should continue to improve:  18...Rb8  19.Qc2  Threatening Qb2 next.  19...f6  20.Qb2  With the idea of Ra1 to trap the queen.  20...b5  21.Ra1  Qb7  22.Ncd6+  Bxd6  23.Rxd6+-  With a completely dominating position. }
