[Round "?"]
[White "2) 1...d5 2.Bf4 c5 with 6...Qxb2"]
[Black "7...Qc3 8.Bb5 g6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 c5 3. e3 Nc6 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Nbd2 Qb6 6. dxc5 Qxb2
{ The most popular move. White should presume that Black is under preparation whilst facing this due to the dynamic nature of the position. }
7. Rb1
{ Logical response. Black has three choices. A@@EndBracket@@  7...Qxa2  B@@EndBracket@@  7...Qa3  C@@EndBracket@@  7...Qc3  . }
7... Qc3
{ The most popular move, and rightfully so. This is the best response for Black, as it does not allow White to play c2-c4. }
8. Bb5 { We continue with our normal plan. } 8... g6
{ Once again, when Black plays ...g6 the nature of the position is going to be more dynamic. }
9. e4
{ Extremely dynamic. White does not wait for Black to develop and strikes immediately.   9.Ne5  I have mentioned this before, but it is important regardless to understand why this move does not work with the queen on c3.  9...Bd7!  And now we longer have the idea of c2-c4. }
9... a6 { This is another idea. Black forces the bishop to make a decision. }
10. Bxc6+ bxc6 11. Be3
{ Intending the idea of kicking the queen via Bd4 or Rb3. } 11... dxe4 12. Bd4
Qa5 13. O-O
{ Development over material.  13.Ne5!?  is also an interesting idea. } 13...
exf3
{ Forced.  13...Bg7?  14.Nc4!  Qd8  15.Nfe5±  Gives White a nearly winning position. The follow-up could be either Nb6 or Rb6 depending on the position. }
14. Nc4
{ White does not wish to waste time with  14.Qxf3  and goes for the main idea of activating the knight. }
14... Qd8 15. Nb6 { Mission accomplished. } 15... fxg2
{ Seems most logical.  15...Ra7  Makes little sense since White can simply recapture the pawn.  16.Qxf3±  White should be clearly better, if not winning. It just does not make sense to move the rook since ... fxg2 does not give up a pawn for free. }
16. Re1 Bg4
{ Only move.  16...Bg7?  17.Nxa8  O-O  Is also possible. But it falls to a beautiful move.  18.Rb8!±  Paralyzing the bishop on c8. Black is now forced to move the queen, which will drop the pawn on e7. }
17. Qd3 Bg7
{ Protecting the f6-knight.  17...Rb8  Does not make sense because of  18.Bxf6  Qxd3  19.cxd3  Rg8  20.d4±  And White has all the activity. Black's bishop will struggle to develop. The rooks on b8 and g8 are completely out of place and uncoordinated. }
18. Nxa8 Qxa8
{ Seems tempting. But White gets an advantage with a nice tactic. } 19. Bxf6
Bxf6 20. Qg3
{ Threatening Rb8+ and Qxg4. Black is now forced to give up the bishop, and then the pawn on g2 as well. There should still be slight compensation for the exchange, but Black's passive queen is far from utilizing any of it. }
