[White "2) 1...d5 2.Bf4 c5 with 6...Qxb2"]
[Black "8...g6 9.e4 dxe4, the alternative 12.Nc4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 c5 3. e3 Nc6 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Nbd2 Qb6 6. dxc5 Qxb2
{ The most popular move. White should presume that Black is under preparation whilst facing this due to the dynamic nature of the position. }
7. Rb1
{ Logical response. Black has three choices. A@@EndBracket@@  7...Qxa2  B@@EndBracket@@  7...Qa3  C@@EndBracket@@  7...Qc3  . }
7... Qc3
{ The most popular move, and rightfully so. This is the best response for Black, as it does not allow White to play c2-c4. }
8. Bb5 { We continue with our normal plan. } 8... g6
{ Once again, when Black plays ...g6 the nature of the position is going to be more dynamic. }
9. e4
{ Extremely dynamic. White does not wait for Black to develop and strikes immediately.   9.Ne5  I have mentioned this before, but it is important regardless to understand why this move does not work with the queen on c3.  9...Bd7!  And now we longer have the idea of c2-c4. }
9... dxe4 { Logical response. However, it is quite dangerous. } 10. Be5
{ The idea behind the previous move since White is able to play Nxe4 in the near future. }
10... Qa5 { Black does not allow Nxe4. } 11. O-O
{ Releasing the pin and sacrificing the f3-knight for the sake of activity. }
11... exf3 12. Nc4
{ Is another interesting idea that will test your opponents memory in this position. }
12... Qd8 13. Qxf3 { Putting pressure on the c6-knight. } 13... Bg4
{ Only move.  13...Bg7?  Generally speaking, development is a good thing. But this is the exception since it gives White too much freedom.  14.Bxc6+  bxc6  15.Rfd1  Bd7  16.Rb7+-  And the d7-bishop will be taken soon. Without material, Black is simply lost due to horribly placed pieces. }
14. Bxc6+ bxc6 15. Qxc6+ Bd7 16. Qb7
{ Keeping the queen active. White threatens Rfd1 next. } 16... Qc8
{ 16...Bg7??  Once again, this will cost Black.  17.Rfd1+-  The d7-bishop will be taken in the next few moves. }
17. Nd6+ exd6 18. Bxf6 Qxb7 19. Rxb7 Rg8 20. Rd1 { Activating the rook. } 20...
d5
{ Since after  20...Bc8  ,  Black goes for the idea of ...d5 push. Therefore, I thought it might be interesting to show why this idea does not work in this case. }
21. c6 { Kicking the bishop away. } 21... Be6
{ 21...Bc8?  This is one move too late. Since White does not need to move the rook anymore!  22.Rxd5!  Bxb7  23.Re5+!  Be7  24.Rxe7+  Kf8  25.cxb7+-  With Rc7-Rc8 and White will promote to a queen. }
22. c4 { We will not give Black a chance to develop ... Bg7. } 22... d4
{ 22...Bg7  Loses to  23.Bxg7  Rxg7  24.cxd5  Bc8  25.Re1++-  With 26. Rbe7 next. White's pawns are far too advanced. Black is dead lost. }
23. Rxd4 Bg7
{ This is a better version in comparison to ...Bg7 straight away, but too will end badly for Black. }
24. Bxg7 Rxg7 25. c7 { Threatening Rb8+ } 25... Rc8 26. Rb8 Ke7 27. Rxc8 Bxc8
28. Rd8
{ And now ...Rg8 is not possible! White will therefore promote to a queen and the rook endgame is completely winning. Black's rook is in the worst square possible. }
