[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2) 1...d5 2.Bf4 c5 with 6...Qxb2"]
[Black "7...Qc3 8.Bb5 e6 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 c5 3. e3 Nc6 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Nbd2 Qb6 6. dxc5 Qxb2
{ The most popular move. White should presume that Black is under preparation whilst facing this due to the dynamic nature of the position. }
7. Rb1
{ Logical response. Black has three choices. A@@EndBracket@@  7...Qxa2  B@@EndBracket@@  7...Qa3  C@@EndBracket@@  7...Qc3  . }
7... Qc3
{ The most popular move, and rightfully so. This is the best response for Black, as it does not allow White to play c2-c4. }
8. Bb5 { We continue with our normal plan. } 8... e6
{ The most popular response. This line is quite critical. } 9. O-O
{ Simple development. } 9... Be7
{ Only move.  9...Bxc5?  is a bit too soon.  10.Be5!  Qa5  11.c4!±  And White gets a clearly better position. }
10. e4 O-O 11. e5 { The point behind e4. } 11... Nd7 12. Nb3
{ Threatening to trap the queen via Bd2. } 12... Qb4 13. Nfd4
{ 13.Nbd4  Qxc5  14.c3  Qxc3  15.Rb3!?  This is an interesting idea that can be investigated further. }
13... Nxd4 14. Nxd4 Qxc5 15. Re1 a6 { Kicking the bishop away. } 16. Bd3 g6 17.
Nb3 Qb4 18. g3 b5 19. h4
{ And once again, White should have decent attacking chances with h5. It is very easy to make a mistake as Black in these positions. }
19... Bb7 20. h5 Rfe8 21. hxg6 hxg6 22. Qg4 Bf8 23. Nd2
{ With a nearly winning position already. } *

