[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3) 1...d5 2.Bf4 c5 with 5...Bf5 and 5...Bg4"]
[Black "Introduction to 5...Bf5"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r2qkb1r/pp2pppp/2n2n2/2pp1b2/3P1B2/4PN2/PPPN1PPP/R2QKB1R w KQkq - 0 6"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ In this chapter, we will be looking at positions where the c8-bishop gets out. With ...Bf5, we will be going Bb5! immediately to put pressure on the queenside now that the bishop is no longer there to protect. The general idea after Bb5 revolves around c2-c4 breakthrough. However, this must be timed correctly.   For example, it is always good to play moves like O-O and Ne5 before playing c4 since White is better prepared for the open center. The target is of course the c6-knight, and in many positions, White will take Bxc6 to damage the queenside pawn structure. Naturally speaking, the target then becomes the weak pawn on c6. }
6. -- *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3) 1...d5 2.Bf4 c5 with 5...Bf5 and 5...Bg4"]
[Black "5...Bf5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 c5 3. e3 Nc6 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Nbd2 Bf5
{ It is natural for Black to get the bishop out before playing ...e6, another way to do this is  5...Bg4  which will be analyzed next. }
6. Bb5
{ Logical and active. The idea is to pose problems along the a4-e8 diagonal with ideas like c4-Ne5. }
6... e6 7. O-O { Development first, c4 next. } 7... Qb6
{ Activating the queen and preparing to capture dxc5 with Bxc5 so that the bishop does not 'lose a move'. }
8. c4
{ White has a deadly threat of a4 followed by a5 in this position. Therefore, it is in Black's best interest to get out of the pin sooner rather than later. }
8... Be7 9. dxc5 Bxc5 10. cxd5 Nxd5 11. Bxc6+ Qxc6 12. Rc1 Nxf4
{ Surprisingly, this capture only makes Black's position worse than it already is because of the additional threat of b2-b4. }
13. exf4 Qb5 { Otherwise b4. } 14. Nb3 Bb6 15. Nbd4 Qd5 16. Nxf5 Qxf5 17. Qa4+
Ke7 18. Qb4+ Kf6 19. Ne5
{ Threatening g4 next, and Black's king is in big trouble. } *

