1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 c5 3. e3 Nc6 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Nbd2 Bf5
{ It is natural for Black to get the bishop out before playing ...e6, another way to do this is  5...Bg4  which will be analyzed next. }
6. Bb5
{ Logical and active. The idea is to pose problems along the a4-e8 diagonal with ideas like c4-Ne5. }
6... cxd4
{ 6...Qb6  This is the most popular move in this position. However, it would eventually transpose into the variation with 6... e6 soon enough.  7.c4  e6  8.O-O  Be7  9.dxc5  With a direct transposition into 6...e6. }
7. exd4
{ Transposes to the mainline with 5...cxd4. An interesting alternative can also be  7.Nxd4!?  Bd7  8.Nxc6  Bxc6  9.Bxc6+  bxc6  10.c4  followed by Qa4-Rc1 and cxd5. This is another risk-free position for White where we can slowly put pressure on the c6-pawn. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3) 1...d5 2.Bf4 c5 with 5...Bf5 and 5...Bg4"]
[Black "Introduction to 5...Bg4"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r2qkb1r/pp2pppp/2n2n2/2pp4/3P1Bb1/4PN2/PPPN1PPP/R2QKB1R w KQkq - 0 5"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ In ...Bg4 positions, we will respond with the quiet h3!? which asks the question of whether Black will take on f3 or go to h5. The former gives White a double bishop advantage and a risk-free position. The idea is to recapture with the d2-knight and then develop Be2 and c3. Black usually challenges with ... Bd6 after playing ...e6 to eliminate the London Bishop.   In this scenario, it is wise to play dxc5 to distract the dark-squared bishop and launch a queenside attack via a3-b4-c4 which opens up the position, and the power of the double bishops will show. If Black manages to play ...cxd4 before going ... Bd6, then we will simply take on d6 and focus on acquiring the e5-square. This can be done via Bd3-Qe2-Re1-Ne5, giving White a comfortable position. Finally, the 'latter' option of ...Bh5 would allow White to play g4-Bb5-Ne5 which not only puts pressure on the c6-knight but also poses threats like h4-h5 with the idea of trapping the bishop. }
5. -- *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3) 1...d5 2.Bf4 c5 with 5...Bf5 and 5...Bg4"]
[Black "5...Bg4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 c5 3. e3 Nc6 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Nbd2 Bg4 6. h3
{ Simple. We see the pin, we remove the pin. This move is relatively less popular than its counterpart,  6.c3  . I don't think that it is a bad move at all, but I don't particularly enjoy the position after  6...e6  7.Qb3  Qc8  with pawns on c5 and e3 since we cannot develop Bd3 anymore. Although, top players have been implementing this setup as White with a fairly decent score.   The text move, on the other hand, is rarely played. At the time of writing, there are 38 games total in this position - 6. c3 had about 500. This is one of the reasons I find this to be more attractive than 6. c3 since it is less likely that your opponent would be prepared for something like this.  Black has two choices: 6... Bh5 and 6... Bxf3, unsurprisingly, they both lead to extremely different positions. }
6... Bh5
{ A move like this is extremely natural, since Black would play this in other positions as well. For example, after @@StartFEN@@r2qkb1r/pp2pppp/2n2n2/2pp4/3P1Bb1/4PN2/PPPN1PPP/R2QKB1R w KQkq - 5 6@@EndFEN@@  6.c3  e6  7.Qb3  Qc8  if White were to go  8.h3  Black would respond with  8...Bh5  .  Therefore, if your opponent plays this, it is highly likely that they are expecting a transposition, or so they think :@@EndBracket@@ }
7. g4
{ Surprisingly, only three people to date have played this move in the past. The majority had transposed after playing  7.c3  . }
7... Bg6 8. Bb5
{ White's intentions are clear - go for Ne5 and follow it up with c4. It should also be noted that with the knight on e5, White will always have ideas like h4-h5 to annoy the g6-bishop in the future. }
8... e6 { Logical move, Black wants to develop as quickly as possible. } 9. Ne5
Rc8 { Is also possible. } 10. h4 { Threatening h5 next. } 10... cxd4
{ Moves like  10...h6  or  10...h5  allow White to capture the bishop and Black would be forced to play fxg6 which damages Black's structure. White can easily castle on the long side in that case, and will be clearly better. }
11. exd4 { Sooner or later, Black has to move the h-pawn. } 11... h5 12. g5 Ne4
{ Time to simplify matters.  12...Nd7?  13.Nxg6  fxg6  14.Bd3+-  is close to being lost. }
13. Bxc6+ bxc6 14. Nxg6 fxg6 15. Nxe4
{ White has successfully damaged Black’s pawn structure, now it’s a - matter of exploiting this in the long term. }
15... dxe4 16. Qe2 { No time to waste! } 16... Qxd4 17. O-O
{ A little counterintuitive, but it works. It's important to not confuse the move order. For example, if White plays @@StartFEN@@2rqkb1r/p5p1/2p1p1p1/6Pp/3PpB1P/8/PPP2P2/R2QK2R w KQk - 0 16@@EndFEN@@  16.O-O  Black is close to winning after  16...Bd6!   A more in-depth analysis of this line is provided here. }
*

