1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 c5 3. e3 Nc6 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Nbd2 Bg4 6. h3
{ Simple. We see the pin, we remove the pin. This move is relatively less popular than its counterpart,  6.c3  . I don't think that it is a bad move at all, but I don't particularly enjoy the position after  6...e6  7.Qb3  Qc8  with pawns on c5 and e3 since we cannot develop Bd3 anymore. Although, top players have been implementing this setup as White with a fairly decent score.   The text move, on the other hand, is rarely played. At the time of writing, there are 38 games total in this position - 6. c3 had about 500. This is one of the reasons I find this to be more attractive than 6. c3 since it is less likely that your opponent would be prepared for something like this.  Black has two choices: 6... Bh5 and 6... Bxf3, unsurprisingly, they both lead to extremely different positions. }
6... Bxf3 7. Nxf3 e6 8. Be2
{ Clever move. White delays c3 so that in future we can go c4 straight without losing a tempo. }
8... cxd4 9. exd4 Bd6 10. Bxd6 Qxd6 11. c3 O-O 12. O-O
{ The position may seem extremely drawish, but this is far from the case. In fact, White maintains a slight edge in this position thanks to the light-squared bishop. Naturally, White aims to play Bd3-Qe2-Rfe1 followed by Ne5, it should be noted that if Black ever captures on e5, we must always capture back with the pawn. The only worry here is what if Black beats White to the race and starts attacking on the queenside? }
12... Rab8 13. Bd3 b5 { Threatening ...b4. What would you do here? } 14. b4
{ With the idea of a2-a4, putting permanent pressure on the b5-pawn. This idea is quite common in QGD structures where Black generally answers b4 with b5! }
