{ Clever move. White delays c3 so that in future we can go c4 straight without losing a tempo. }
8... Bd6 9. dxc5 Bxf4 10. exf4 Qa5+ 11. c3 Qxc5 12. Bd3
{ Activating the bishop. } 12... O-O 13. O-O Qd6 14. g3
{ Although the position remains equal, once again White seems to be much more comfortable in comparison. White's idea is to take control of the e5-square via Qe2-Rfe1-Ne5 and continue with Rad1-Kg2-h4. I prefer this position because we have a beautiful bishop on d3, so I would try to keep this bishop for as long as possible.   It should also be noted that White's slightly different pawn structure @@StartBracket@@pawn on f4 instead of d4@@EndBracket@@ has a very nice practical advantage, which is that now ideas like ...b5-b4 are not threatening at all and White can just push c4 afterward. Without this idea, I am not sure what Black's plan of action will be. }
