[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4) The Hypermodern Approach: 5...Nh5 "]
[Black "Introduction to 5...Nh5"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1bqkb1r/pp2pppp/2n5/2pp3n/3P1B2/4PN2/PPPN1PPP/R2QKB1R w KQkq - 0 5"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ In this chapter, we will be looking at the modern approach with ...Nh5. We ill be capturing the c5-pawn since it is free for the moment. Black generally follows this up with ... Nxf4-exf4 and now Black has to recover the pawn on c5 which is a struggle.   The idea with ...Qa5 is the only practical way of doing so, and in that case we will be utilising our time well and break with c4! The idea is the same as in Chapter 1 where after ...Qxc5 White has the option of a3-Bd3 and at the right time, to push b4 and kick the queen away. If Black does not go for ...Qa5 ideas, then the c5-pawn will remain. There is no need to break with c4 anymore and White can play more calm with c3-Bd3 and O-O. }
5. -- *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4) The Hypermodern Approach: 5...Nh5 "]
[Black "7...g6 with 8...Bh6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 c5 3. e3 Nc6 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Nbd2 Nh5
{ This hypermodern approach is quite popular at the top level in the past two years. If your opponent plays this, you can safely say that they hate the London, and the London bishop. But what they don't know is that we never needed the bishop to annoy them ;@@EndBracket@@ }
6. dxc5 { Free pawns are always welcome. } 6... Nxf4 7. exf4 g6 8. c3 Bh6 9. g3
O-O 10. Nb3
{ Logical move. White not only overprotects the c5-pawn, but also prepares to counter a possible break in the queenside via ...b6. }
10... b6 11. Bb5 { And now Black is forced to retreat to an awkward square. }
11... Nb8 12. cxb6 Qxb6 13. Be2
{ Not  14.Bd3  since it blocks our queen's attack on d5. This is important since we should not be allowing ...Bh3. }
13... Rd8 14. Qd4 { When up in material... trade! } 14... Qc7 15. O-O
{ And White is simply a pawn up for next to no compensation. } *

