{ Threatening ...e5 next. This is quite logical since Black has two bishops, and wants to open up the position. }
13. c4
{ Before your opponent breaks the center, you break it yourself! This kind of idea is quite normal in many openings. For example, in Nimzo 4.f3 variation, White always threatens to go e3-e4, but before White does that, Black strikes with ...c5! }
13... Rb8 { Only delays ...e5 and gives White an extra tempo. } 14. b4 e5 15.
Rad1
{ With the idea of Rfe1. White's idea should be to take on d5, not e5. The reason is that the former allows White to create a potential passer on the queenside, and the latter activates our opponent's bishop on g7 and the rook on f8. }
15... Be6 16. cxd5 cxd5 17. Rfe1
{ White should be quite comfortably better here. The follow-up could be to play Nb3 followed by b5-c6. }
