[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 c5 3. e3 Nc6 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Nbd2 Nh5
{ This hypermodern approach is quite popular at the top level in the past two years. If your opponent plays this, you can safely say that they hate the London, and the London bishop. But what they don't know is that we never needed the bishop to annoy them ;@@EndBracket@@ }
6. dxc5 { Free pawns are always welcome. } 6... Nxf4 7. exf4 Qa5 8. c4
{ They say greed will get us all. Well, let's try. } 8... Qxc5 9. b4
{ This move was tried by Eric Rosen recently. The game didn't go his way as I believe he either forgot his preparation or mixed up the move order. }
9... Nxb4 10. a3 Na6 11. cxd5
{ In the aforementioned game, Eric went for  11.Ne5  Qa5  12.cxd5  g6  And now Black is more or less fine, since we do not have the crucial tempo with Rc1! had the queen been on c5. }
11... Qxd5
{ It's highly unlikely anybody would dare to take this pawn, but we should know what to do against it anyways. }
12. Bc4 Qa5 { 12...Qd8?  13.Ne5!  e6  14.Qa4++-  Resignation is near. } 13. Rb1
{ Threatening Bb5+ ideas. } 13... Nc7 14. O-O
{ It's not like Black can castle anyways, so why rush? } 14... e6 15. Ne4
{ Taking control of the d6-square. } 15... Bxa3 16. Nd6+ Ke7
{ 16...Bxd6  17.Qxd6+-  And White is clearly winning since Black will never be able to castle. }
17. Nxf7 Kxf7 18. Ne5+ Ke8 19. Rxb7
{ If this happens in your game, you can always claim that you saw this when you played Rb1, and your opponent would have no choice but to believe you. }
