1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 c5 3. e3 Nc6 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Nbd2 Nh5
{ This hypermodern approach is quite popular at the top level in the past two years. If your opponent plays this, you can safely say that they hate the London, and the London bishop. But what they don't know is that we never needed the bishop to annoy them ;@@EndBracket@@ }
6. dxc5 { Free pawns are always welcome. } 6... Nxf4 7. exf4 Qa5 8. c4
{ They say greed will get us all. Well, let's try. } 8... e6 { Logical. } 9. a3
Qxc5 10. Bd3 { Simple development. } 10... g6 11. O-O Bg7 12. cxd5 Qxd5 13. Be4
Qd6 14. Bxc6+ bxc6 { Is also possible. } 15. Qc2 O-O 16. Ne5
{ Blocking the bishop. Black can either take on e5 eventually and give up control of the dark squares or push f7-f6, which restricts the g7-bishop. }
16... Qd4 17. Ne4 Bxe5 18. fxe5 Qxe5 19. Rfe1
{ And White has good compensation for the pawn. Of course, we can take on c6 whenever we want, but I would recommend against that. That pawn is a liability since it is not only isolated, but also in probably the worst square possible on the board as it blocks the b7-bishop. In fact, I think it is Black who would sacrifice this pawn via c6-c5 eventually to gain some activity. This can of course be prevented via b4-Nc5. }
