[White "4) The Hypermodern Approach: 5...Nh5 "]
[Black "7...Qa5 with 8...e6 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 c5 3. e3 Nc6 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Nbd2 Nh5
{ This hypermodern approach is quite popular at the top level in the past two years. If your opponent plays this, you can safely say that they hate the London, and the London bishop. But what they don't know is that we never needed the bishop to annoy them ;@@EndBracket@@ }
6. dxc5 { Free pawns are always welcome. } 6... Nxf4 7. exf4 Qa5 8. c4
{ They say greed will get us all. Well, let's try. } 8... e6 { Logical. } 9. a3
Qxc5 10. Bd3 { Simple development. } 10... g6 11. O-O Bg7 12. cxd5 Qxd5 13. Be4
Qd6 14. Bxc6+ Qxc6 { Black keeps the pawn structure intact. } 15. Ne5
{ Immediately challenging the queen. It’s key to note that since this is a double-knight vs double-bishop situation, White has to make sure the bishops do not get active. }
15... Qd5 16. Ndc4 Qxd1 17. Raxd1 O-O 18. Rfe1
{ And we reach an endgame where White's pieces are placed ideally and Black is far from it. It is surprising to me that the computer shows equal, if I were given a choice to play this position as White or Black, I would choose White every single time.  Black can and should kick the e5-knight via f7-f6 soon, but it makes the e6-pawn weak. Therefore, ideas like Nd3-Nc5 would be quite effective, not to mention that you can always go Nd6-Nxc8 to eliminate a defender for this pawn. If Black does nothing, then White can slowly improve the position via Rd3-Red1-h4 and so on. }
