[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5) 1...d5 2.Bf4 c5 with 5...cxd4"]
[Black "Introduction to 5...cxd4"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1bqkb1r/pp2pppp/2n2n2/3p4/3p1B2/4PN2/PPPN1PPP/R2QKB1R w KQkq - 0 6"]
[SetUp "1"]

6. exd4
{ In this chapter, we will be looking at 5... cxd4. This exchange is in fact, quite ideal for White. There are multiple reasons:   1@@EndBracket@@ if Black plays ...Qb6 we can safely respond with Nb3 since Black does not pose a threat of ...c4 anymore.   2@@EndBracket@@ in the ...Bf5 line White plays the usual way with Bb5-Ne5 and c4, which is much more dangerous in this position since White has a chance to gain superiority on the queenside with the c4-c5 push.  3@@EndBracket@@ in ...Bg4 setups White goes for c3-Qb3 and Bd3 which would not be possible had the pawn been on c5 due to threat of ...c4. I have always enjoyed London positions, but when Black takes on d4, it is the cherry on top! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5) 1...d5 2.Bf4 c5 with 5...cxd4"]
[Black "6...Bg4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 c5 3. e3 Nc6 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Nbd2 cxd4
{ As a London player, I have always felt comfortable with this exchange. I believe that the c5-pawn is considerably more important to Black in comparison to the e3-pawn. This approach is universal to chess. When we exchange pawns, we always tend to consider what is being exchanged, however, it is always what remains on the board. }
6. exd4 Bg4
{ We looked at a similar position previously where Black opted for immediate ...Bg4. The difference now is that Black has already committed ...cxd4, this is why we can go for the normal plan with c3-Qb3 as we can play Bd3 where the idea of ...c5-c4 is not possible. }
7. c3 e6 8. Qb3 Bd6
{ This ambitous try has become popular recently. Black intends to change the dynamic of the game by sacrificing a pawn and getting a double bishop advantage as compensation. }
9. Qxb7 O-O { Is liked more by the computer, but after } 10. Bg3 Rc8 11. Bd3
{ White retains an extra pawn with little to no compensation. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5) 1...d5 2.Bf4 c5 with 5...cxd4"]
[Black "6...Bg4 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 c5 3. e3 Nc6 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Nbd2 cxd4
{ As a London player, I have always felt comfortable with this exchange. I believe that the c5-pawn is considerably more important to Black in comparison to the e3-pawn. This approach is universal to chess. When we exchange pawns, we always tend to consider what is being exchanged, however, it is always what remains on the board. }
6. exd4 Bg4
{ We looked at a similar position previously where Black opted for immediate ...Bg4. The difference now is that Black has already committed ...cxd4, this is why we can go for the normal plan with c3-Qb3 as we can play Bd3 where the idea of ...c5-c4 is not possible. }
7. c3 e6 8. Qb3 Bd6
{ This ambitous try has become popular recently. Black intends to change the dynamic of the game by sacrificing a pawn and getting a double bishop advantage as compensation. }
9. Qxb7 Bxf4 10. Qxc6+ Kf8
{ This position is quite critical. Before we proceed with the moves, we should understand Black's intentions. If this position comes on your board, it is very likely that your opponent prepared this line and has no intentions of drawing the game.   Furthermore, Black wants to launch a kingside attack via ...g6-h5-h4 or ...g5-h5-Bf5-g4, provided that White castles on the short side. If we were to castle on the long side instead, Black has a strong resource ...Ne4! which immediately gives them a winning advantage. This does not mean that the position is worse for White, of course - but it is important to understand these things so that our approach is precise. }
11. Ne5
{ Taking control of the center and limiting the activity of Black's dark-squared bishop. It is also important to note that since Black has a double bishop advantage, it is in our best interest to try and eliminate at least one of them in the near future. Apart from this, we are also intending to push f2-f3 at some stage to kick the g4-bishop and control the important e4-square, this is relevant if we ever want to castle on the long side.   Another side note: at the time of writing, White has won all of the games in this position, so we are on the right track! }
11... Bxd2+
{ This looks like the most logical move, but it is in fact a huge mistake since Black not only gives up the double-bishop advantage, but also gives up the control of the dark squares altogether. }
12. Kxd2 Ne4+ 13. Ke3
{ 13.Ke1  is also fine, of course - but the King on e3 surprisingly helps White develop faster since after developing the f1-bishop, the rooks are immediately connected. }
*

