7. c3 e6 8. Qb3 Qc8 9. Bd3
{ Once again, I'd like to reiterate that if Black did not exchange ... cxd4, Bd3 would simply not be possible. Our bishops are now placed perfectly, controlling the two most important diagonals in the position. Personally speaking, I have always felt that Black should not allow this structure. }
9... Be7 10. O-O
{ The development is complete. I believe that in such positions it is important to understand 'how to not turn this into an equal position'. So, let's first understand how Black can potentially equalize this position. The answer is simple, if both bishops were traded off the board, White's advantage would diminish, for the most part, there are exceptions.   This is possible through two ideas: ...Bh5-Bg6 & ... Qd7-Bd6. The former is something we cannot stop, unfortunately, but it is important that we take on g6 and not the other way around, the reason is that after ...hxg6 White can launch a kingside attack via h4-g3-Ng5 and try to push h5. The latter, on the other hand, we can stop. In most cases, whenever Black goes ...Qd7, we can play Ne5! and recapture with dxe5, which keeps the bishop on the board and also kicks the f6-knight from its ideal square, leaving Black with one less defensive resource.   If Black chooses to exchange the dark-squared bishop through another idea, for example, ...Bd8-Bc7 or ...Rd8-Bd6  @@StartBracket@@after castling@@EndBracket@@, we can still go for Ne5 and follow the same idea. }
10... Bh5
{ This is the second most popular move in this position. Black intends to delay castling for a little bit to avoid any attacking possibilities on the kingside. }
11. a3
{ A very subtle novelty. White is in no rush to attack since we are not sure which side the king is going to castle. If Black decides to castle short side, we can continue normally and a3 will be useful to guard against ...b5-b4 ideas @@StartBracket@@as you will see in the mainline@@EndBracket@@. And of course, if Black goes long instead, then a3 will help to launch queenside attack via c4-b4. }
11... O-O 12. Rfe1 Bg6 13. Bxg6 hxg6 14. h4
{ And we transpose into the mainline with an extra tempo of a3. } *

