11... O-O 12. Rfe1 Qd7 13. Ne5 Nxe5 14. dxe5 Ne8 15. Qc2 { Provoking ... Bg6. }
15... Bg6 16. Bxg6 { 16.Nf3!?  is also possible in this position. } 16... fxg6
{ 16...hxg6  17.Nf3⩲  White can continue with the same idea of h4-g3-Kg2 and eventually go for the h5 break. It also doesn't hurt to insert Bg5 in between. }
17. Be3
{ And White objectively has a better position thanks to Black's broken pawn structure, awkwardly placed pieces, and space. White should try to reroute the queen to g4 perhaps through Nf3-Qd2-Qd4-Qg4 so that h4-h5 ideas remain dangerous. }
