1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 c5 3. e3 Nc6 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Nbd2 cxd4
{ As a London player, I have always felt comfortable with this exchange. I believe that the c5-pawn is considerably more important to Black in comparison to the e3-pawn. This approach is universal to chess. When we exchange pawns, we always tend to consider what is being exchanged, however, it is always what remains on the board. }
6. exd4 Qb6 7. Nb3 Bg4 8. h3
{ White can also play  8.a4  with the idea of a5. However, after analyzing the position in depth it seems that it is better to play 8. h3 right now since after  8...Bxf3  9.Qxf3  e6  Black won't have the idea of going ...Bd6. }
8... Bh5 9. a4 { Threatening a5-a6. } 9... a6
{ For example, if Black develops normally with  9...e6?  White can go  10.g4!  Bg6  11.a5!  Qd8  12.a6±  and Black is in serious trouble. }
10. a5 Qd8 11. g4 Bg6 12. Ne5
{ Without this move, g4 is pointless. White threatens to go h4 and annoy the bishop. }
12... e6 13. h4
{ Logical. Black simply cannot touch the h-pawn at the moment as we can take on g6 and damage the structure, therefore, Black has to take on e5 first. }
13... Nxe5 14. dxe5 Qc7
{ Only move.  14...Nd7??  Loses the piece immediately.  15.h5  Be4  16.f3+- }
15. Qd4 { Protecting the f4-bishop. } 15... Nd7 16. h5 Be4
{ Only move.  16...Bxc2??  Loses material quickly after  17.Rc1+-  followed by Bd3. }
17. Rh3 h6 { Opening a square for the bishop. } 18. Rc3 Qd8 19. Bd3 Bxd3 20.
cxd3 Be7
{ Only move yet again. Anything else is pointless in this position since White will inevitably gain control of the c-file and threaten to occupy the 7th rank via Rc7. }
21. Rac1 O-O 22. Rc7 Rb8
{ This move seems perfectly logical, but is in fact a blunder. This position can also be a puzzle! So if you are interested - White to play and win! }
23. Qa4
{ If you found this - well done! Black's knight has no place to go. So ...b5 is forced. }
23... b5 24. Qd4
{ White is completely winning, not because there is a direct threat, but rather Black's inability to get out of this position. White does not need to rush here at all and can continue with moves like Ke2-Qe3/Qc3-Nd4 etc. Tactically speaking, Black's only way to break in this position is ...f6, which is now impossible because of Qa7! This is why provoking ...b5 was important. Chess is crazy. }
