[Black "6...Qb6 #10"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 c5 3. e3 Nc6 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Nbd2 cxd4
{ As a London player, I have always felt comfortable with this exchange. I believe that the c5-pawn is considerably more important to Black in comparison to the e3-pawn. This approach is universal to chess. When we exchange pawns, we always tend to consider what is being exchanged, however, it is always what remains on the board. }
6. exd4 Qb6 7. Nb3 Bf5 8. a4
{ We have seen this idea before. White simply wants to kick the queen away from b6 and also aims to push a6 to weaken Black's queenside. }
8... a6 9. a5 Qd8 10. Ne5
{ This move has two ideas.   1@@EndBracket@@ White wants to damage Black's queenside pawn structure by taking on c6.   2@@EndBracket@@ White intends to go g4-h4 to pose problems for the bishop on f5. }
10... e6 11. Nxc6 { 11.g4!?  is another interesting idea. } 11... bxc6 12. Be2
Be7
{ 12...Bd6?!  seems logical at first, but is in fact a positional mistake since Black gives up complete control of the c5-square.  13.Bxd6  Qxd6  14.Nc5±  And White will grab the pawn soon. }
13. O-O O-O 14. c4
{ At first, it seems like we are aiming to break the center, but this is incorrect. The idea is to push c5 and get the a1-rook to b6, even if it means sacrificing an exchange. If White is able to do this successfully, White will be clearly better, if not winning. }
14... dxc4 { Logical. Black does not want to allow c5. } 15. Bxc4
{ Threatening Qe2 to put more pressure on the a6-pawn. } 15... Be4 16. Nc5
{ 16.Qe2  is also possible.  16...Bd5  17.Rfc1  White has a slight pull because of the weaknesses on c6 and a6, but I believe the endgame after 16. Nc5 offers considerably better chances. }
16... Bxc5 17. dxc5 Qxd1 18. Rfxd1 Bd5 19. Bd3
{ I will stop here. We have an extremely comfortable endgame ahead thanks to the mighty London Bishop and the d3-bishop that does a great job of keeping pressure on the a6-pawn. We don't need to rush in this case since Black does not have any direct way to get out of this mess. Therefore, we should keep the tension and perhaps consider expanding on the kingside via h4. This can be followed by rerouting the London Bishop via Be5-Bc3 and finally we can look into advancing on the kingside even more via f4-g4. }
