{ This move has two ideas.   1@@EndBracket@@ White wants to damage Black's queenside pawn structure by taking on c6.   2@@EndBracket@@ White intends to go g4-h4 to pose problems for the bishop on f5. }
10... e6 11. Nxc6 { 11.g4!?  is another interesting idea. } 11... bxc6 12. Be2
Be7
{ 12...Bd6?!  seems logical at first, but is in fact a positional mistake since Black gives up complete control of the c5-square.  13.Bxd6  Qxd6  14.Nc5±  And White will grab the pawn soon. }
13. O-O O-O 14. c4
{ At first, it seems like we are aiming to break the center, but this is incorrect. The idea is to push c5 and get the a1-rook to b6, even if it means sacrificing an exchange. If White is able to do this successfully, White will be clearly better, if not winning. }
14... Qd7
{ This is another idea that Black could try, although I feel it's not the most effective one. Black aims to reroute the queen to b7 to put pressure on the b3-knight, as well as put resistance towards our idea of Ra4-Rb4. }
15. c5 Qb7 16. Ra4 Nd7
{ We should be careful of ...e5 breakthrough in this scenario. } 17. Re1
{ Logical developing move that is not only aimed towards the ...e5-break, but also to play Bf1-Re3 to overprotect the b3-knight, and follow it up with Qd2-Rb4.   17.Bd2  Looks amazing but sadly does not work due to a tactic.  17...17...Rfb8!  18.Rb4  Qxb4!  19.Bxb4  Rxb4  And even though Black is technically down in material, the lack of activity from White's side fully compensates for this. }
17... Rfe8 18. Bf1 e5
{ This has to be played sooner or later, otherwise White will continue with Re3 and dominate on the queenside. }
19. Bd2 { Simple retreat, threatening Rb4 once again. } 19... exd4
{ 19...Rab8  One might wonder why this does not work anymore, well it's because Black has pushed ...e5 and the position is no longer considered to be 'closed'.  20.Rb4  Qxb4  21.Bxb4  Rxb4  22.dxe5+-  With a winning position. }
20. Rxe7 { Beauty. } 20... Rxe7 21. Nxd4 Bg6 22. Rb4 Qc8 23. Rb6 Nxb6 24. axb6
{ White is simply dominating here. } *

