[White "5) 1...d5 2.Bf4 c5 with 5...cxd4"]
[Black "6...Bf5 with 7...Rc8 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 c5 3. e3 Nc6 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Nbd2 cxd4
{ As a London player, I have always felt comfortable with this exchange. I believe that the c5-pawn is considerably more important to Black in comparison to the e3-pawn. This approach is universal to chess. When we exchange pawns, we always tend to consider what is being exchanged, however, it is always what remains on the board. }
6. exd4 Bf5 7. Bb5
{ This is the second most popular move, but the most challenging one for Black. The idea is to follow up via Ne5 and c4, this is the main reason why we did not push c3 earlier. I should mention that at the time of writing, White has scored 71% in this position with the majority of the games played by GMs with both colors, this is a strong indication that Black is yet to find a line that comfortably equalizes. There are three main moves to consider here:   A@@EndBracket@@  7...Qb6  , B@@EndBracket@@  7...Rc8  and C@@EndBracket@@  7...e6  transposes to the mainline with 5...cxd4. }
7... Rc8
{ This is another try. The idea is simple, Black does not want to damage their pawn structure. }
8. Ne5 Qb6 9. Qe2
{ Interesting Novelty. White is ready to sacrifice the d4-pawn in exchange for initiative since Black is far from getting their king to safety. }
9... Qxd4
{ If Black does not take, I feel that Qe2 would be completely justified as we saw in the 9...e6 variation. }
10. g3
{ Protecting the bishop. This position is quite critical for both sides, but more so for Black since the king is still far from safety. However, Black is unable to fix this for the moment since both ... e6 & ...g6 ideas allow tactical shots that gives White a winning advantage. }
10... Qxb2 { This is possible, but of course is very dangerous for Black. } 11.
O-O { Development first. } 11... Qc3
{ Also seems logical, but it has a defect. Firstly, Black will not be able to push ...e6 in this position since White has Bxc6-Qa6 ideas. Secondly, if Black decides to ever take on e5, we will recapture with a bishop and the queen will be forced to move, losing a tempo. }
12. Rab1 { Same idea. We are now threatening Nxc6-Ba6. } 12... Nd7
{ Only move. } 13. Rfe1 Ndxe5 14. Bxe5
{ This is one of the reasons Qa3 is preferred over Qc3 since now Black will lose a tempo. }
14... Qc5
{ 14...Qa5??  Blunders away the position immediately.  15.Bxg7!!+-  Boom! } 15.
Nb3 Qxc2 16. Qe3
{ White has tremendous initiative for the material. White can follow up with Nd4-Rbc1 and sooner or later there Black's position will collapse due to lack of development. }
