[White "5) 1...d5 2.Bf4 c5 with 5...cxd4"]
[Black "6...Bf5 with 7...e6 #4"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 c5 3. e3 Nc6 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Nbd2 cxd4
{ As a London player, I have always felt comfortable with this exchange. I believe that the c5-pawn is considerably more important to Black in comparison to the e3-pawn. This approach is universal to chess. When we exchange pawns, we always tend to consider what is being exchanged, however, it is always what remains on the board. }
6. exd4 Bf5 7. Bb5
{ This is the second most popular move, but the most challenging one for Black. The idea is to follow up via Ne5 and c4, this is the main reason why we did not push c3 earlier. I should mention that at the time of writing, White has scored 71% in this position with the majority of the games played by GMs with both colors, this is a strong indication that Black is yet to find a line that comfortably equalizes. There are three main moves to consider here:   A@@EndBracket@@  7...Qb6  , B@@EndBracket@@  7...Rc8  and C@@EndBracket@@  7...e6  transposes to the mainline with 5...cxd4. }
7... e6
{ The most popular response. Black does not wish to waste any time and wants to activate their pieces and get the king to safety. The drawback of such a move is that now the a4-e8 diagonal is unchallenged since Black's light-squared bishop is unable to defend via ...Bd7 anymore. }
8. Ne5 { Immediately putting pressure on the a4-e8 diagonal. } 8... Qb6
{ Only move.  8...Rc8  blunders away an exchange.  9.Nxc6  bxc6  10.Ba6+-  With a winning position. }
9. c4 dxc4 10. Bxc6+ bxc6 11. Ndxc4 Qb5
{ This is a clever move aimed to provoke a4, which we inevitably must. The point is that once White has pushed a4, it stops the idea of Qa4 in the future. }
12. a4 Qb7 13. O-O Nd5 14. Bg3
{ Since 14. g4 is not possible anymore, we will go with a quite retreat. }
14... Be7 15. Qe2 { Protecting the b2-pawn and threatening Na5. } 15... Rc8 16.
Na5 Qb6 17. Nec4
{ Once again, the threat of Nd6+ can be quite deadly for Black. } 17... Qb4
{ 17...Qd8??  Blunders away material after  18.Nb7!+-  followed by Nd6+. } 18.
Ra3
{ The queen is pretty much trapped for the moment. Black needs to act fast. }
18... Nb6
{ Only move.  18...O-O??  allows a beautiful move.  19.Rfa1!  followed by Rb3 and the queen is trapped. }
19. Rc1 { Bringing the last piece into play. } 19... O-O 20. Rcc3
{ Once again, we threaten Rcb3 next to trap the queen. } 20... Nxc4
{ The easy way out. } 21. Nxc4 Qb7
{ The following move is an important middlegame concept that the user should try to understand. This is not just applicable to this position but can also be used as a general strategic theme in chess. When your opponent has two bishops, exchange one of them. }
22. Bd6 Qd7 23. Bxe7 Qxe7 24. Ra1
{ Followed by Rac1 and perhaps a slow move like b3. White can keep long-term pressure on the weak c6-pawn, which guarantees a lasting advantage for White. }
*

