[Black "Introduction to 2...Bf5"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "rn1qkbnr/ppp1pppp/8/3p1b2/3P1B2/8/PPP1PPPP/RN1QKBNR w KQkq - 0 3"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ In this chapter, we will be looking at the copycat variation. This variation is similar to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.Bf4  Nf6  3.e3  Bf5  - Chapter 8 -  and if after 3. e3 Black plays 3... Nf6 will transpose.   However, the main focus of this chapter is 3... e6. I have chosen a rather unusual setup with 4. Nc3 with the intention of kicking the bishop with g4 in pursuit of a kingside attack. The follow-up is obvious, to push h4 and to create firstly kingside attacking chances and secondly to trap the bishop on g6. However, in most cases, White will be playing Bd3 at some point to exchange the light-squared squared bishop so that Black's kingside is defenseless.   Furthermore, it is important to know that the g1-knight will almost never develop to f3 in this scenario since that square is reserved for the f2-pawn. The knight, therefore, finds activity via Nge2-Nf4 and becomes an important piece that carries the kingside attack. }
3. -- *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6) The Imitating Bishop"]
[Black "4.Nf3 instead of 4.Nc3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 Bf5
{ Black gets the bishop out early. The reader should note that there is a small difference in comparison to the variation with  2...Nf6  3.e3  Bf5  as in that variation the knight has committed itself to ...f6. The majority of the lines here will transpose to that chapter, but there are some cases where it does not. I will explain this shortly. }
3. e3 { Keeping in line with the repertoire. } 3... e6
{ The smart choice. By going with this move order, Black eliminates the choice of  4.Bd3  for now. The reason is that after  4...Bxd3  5.cxd3  c5!  And Black equalizes the position. @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/ppp1pppp/8/3p1b2/3P1B2/4P3/PPP2PPP/RN1QKBNR b KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Nf6  4.Bd3  transposes to the 2... Nf6 3. e3 Bf5 Chapter. }
4. Nf3
{ I spent a very long time trying to make this work, but unfortunately was not satisfied with the outcome. }
4... Nf6 5. Nc3 Bb4
{ This is the problem.  5...Bd6  This line was quite nice for White since we get to execute the idea with  6.Ne5!  and this more or less transposes into the variation with 2...Nf6 3. e3 Bf5.  6...h6  7.Bd3  Bxd3  8.cxd3⩲  with a comfortable position. }
6. Bd3 Bg6 7. O-O O-O 8. Nb5 a6
{ Inviting Nxc7.  8...Na6  allows White to get a small advantage with  9.a3  Be7  10.c4  c6  11.Nc3⩲  with a great position. }
9. Bxc7 { The following sequence is pretty much forced from both sides. } 9...
Qe7 10. a3 axb5 11. Bxb8 Bxa3 12. Rxa3 Rxa3 13. bxa3 Rxb8 14. Qb1
{ And this position seemed extremely drawish to me. This is why I decided to go with Nc3 straight away. }
