{ The smart choice. By going with this move order, Black eliminates the choice of  4.Bd3  for now. The reason is that after  4...Bxd3  5.cxd3  c5!  And Black equalizes the position. @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/ppp1pppp/8/3p1b2/3P1B2/4P3/PPP2PPP/RN1QKBNR b KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Nf6  4.Bd3  transposes to the 2... Nf6 3. e3 Bf5 Chapter. }
4. Nc3
{ I came across this move after going through a few different ideas. I think this is by far the most interesting out of all. The idea is simple, by going Nc3 we control the e4-square and are now threatening to go g4 next. }
4... Bd6 { Most precise. } 5. g4 Bg6
{ 5...Bxf4?  is not ideal because of  6.gxf5  Bh6  7.fxe6  fxe6  8.Qg4!±  White gets a comfortable advantage thanks to the weak pawn on e6. The bishop on h6 seems to me out of place. White should try to go Bh3 to not allow Black to castle. }
6. Nge2 { Protecting the f4-bishop. } 6... Nf6 7. f3
{ Defending the g4-pawn and aiming for h4 next. } 7... h5 8. g5 Ng8 9. Qd2
{ Preparing to castle long. } 9... Ne7 10. Bxd6
{ Not entirely necessary, but it is useful since White intends to go Nf4 at some stage. }
10... cxd6
{ Opening a file where our king is destined to go. This allows White to get a slight advantage. }
11. O-O-O Nbc6 12. Nf4 { With the idea of e4 next. } *

