[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "7) Slav Defense"]
[Black "Introduction to Slav"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "rnbqkb1r/pp2pppp/2p2n2/3p4/3P1B2/4P3/PPP2PPP/RN1QKBNR w KQkq - 0 4"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ In this chapter, we will be looking at Slav structures. It is a bit strange for Black to play ...c6 since we have not yet committed c4, but it is popular regardless. Firstly, the reader should understand that with this move order, White has gained a much better version of the Slav since the bishop is out on f4. In the normal Slav Defense, this is not possible.   For example, if White goes @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.c4  c6  then  3.Bf4  is considered to be a mistake since Black can capture  3...dxc4  . The continuation in this chapter is  4.c4  to transpose into the better version of the Slav with the idea of Nc3-Qb3. Please note that this bishop plays an important role on the queenside since Black is unable to defend the pawn on b7 with ...Qc7. Therefore, Black ends up with two choices:   1@@EndBracket@@ Capture. ...dxc4 and then play ...Qb6 or...   2@@EndBracket@@ Defend with ...Qc8. In the first variation, White gets an ideal Slav position since both bishops @@StartBracket@@f4 and c4@@EndBracket@@ become super active.   In most 1. d4 d5 positions, Black's main goal is to get ...c5 or ...e5 break, which becomes nearly impossible in this case, and Black is forced to remain passive. Defending with ...Qc8 is even worse since the queen is placed passively and allows tactics along the c-file via Rc1-cxd5 and there will be threats such as Nb5 or Nxd5, depending on the position. }
4. -- *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "7) Slav Defense"]
[Black "4...Bf5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 Nf6 3. e3
{ We are delaying the development of the f3-knight for two reasons:   1@@EndBracket@@ The knight may develop to e2 in some positions.   2@@EndBracket@@ Sometimes White purposefully delays developing the g1-knight to gain queenside play. }
3... c6
{ The Slav Approach. This particular move order makes little sense because White has not pushed c4 yet. I believe that it is more likely to expect The Slav Approach after  3...Bf5  4.c4  c6  , but we do not play  4.c4  in that position and this is why I decided to add this particular move order. I believe this to be a dubious move since Black is eliminating any chance of pushing ...c5, which is widely considered to be the best approach against the London. Secondly, this puts Black in a tough theoretical spot since the bishop on c8 will either be blocked by its own pawns forever or the bishop would need to come out early, which allows White to put lasting pressure along the b7-pawn. Either way, Black suffers. }
4. c4
{ Wasting no opportunity. It is worth noting that this is a far superior version of the Slav for White. Let's do a quick comparison for clarity. In the main slav, the move order is as follows: @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.c4  c6  3.Nc3  Nf6  4.Bf4  @@StartBracket@@Let's just call it a viable move for the sake of the comparison@@EndBracket@@ In this scenario, Black is able to play  4...dxc4  and hold on to the pawn. As we can see, we do not have this issue in this case since our c4-pawn is protected. White will follow up with Nc3 and transpose into a version of Slav where ... dxc4 was never an option. }
4... Bf5
{ This is perhaps more likely to come in practice, but I think Black ends up in a worse position either way. }
5. Nc3 { Developing the queenside pieces and preparing for Qb3 next. } 5... Qb6
{ Is possible to avoid Qb3 ideas. } 6. Qd2
{ Protecting the b2-pawn.  6.Qb3  is also possible, but White’s idea is to go c5-b4 in the near future which makes the queen a bit misplaced. Black can respond with  6...Nbd7  7.c5  Qxb3  8.axb3  and  8…e5!  Breaking the center. This gives Black unnecessary chances. }
6... e6 7. c5
{ Gaining advantage of the early ...Qb6 as now Black is forced to retreat back to d8 and a couple of moves. }
7... Qd8 8. b4 Nbd7 9. Nf3
{ White has a fantastic position. The queenside play seems extremely dangerous, the b5 push seems inevitable and Black on the other hand seems to have no counterplay in return. I would recommend first putting the king to safety perhaps via h3-Bd3-O-O and only then aim to push b5. }
*

