{ Making space for the knight on f6 in view of g5. } 10. Bxc4 Nb6 11. Bb3
{ Key move. The bishop acts as a defender for any queenside threats like ...Qb4 and more importantly, prepares for the inevitable ...e5 push which will undoubtedly make the bishop stronger. These ideas are fairly common in the Slav, however, as mentioned a bit earlier - this is a far worse version of the Slav for Black.   11.Bd3  Might seem logical at first since the b1-h7 is the only 'open' diagonal in the position. However, in normal circumstances, this would be fine. In this case, Black has a tactical escape with the move  11...e5!  And now, White should be careful to not end up in trouble. }
