{ I would like to stop here for a moment and provide some clarity. This position can technically arise from two different openings: 1@@EndBracket@@ Queen's Gambit Declined @@StartBracket@@QGD@@EndBracket@@ and 2@@EndBracket@@ Slav.  In QGD, the move order is @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.c4  e6  3.Nf3  Nf6  4.Nc3  Nbd7  5.Bf4  c6  6.e3  . In Slav, the move order is @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.c4  c6  3.Nf3  Nf6  4.Nc3  e6  5.Bf4  Nbd7  6.e3  .  You will notice that in both cases, Black has opted for an inferior option in comparison to the mainline. In both cases, Black could have taken on c4 as soon as White played Bf4. Additionally, in the Slav Defence White usually plays 5. e3 @@StartBracket@@also known as Semi-Slav@@EndBracket@@ which after 5... Nbd7 is a typical position inside the Slav and is also identical to the position in front of you with one key difference - the Bishop is now active on f4.   This proves that although we have transposed into a Slav/QGD hybrid, White is in a much better version of them due to the active bishop and Black's unnecessary ...c6 push that only delays ...c5, which is what Black has to play at some stage if Black intends on getting any kind of activity.   Another side note: I would avoid taking on d5 unless absolutely necessary. This is because it opens up a diagonal for the c8-bishop, not to mention that it transposes into QGD Exchange that arises after  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.c4  e6  3.Nc3  Be7  4.cxd5  exd5  5.Bf4  Nf6  6.e3  c6  7.Nf3  Nbd7  . It is truly beautiful how one position can resemble so many openings. }
6... Be7 7. Bd3 O-O 8. O-O dxc4 { Black has to take at some point. } 9. Bxc4 b5
10. Bd3 Bb7
{ Development is complete. Black will now aim to push ...c5 as soon as possible. }
11. Ne5 { It's time for action. } 11... a6 12. Qf3 Qb6
{ Is another logical response. } 13. Ne4
{ Cleverly preparing for the ... c5 break. } 13... Nxe5 14. Bxe5 Nd7 15. Bd6
{ Further weakening the dark-squares. } 15... Bxd6 16. Nxd6 Ra7 17. Rac1
{ With a great position. Black is once again unable to play ...c5. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "7) Slav Defense"]
[Black "4...e6 with 5...Nbd7 #7"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 Nf6 3. e3
{ We are delaying the development of the f3-knight for two reasons:   1@@EndBracket@@ The knight may develop to e2 in some positions.   2@@EndBracket@@ Sometimes White purposefully delays developing the g1-knight to gain queenside play. }
3... c6
{ The Slav Approach. This particular move order makes little sense because White has not pushed c4 yet. I believe that it is more likely to expect The Slav Approach after  3...Bf5  4.c4  c6  , but we do not play  4.c4  in that position and this is why I decided to add this particular move order. I believe this to be a dubious move since Black is eliminating any chance of pushing ...c5, which is widely considered to be the best approach against the London. Secondly, this puts Black in a tough theoretical spot since the bishop on c8 will either be blocked by its own pawns forever or the bishop would need to come out early, which allows White to put lasting pressure along the b7-pawn. Either way, Black suffers. }
4. c4
{ Wasting no opportunity. It is worth noting that this is a far superior version of the Slav for White. Let's do a quick comparison for clarity. In the main slav, the move order is as follows: @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.c4  c6  3.Nc3  Nf6  4.Bf4  @@StartBracket@@Let's just call it a viable move for the sake of the comparison@@EndBracket@@ In this scenario, Black is able to play  4...dxc4  and hold on to the pawn. As we can see, we do not have this issue in this case since our c4-pawn is protected. White will follow up with Nc3 and transpose into a version of Slav where ... dxc4 was never an option. }
4... e6 5. Nc3
{ Mission accomplished. The bishop is now stuck behind its own pawns and Black will have problems with space as a result of this. }
5... Nbd7 6. Nf3
{ I would like to stop here for a moment and provide some clarity. This position can technically arise from two different openings: 1@@EndBracket@@ Queen's Gambit Declined @@StartBracket@@QGD@@EndBracket@@ and 2@@EndBracket@@ Slav.  In QGD, the move order is @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.c4  e6  3.Nf3  Nf6  4.Nc3  Nbd7  5.Bf4  c6  6.e3  . In Slav, the move order is @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.c4  c6  3.Nf3  Nf6  4.Nc3  e6  5.Bf4  Nbd7  6.e3  .  You will notice that in both cases, Black has opted for an inferior option in comparison to the mainline. In both cases, Black could have taken on c4 as soon as White played Bf4. Additionally, in the Slav Defence White usually plays 5. e3 @@StartBracket@@also known as Semi-Slav@@EndBracket@@ which after 5... Nbd7 is a typical position inside the Slav and is also identical to the position in front of you with one key difference - the Bishop is now active on f4.   This proves that although we have transposed into a Slav/QGD hybrid, White is in a much better version of them due to the active bishop and Black's unnecessary ...c6 push that only delays ...c5, which is what Black has to play at some stage if Black intends on getting any kind of activity.   Another side note: I would avoid taking on d5 unless absolutely necessary. This is because it opens up a diagonal for the c8-bishop, not to mention that it transposes into QGD Exchange that arises after  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.c4  e6  3.Nc3  Be7  4.cxd5  exd5  5.Bf4  Nf6  6.e3  c6  7.Nf3  Nbd7  . It is truly beautiful how one position can resemble so many openings. }
6... Be7 7. Bd3 O-O 8. O-O dxc4 { Black has to take at some point. } 9. Bxc4 b5
10. Bd3 Bb7
{ Development is complete. Black will now aim to push ...c5 as soon as possible. }
11. Ne5 { It's time for action. } 11... a6 12. Qf3 Qb6
{ Is another logical response. } 13. Ne4
{ Cleverly preparing for the ... c5 break. } 13... Nxe5 14. Bxe5 Nxe4 15. Bxe4
f5 { The only way to push ...c5 and gain some activity. } 16. Qg3 Rf7 17. Bf3
c5 { Mission accomplished, but it's too late. } 18. dxc5 Bxc5 19. Rfd1
{ And interestingly, the problem with the c6-pawn may have been solved, but it ended up creating a similar problem with the e6-pawn as well. Therefore, White still maintains a clear advantage in this position with little to no risk. }
