[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8) 1...d5 2.Bf4 Nf6 with 3...Bf5, 3...Bg4 and 3...c5"]
[Black "Introduction to 3...Bg4"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "rn1qkb1r/ppp1pppp/5n2/3p4/3P1Bb1/4P3/PPP2PPP/RN1QKBNR w KQkq - 0 4"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ This chapter consists of three different moves. 1@@EndBracket@@ 3... Bg4. 2@@EndBracket@@ 3... Bf5 and 3@@EndBracket@@ 3... c5.  The variation with 3... Bg4 seems a bit tricky at first. But the approach is quite simple and relatable to the chapter on Slav.   We will answer with @@StartFEN@@rn1qkb1r/ppp1pppp/5n2/3p4/3P1Bb1/4P3/PPP2PPP/RN1QKBNR w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Qd3!?  ,  immediately threatening to take the pawn with Qb5+. If this is stopped with  4...c6  ,  then the position looks quite familiar to Slav. The queen on d3 is not useless and will transfer to b3 to attack the undefended pawn on b7. As mentioned a bit earlier, Black is unable to defend this pawn with ...Qc7, leaving Black with the second-best option of going ...Qb6.   While this seems like it solves the problem, it is far from the case because we will continue the queenside play with c5!? forcing the exchange of the queens and in the long run, going for the b4-b5 breakthrough. Therefore, Black is forced to include ...dxc4 prior to playing ...Qb6, which gives up the center. White can recapture with the f1-bishop, develop with Nge2 and simply castle. }
4. -- *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8) 1...d5 2.Bf4 Nf6 with 3...Bf5, 3...Bg4 and 3...c5"]
[Black "3...Bg4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 Nf6 3. e3
{ We are delaying the development of the f3-knight for two reasons:   1@@EndBracket@@ The knight may develop to e2 in some positions.   2@@EndBracket@@ Sometimes White purposefully delays developing the g1-knight to gain queenside play. }
3... Bg4
{ This move doesn't seem as dangerous, but it can be a pain if White does not know what to do. During the Boardwalk Pearson event in 2018, GM Sergey Kasparov employed this against me and I was completely clueless. I managed to get into a worse position shortly after. I think the idea if fairly simple, and the player just needs to be aware of it. }
4. Qd3
{ Extremely important. White aims to reroute the queen to either b3 or b5 to attack the b7-pawn. In this position, two moves make sense -  4...c6  and  4...e6  . }
4... e6 { The bold response. Black is not afraid of losing the pawn on b7. } 5.
Qb5+ Nbd7 6. Qxb7 Rb8 7. Qxa7
{ And now if Black wants to have any kind of compensation, Black needs a breakthrough immediately. }
7... Rxb2
{ Threatening ...Bb4+ ideas. Therefore, White must create space for the king immediately. }
8. f3 e5 { 8...Bf5??  is just losing after  9.Bxc7+- } 9. Bxe5 Bf5
{ Goes into a complicated yet forcing line that ends in a better position for White. }
10. Bxc7 Qe7 11. Kf2 { Protecting e3. } 11... Bxc2
{ 11...Rxc2+?  12.Ne2  is just winning. } 12. Be2 Bxb1 13. Qa8+ Nb8 14. Bxb8
Qd8 15. Qa4+ Qd7 16. Qxd7+ Kxd7 17. Be5
{ And White is two pawns up at the moment but will be a pawn up regardless. White should try to develop the g1-knight soon and activate the h1-rook. }
*

