[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8) 1...d5 2.Bf4 Nf6 with 3...Bf5, 3...Bg4 and 3...c5"]
[Black "3...Bg4 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 Nf6 3. e3
{ We are delaying the development of the f3-knight for two reasons:   1@@EndBracket@@ The knight may develop to e2 in some positions.   2@@EndBracket@@ Sometimes White purposefully delays developing the g1-knight to gain queenside play. }
3... Bg4
{ This move doesn't seem as dangerous, but it can be a pain if White does not know what to do. During the Boardwalk Pearson event in 2018, GM Sergey Kasparov employed this against me and I was completely clueless. I managed to get into a worse position shortly after. I think the idea if fairly simple, and the player just needs to be aware of it. }
4. Qd3
{ Extremely important. White aims to reroute the queen to either b3 or b5 to attack the b7-pawn. In this position, two moves make sense -  4...c6  and  4...e6  . }
4... c6 { The not so bold response. } 5. h3
{ It's always good to insert this move when possible since in the future White may have plans of going g4-h4, not to mention that if White were to ever castle on the kingside then backrank would not be an issue. }
5... Bh5 6. Qb3 Qb6 7. c4 dxc4
{ 7...e6  We have seen this in the past. White will get a much better endgame after  8.c5  Qxb3  9.axb3  and b4-b5 cannot be stopped. Another benefit is that since we have not committed Nc3, we can instead go for Nd2-Nb3-Na5 to put pressure on the b7-pawn. }
8. Bxc4 e6 9. Nc3 Nbd7 10. Nge2
{ The point. The long-term idea is to play f3-e4 and to completely restrict the g6-bishop from the position. }
10... Be7 11. f3 Bg6 12. e4 O-O 13. h4 h5 14. Rd1
{ And White has domination in the center, and has successfully restricted the g6-bishop from being in the game. This type of position is quite similar to the one in the @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pp2pppp/2p2n2/3p4/2PP4/2N2N2/PP2PPPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 3 4@@EndFEN@@  4...dxc4  Slav where after  5.a4  Bf5  6.Ne5  Nbd7  7.Nxc4  Nb6  8.Ne5  a5  9.f3!?  and white pushes for e4 eventually to restrict the bishop. You could theoretically get a very similar position from that to here, provided that everything has gone horribly wrong for Black. }
