[FEN "rn1qkb1r/ppp1pppp/5n2/3p1b2/3P1B2/4P3/PPP2PPP/RN1QKBNR w KQkq - 0 4"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ In this variation, naturally - I spent a long time analyzing the move 4. c4 to keep the ideas aligned, but I was not completely satisfied with the results. Therefore, I decided to go with an interesting idea of 4. Bd3!?.   This move forces Black to make a decision of whether to take the bishop or retreat with ...Bg6. If Black goes for ...Bg6, then White continues normal development with Nf3 and O-O. Once the development is complete, White should take Bxg6 to create a hook on g6. This is important because in the long run, White can always keep the idea of going h4-h5 or h4-Ng5 which puts lasting pressure on the kingside.   Furthermore, with ...hxg6, the move Ne5 seems even stronger since Black will not be able to kick the knight with ...f6 due to the g6-pawn left hanging. If Black takes the bishop on d3, then we will respond with the tricky cxd3!? This move gives White an extremely pleasant position for several reasons.   • Firstly, the outpost on e4 is always protected.   • Secondly, White gets a semi-open c-file which is useful to put pressure on the c7-pawn.   • Thirdly, removing the c2-pawn allows White to play Qb3 quickly and lastly, the breakthrough of ...c5 or ... e5 does not do much since White can simply capture and push the d-pawn, making the breakthrough a bit pointless. }
4. -- *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8) 1...d5 2.Bf4 Nf6 with 3...Bf5, 3...Bg4 and 3...c5"]
[Black "3...Bf5 with 4...e6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 Nf6 3. e3
{ We are delaying the development of the f3-knight for two reasons:   1@@EndBracket@@ The knight may develop to e2 in some positions.   2@@EndBracket@@ Sometimes White purposefully delays developing the g1-knight to gain queenside play. }
3... Bf5
{ The idea behind this move is similar to  3...Bg4  .  Black intends to get the bishop out before playing ...e6. Another important note is that unlike the line with 3... c6, Black has smartly kept the pawn on c7 to push ...c5 once the development is complete.  For a long time, I tried to make @@StartFEN@@rn1qkb1r/ppp1pppp/5n2/3p1b2/3P1B2/4P3/PPP2PPP/RN1QKBNR w KQkq - 1 4@@EndFEN@@  4.c4  work here but I did not like the lines with  4...e6  5.Nc3  Bb4!?  and even though this is played regularly at the top level, I believe I have found something much better. }
4. Bd3
{ The solid approach. White offers the trade of the light square bishops. }
4... e6 { This is another way to go. } 5. Bxf5 exf5 6. Ne2
{ Key move. The knight on e2 is superior in comparison to f3. The reason is that once Black plays ...Bd6 we don't really have to move the bishop since we can recapture with the knight. }
6... Bd6 { Seems most logical. } 7. Qd3
{ Clever move. We attack the f5-pawn immediately since Black cannot play ...Qd7 because of Bxd6. }
7... Bxf4 { 7...g6?  blunders the pawn to  8.Qb5++- } 8. Nxf4 Qd7
{ Controlling both f5 and b5. } 9. c4
{ Putting immediate pressure on the d5-pawn. } 9... Nc6
{ This is a smart move aimed against  10.Nc3  since Black now has  10...Nb4!  followed by capture on c4. }
10. Nd2 { Protecting the c4-pawn. } 10... O-O 11. Rc1
{ Getting the rook in action. We can delay castling for now. } 11... Ne7 12. c5
{ Denying any simplifications and preparing for Nf3-Ne5 ideas. } 12... Ne4
{ Is another important move. Black wants to start a kingside attack via ...g5. Although it isn't threatening - seems unnecessary to allow and can simply be stopped by playing }
13. Nf3 g5 { Is not effective in this case. } 14. Ne2
{ Followed by h4 next and it is Black who should be careful to not allow kingside attack via the h-file. }
