[White "8) 1...d5 2.Bf4 Nf6 with 3...Bf5, 3...Bg4 and 3...c5"]
[Black "3...Bf5 with 4...Bg6 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 Nf6 3. e3
{ We are delaying the development of the f3-knight for two reasons:   1@@EndBracket@@ The knight may develop to e2 in some positions.   2@@EndBracket@@ Sometimes White purposefully delays developing the g1-knight to gain queenside play. }
3... Bf5
{ The idea behind this move is similar to  3...Bg4  .  Black intends to get the bishop out before playing ...e6. Another important note is that unlike the line with 3... c6, Black has smartly kept the pawn on c7 to push ...c5 once the development is complete.  For a long time, I tried to make @@StartFEN@@rn1qkb1r/ppp1pppp/5n2/3p1b2/3P1B2/4P3/PPP2PPP/RN1QKBNR w KQkq - 1 4@@EndFEN@@  4.c4  work here but I did not like the lines with  4...e6  5.Nc3  Bb4!?  and even though this is played regularly at the top level, I believe I have found something much better. }
4. Bd3
{ The solid approach. White offers the trade of the light square bishops. }
4... Bg6 { The quiet retreat. } 5. Nf3 e6
{ Makes the most sense.  5...Nbd7  6.O-O  e6  7.c4  transposes to the mainline. }
6. O-O { Castling is complete, we will now aim for c4 next. } 6... Nbd7
{ Is also possible. If we do not act quickly, Black will break with ...c5 and the queenside play will somewhat disappear. }
7. c4 dxc4
{ 7...c6  We have already seen this position when Black pushes ...c6, we can safely take the bishop.  8.Bxg6  hxg6  9.Nbd2⩲  With a good position for White. }
8. Bxc4 Bd6 9. Ne5 { No exchanges! } 9... O-O 10. h3
{ Creating a space for the bishop on h2. The follow-up should be to go Nc3-Qb3-a4. }
10... Bh5
{ Smart move, otherwise Black isn't able to play ...c6 because of Nxg6. } 11.
Qb3 Nb6 12. Nc3
{ The nature of the position is somewhat closed, so we should not be afraid of exchanging a bishop for a knight since the knight performs better in closed positions. }
12... a5 13. a4
{ Whenever we push a4-a5 in these types of structures, we should be careful to now allow ...Nd5-Nb4. This is a common idea in Slav positions and Black is generally quite comfortable once the knight reaches the outpost since White's pressure on the queenside is blocked. }
13... Nxc4 { Is somewhat logical, but it does not work in this case. } 14. Qxc4
c6 { We will not allow ...Nd5 anymore. } 15. e4
{ And now Black's knight is sad on f6. Without any ...Nb4, the position is pure suffering. One might wonder, why not place the bishop on b4 instead? Well, the reason is that we can always kick that bishop with Na2 ideas, so it isn't really an 'outpost'. }
