[Black "3...Bf5 with 4...Bg6 #9"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 Nf6 3. e3
{ We are delaying the development of the f3-knight for two reasons:   1@@EndBracket@@ The knight may develop to e2 in some positions.   2@@EndBracket@@ Sometimes White purposefully delays developing the g1-knight to gain queenside play. }
3... Bf5
{ The idea behind this move is similar to  3...Bg4  .  Black intends to get the bishop out before playing ...e6. Another important note is that unlike the line with 3... c6, Black has smartly kept the pawn on c7 to push ...c5 once the development is complete.  For a long time, I tried to make @@StartFEN@@rn1qkb1r/ppp1pppp/5n2/3p1b2/3P1B2/4P3/PPP2PPP/RN1QKBNR w KQkq - 1 4@@EndFEN@@  4.c4  work here but I did not like the lines with  4...e6  5.Nc3  Bb4!?  and even though this is played regularly at the top level, I believe I have found something much better. }
4. Bd3
{ The solid approach. White offers the trade of the light square bishops. }
4... Bg6 { The quiet retreat. } 5. Nf3 e6
{ Makes the most sense.  5...Nbd7  6.O-O  e6  7.c4  transposes to the mainline. }
6. O-O { Castling is complete, we will now aim for c4 next. } 6... Bd6
{ Black has committed ...Bd6, which means if now ...c5 was played Black would lose a tempo. Therefore, we can exchange safely on g6. }
7. Bxg6 hxg6 8. Nbd2 O-O
{ Perhaps the most logical move. Generally speaking,  9.c4  is the main idea in this position. But, Black can potentially play  9...Bxf4  10.exf4  dxc4  and the pawn structure seems a bit awkward. Therefore, I will suggest a different idea here. }
9. c3 { Keeping the tension. } 9... Nbd7 10. h4 { Generating kingside play. }
10... Rc8 11. g3 Bxf4 12. exf4 c5 13. Re1
{ Making sure that after  13...cxd4  14.Nxd4  there is no  14...e5  to open up the position. }
13... Qb6 14. Qb3
{ With a slow game ahead. White's plan should be to go Kg2-Ne5 in the near future. In long term, I would advise the reader to try and create imbalances in the position whenever possible. For example, after ...cxd4 we should be taking with the knight, not the pawn.   Another example is if Black takes on b3, we should recapture with the pawn, not the knight. Imbalances are your friend in these positions since the advantage is extremely positional and by creating imbalances we avoid getting into positions where a fortress can be formed. }
