[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8) 1...d5 2.Bf4 Nf6 with 3...Bf5, 3...Bg4 and 3...c5"]
[Black "3...Bf5 with 4...Bxd3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 Nf6 3. e3
{ We are delaying the development of the f3-knight for two reasons:   1@@EndBracket@@ The knight may develop to e2 in some positions.   2@@EndBracket@@ Sometimes White purposefully delays developing the g1-knight to gain queenside play. }
3... Bf5
{ The idea behind this move is similar to  3...Bg4  .  Black intends to get the bishop out before playing ...e6. Another important note is that unlike the line with 3... c6, Black has smartly kept the pawn on c7 to push ...c5 once the development is complete.  For a long time, I tried to make @@StartFEN@@rn1qkb1r/ppp1pppp/5n2/3p1b2/3P1B2/4P3/PPP2PPP/RN1QKBNR w KQkq - 1 4@@EndFEN@@  4.c4  work here but I did not like the lines with  4...e6  5.Nc3  Bb4!?  and even though this is played regularly at the top level, I believe I have found something much better. }
4. Bd3
{ The solid approach. White offers the trade of the light square bishops. }
4... Bxd3
{ The most popular response, and rightfully so. This is where we include the sideline which works really well for White. }
5. cxd3
{ The point. Doubled-pawns are generally considered to be bad, but that is usually not the case. It is 'isolated doubled-pawns' which is the real issue. In this case, capturing with the c-pawn opens up a file for White which can be used to put pressure on the c7-pawn. Furthermore, moves like ...c5 don't seem as dangerous since we have an extra pawn on the d-file. Lastly, the pawn on d3 makes sure that Black will never be able to play ...Ne4 and we will be going for the e3-e4 break when the time is right! }
5... c6 6. Nc3 Qb6
{ This is the only real difference between ...c6 and ...e6. But it does not really affect us.  6...e6  7.Nf3  transposes to 5... e6. }
7. Rb1 { Protecting the b2-pawn. } 7... e6 8. Nf3
{ The queen on b6 is now misplaced. As a result of this, Black is unable to play ...Bd6 anymore. }
8... Be7
{ 8...Nh5  can be answered with  9.Bg5!⩲  with the idea of breaking with e4 next. }
9. O-O O-O 10. e4
{ There aren't many games in this position. So it is important to understand White's next few moves, and I promise the dynamic players will enjoy this. The idea is to block the center with e5 next and continue to attack on the kingside London Style with h4-h5-h6, creating problems along the dark squares. If Black were to respond with ...h6 instead, we can go even more aggressive with g4-g5. It may not seem like it, but Black should be very careful in a position like this. }
10... c5
{ Most logical response. When facing a potential flank attack, break the center.  10...Nbd7?  will just allow  11.e5  Ne8  12.h4±  and White carries the attack as mentioned earlier. }
11. Na4 Qb5 12. Nxc5 b6
{ Only move.  12...Bxc5?  13.dxc5  Qxc5  14.Rc1±  This is clearly better for White, since the dark squares are left unprotected. }
13. Bg5 bxc5 14. e5 Nbd7 { Logical. } 15. exf6 Bxf6 16. Bxf6 Nxf6 17. a4
{ Gaining space on the queenside before taking on c5. } 17... Qb6 18. dxc5 Qxc5
19. b4 Qd6 20. b5
{ Once again, we have a substantial positional advantage. White's next few moves could be Qb3-Rfc1 and try to go for Nd4 at some stage. It would be wise to throw g3 at some stage to not allow any activity with ...Qf4. If executed correctly, I think White will come out on top. }
*

