{ Black ignores the theat of Qb3 and continue with the development. } 7. Qb3 b6
{ Has been tried a few times. } 8. Bxd6 Qxd6 9. Nf3 O-O 10. O-O Nc6
{ This seems a bit strange, but it has been tried in the past.  10...c5  11.e4  transposes to the mainline. }
11. Rac1 a6 { Preventing Nb5 ideas. } 12. Na4
{ A fairly common idea that is often applied in theory. White places the knight on a4 and holds the pawn on b6 as a hostage since ...b5 will be giving away an outpost on c5. }
12... Rac8 13. Qc3 Ne7 14. b4
{ Preventing ...c5. Once again - if Black is unable to play ...c5 or ...e5 in this position, Black will remain slightly worse. }
14... Nd7 15. Rc2 h6 16. Rfc1 Rfd8 17. Qb3
{ With fantastic play. The point of cxd3 is accomplished. White has domination over the c-file and can now think of creating kingside play, perhaps via h4-g3-Kg2. Black's position is 'planless', therefore, White does not need to rush. }
