[Black "Introduction to 3...c5"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "rnbqkb1r/pp2pppp/5n2/2pp4/3P1B2/4P3/PPP2PPP/RN1QKBNR w KQkq - 0 4"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ This variation will largely transpose into other chapters. For example, after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pp2pppp/5n2/2pp4/3P1B2/4P3/PPP2PPP/RN1QKBNR w KQkq c6 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Nf3  Nc6  5.Nbd2  transposes to Chapters 1-5. Another transposition comes after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pp2pppp/5n2/2pp4/3P1B2/4P3/PPP2PPP/RN1QKBNR w KQkq c6 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Nf3  e6  5.Nbd2  which is discussed in Chapter 10. Therefore, this variation is only considers options that do not transpose into other chapters.   This is only possible if after 4. Nf3 Black goes 4... Qb6. This position might seem familiar since it is still very likely to transpose into Chapters 1 & 2 should Black commit ...Nc6, which is the best response. This variation is unlikely to come up in a practical game, but important regardless. We will sacrifice the b2-pawn just like in the first two chapters and continue with Rb1-Bb5-Ne5-c4 ideas to break the center.   The question then becomes, why is it superior to Chapters 1 & 2? Well, let's look at the move order: @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pp2pppp/5n2/2pp4/3P1B2/4PN2/PPP2PPP/RN1QKB1R b KQkq - 1 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Qb6  5.Nbd2  Qxb2  6.Rb1  Qc3  7.Bb5+  .  The arising position demonstrates a key difference between the first two chapters and this position. White has not committed dxc5. This move not only saves a crucial tempo in a dynamic position but also keeps the center in our control, which makes the breakthrough of Ne5-c4 all the more dangerous. }
4. -- *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8) 1...d5 2.Bf4 Nf6 with 3...Bf5, 3...Bg4 and 3...c5"]
[Black "3...c5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 Nf6 3. e3
{ We are delaying the development of the f3-knight for two reasons:   1@@EndBracket@@ The knight may develop to e2 in some positions.   2@@EndBracket@@ Sometimes White purposefully delays developing the g1-knight to gain queenside play. }
3... c5
{ This move order will eventually transpose once Black commits ...Nc6. Therefore, we can continue in the same fashion. }
4. Nf3 Qb6
{ 4...Nc6  5.Nbd2  transposes to 2... c5 Chapter.  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pp2pppp/5n2/2pp4/3P1B2/4PN2/PPP2PPP/RN1QKB1R b KQkq - 1 4@@EndFEN@@  4...e6  5.Nbd2  transposes to the variation with 3...e6. }
5. Nbd2 { Keeping in line with the theme of our repertoire. } 5... Qxb2
{ 5...e6  6.Rb1  transposes to 3...e6 move order.  @@StartFEN@@rnb1kb1r/pp2pppp/1q3n2/2pp4/3P1B2/4PN2/PPPN1PPP/R2QKB1R b KQkq - 3 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Nc6  6.dxc5  will  transpose to the 2...c5 Chapter. }
6. Rb1
{ This setup can @@StartBracket@@and should@@EndBracket@@ be compared to the 6... Qxb2 variation in 2... c5 chapter. This is by far a worse version of that variation and in quite a number of lines would directly transpose once Black plays ... Nc6. The one key difference I can understand between these two cases is that White has not committed dxc5, which allows White to have other ideas in the position that could be better. I will explain this further shortly. }
6... Qa3
{ Perhaps this is a good moment to understand the difference. In this case, since White has not committed dxc5, there is an additional @@StartBracket@@perhaps even better@@EndBracket@@ option. }
7. c4 { Breaking the center immediately. } 7... e6 8. cxd5 exd5 9. e4
{ Breaking the center once again! } 9... c4 10. exd5 Nxd5 11. Nxc4 Bb4+
{ Forced, since otherwise, Black loses the queen. } 12. Nfd2 Bxd2+ 13. Bxd2
{ Preserving the London bishop. } 13... Qe7+ 14. Ne3
{ With a great position. White can simply develop now via Be2-O-O and eventually activate the light-squared bishop via Bf3 and push d5 at the right moment if needed. }
*

[Event "?"]
