{ 16...Ba6?!  will allow  17.axb5  Nxf4  18.Qxf4  Bxb5  19.Nxc4⩲  White just seems to be a pawn up for no compensation. }
17. Nxc4 Ba6
{ Most precise. Defending the pawn with  17...Nc5?  is of course bad because of  18.Be3!  Nxe3  19.Qxe3  Qc7  20.Nd6  with the idea of Rh4 next to bring the rook into play, the a4-pawn will soon fall. }
18. Rxa4 Bb5 19. Ra1 Qb8 20. Bc1
{ Denying ...Nxf4 and protecting the b2-pawn. The position remains complicated, and experienced players will tend to play better in such situations. White still has an extra pawn for now. One small tip to remember: Do not try to simplify the position unless you are sure the resulting position is better. }
20... Bxc4 21. Bxc4 Nxe5 22. Be2
{ I would choose  22.Be2  over  22.Bxd5  in this position. But this decision is rather personal if you feel more comfortable with  22.Bxd5  , by all means, go for it! }
