8. Bd3
{ Developing the bishop. Once this move is played, we should expect the b8-knight into action in the next move. It is obvious that the knight will either go to ...c6 or ...d7. The difference is not huge, but it is still important for a full understanding of the position. I will explain this in point-by-point format.  1@@EndBracket@@ Both knights @@StartBracket@@on c6 and d7@@EndBracket@@ will get taken eventually by the e5-knight. Therefore, in some variations, the knight on d7 takes preference since capturing with ...bxc6 breaks the pawn structure and ...Qxc6 allows for a tempo with Ne5! The knight on d7, on the other hand, usually can be recapture with ...Bxd7 which saves Black this trouble.   2@@EndBracket@@ The idea of ...b6-Bb7 is normal to play in both situations. The knight on c6 once again is inferior since Nxc6 will have to be recaptured by the queen and lose a tempo.   3@@EndBracket@@ The benefit of placing the knight on ...c6 seems to be that the knight can @@StartBracket@@and should@@EndBracket@@ maneuver to ...e7 as quickly as possible, with ...b6-Bb7-Ne4-f6 to follow. Another advantage is that when the knight is on ...c6, there are ideas with ...Ng4! possible. This is not the case with the knight on d7 since Nxd7 attacks the rook on f8 @@StartBracket@@this will be mentioned in one of the lines for clarity@@EndBracket@@.   Now that we know the ideas behind them, let's take a look at our approach against both:   A@@EndBracket@@ Against ...Nbd7 structures, play Ndf3 to protect the e5-knight. If Black does not do anything even for a move @@StartBracket@@i,e does not play ...Ne4@@EndBracket@@ then go for g4-g5! This will provoke ...Ne4, and stop the idea of ...f6. Eventually, try to take the knight on d7 and put your other knight on e5. However, if your opponent does play ... Ne4 immediately, then castle and wait for your opponent to develop with ... b6-Bb7. Once this is done, take the knight on d7, place the other knight on e5 and kick the e4-knight with f3!   B@@EndBracket@@ Against ...Nc6 structures, play Ndf3 once again to protect e5. If Black does not do anything, go for h4-h5 or h4-Ng5 ideas. The reason why g4-g5 does not work is that Black's knight has an extra square to run to @@StartBracket@@d7@@EndBracket@@. If Black does play ...Ne4, then castle and wait for Black to push ...b6 and take Nxc6 immediately @@StartBracket@@note that we are not waiting for ...Bb7 in this case@@EndBracket@@ and force Black to recapture with ...Qxc6 then go for Ne5 followed by f3 once again to kick the knight. }
8... Nbd7 9. Ndf3 Ne4
{ The most popular move. The idea of g4-g5 makes little sense now since Black can push ...f6 instantly. So, we will simply castle instead. }
10. O-O f6
{ Falls into a trap. It is worth noting that this is the most popular move in this position, out of possible 9 games, 8 players opted for this move  @@StartBracket@@!@@EndBracket@@ }
11. Nxd7 Bxd7 12. Bxe4 dxe4 13. Bxd6 Qxd6 14. dxc5
{ The d7-bishop is now hanging, and White wins a pawn for free. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "9) 1...d5 2.Bf4 Nf6 with 3...e6 and 4...Bd6"]
[Black "5...O-O with 7...Qc7 #8"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 Nf6 3. e3
{ We are delaying the development of the f3-knight for two reasons:   1@@EndBracket@@ The knight may develop to e2 in some positions.   2@@EndBracket@@ Sometimes White purposefully delays developing the g1-knight to gain queenside play. }
3... e6
{ Black keeps the bishop on c8. This is the classical response against London. Black's idea is to play ...Bd6-c5-Nc6-O-O, as you may have already realized: the move order can change! }
4. Nf3
{ The most popular move. This move order is key to remember since we have a surprise waiting after  4...Bd6 }
4... Bd6 5. Ne5
{ The fight is on. White denies the exchange of the dark-squared bishop and prepares for a potential kingside attack after Black inevitably castles.   5.Bg3  This is something to avoid. The reason is that after  5...O-O  6.Nbd2  c5  7.c3  Black can delay the development of the b8-knight and simply go  7...Qc7  and after  8.Bd3  Black smartly places the knight to  8...Nbd7  And this position is identical to the mainline with one key difference. The knight is now on d7 instead of c6. This means that we cannot play dxc5 anymore and are more or less forced to play  9.O-O  After which Black has  9...e5!=  which equalizes the position. }
5... O-O
{ It is worth noting that  5...c5  is not possible in this case because of  6.Bb5+!±  And Black is forced to break castling to avoid material loss. }
6. Nd2 c5
{ 6...Nbd7  is just wrong, because after  7.Bd3⩲  Black is unable to push ...c5 in view of Nxf7. }
7. c3
{ We have reached the first main position of this repertoire. The idea for White is to create kingside play via h4-h5-Bd3-Qf3-Qg3. This setup has become quite popular amongst top players since 2020. Some of them include Tabatabei, Demchenko, Caruana, Alireza, and of course the legend himself, Kamsky. }
7... Qc7
{ This move is a bit more flexible than  7...Nc6  since the knight can also develop to d7. I will explain the differences between these two in the next move. }
8. Bd3
{ Developing the bishop. Once this move is played, we should expect the b8-knight into action in the next move. It is obvious that the knight will either go to ...c6 or ...d7. The difference is not huge, but it is still important for a full understanding of the position. I will explain this in point-by-point format.  1@@EndBracket@@ Both knights @@StartBracket@@on c6 and d7@@EndBracket@@ will get taken eventually by the e5-knight. Therefore, in some variations, the knight on d7 takes preference since capturing with ...bxc6 breaks the pawn structure and ...Qxc6 allows for a tempo with Ne5! The knight on d7, on the other hand, usually can be recapture with ...Bxd7 which saves Black this trouble.   2@@EndBracket@@ The idea of ...b6-Bb7 is normal to play in both situations. The knight on c6 once again is inferior since Nxc6 will have to be recaptured by the queen and lose a tempo.   3@@EndBracket@@ The benefit of placing the knight on ...c6 seems to be that the knight can @@StartBracket@@and should@@EndBracket@@ maneuver to ...e7 as quickly as possible, with ...b6-Bb7-Ne4-f6 to follow. Another advantage is that when the knight is on ...c6, there are ideas with ...Ng4! possible. This is not the case with the knight on d7 since Nxd7 attacks the rook on f8 @@StartBracket@@this will be mentioned in one of the lines for clarity@@EndBracket@@.   Now that we know the ideas behind them, let's take a look at our approach against both:   A@@EndBracket@@ Against ...Nbd7 structures, play Ndf3 to protect the e5-knight. If Black does not do anything even for a move @@StartBracket@@i,e does not play ...Ne4@@EndBracket@@ then go for g4-g5! This will provoke ...Ne4, and stop the idea of ...f6. Eventually, try to take the knight on d7 and put your other knight on e5. However, if your opponent does play ... Ne4 immediately, then castle and wait for your opponent to develop with ... b6-Bb7. Once this is done, take the knight on d7, place the other knight on e5 and kick the e4-knight with f3!   B@@EndBracket@@ Against ...Nc6 structures, play Ndf3 once again to protect e5. If Black does not do anything, go for h4-h5 or h4-Ng5 ideas. The reason why g4-g5 does not work is that Black's knight has an extra square to run to @@StartBracket@@d7@@EndBracket@@. If Black does play ...Ne4, then castle and wait for Black to push ...b6 and take Nxc6 immediately @@StartBracket@@note that we are not waiting for ...Bb7 in this case@@EndBracket@@ and force Black to recapture with ...Qxc6 then go for Ne5 followed by f3 once again to kick the knight. }
8... Nbd7 9. Ndf3 Ne4
{ The most popular move. The idea of g4-g5 makes little sense now since Black can push ...f6 instantly. So, we will simply castle instead. }
10. O-O b6 11. Rc1
{ Simple developing move, we should now keep the threat of c3-c4 in mind. }
11... f6 { Once again lands in a bad position. } 12. Nxd7 Bxd7 13. Bxe4 dxe4
14. Bxd6 Qxd6 15. dxc5
{ And even though the pawn can be recaptured by the b6-pawn. The queen is still overloaded! }
15... Qc6 16. Nd2 bxc5 17. Nxe4 { Once again, White is a pawn up for nothing. }
*

