8. Bd3
{ Developing the bishop. Once this move is played, we should expect the b8-knight into action in the next move. It is obvious that the knight will either go to ...c6 or ...d7. The difference is not huge, but it is still important for a full understanding of the position. I will explain this in point-by-point format.  1@@EndBracket@@ Both knights @@StartBracket@@on c6 and d7@@EndBracket@@ will get taken eventually by the e5-knight. Therefore, in some variations, the knight on d7 takes preference since capturing with ...bxc6 breaks the pawn structure and ...Qxc6 allows for a tempo with Ne5! The knight on d7, on the other hand, usually can be recapture with ...Bxd7 which saves Black this trouble.   2@@EndBracket@@ The idea of ...b6-Bb7 is normal to play in both situations. The knight on c6 once again is inferior since Nxc6 will have to be recaptured by the queen and lose a tempo.   3@@EndBracket@@ The benefit of placing the knight on ...c6 seems to be that the knight can @@StartBracket@@and should@@EndBracket@@ maneuver to ...e7 as quickly as possible, with ...b6-Bb7-Ne4-f6 to follow. Another advantage is that when the knight is on ...c6, there are ideas with ...Ng4! possible. This is not the case with the knight on d7 since Nxd7 attacks the rook on f8 @@StartBracket@@this will be mentioned in one of the lines for clarity@@EndBracket@@.   Now that we know the ideas behind them, let's take a look at our approach against both:   A@@EndBracket@@ Against ...Nbd7 structures, play Ndf3 to protect the e5-knight. If Black does not do anything even for a move @@StartBracket@@i,e does not play ...Ne4@@EndBracket@@ then go for g4-g5! This will provoke ...Ne4, and stop the idea of ...f6. Eventually, try to take the knight on d7 and put your other knight on e5. However, if your opponent does play ... Ne4 immediately, then castle and wait for your opponent to develop with ... b6-Bb7. Once this is done, take the knight on d7, place the other knight on e5 and kick the e4-knight with f