[White "10) London Mainline"]
[Black "Introduction to 5...Bd6 (Without Nc6)"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "rnbqk2r/pp3ppp/3bpn2/2pp4/3P1B2/4PN2/PPPN1PPP/R2QKB1R w KQkq - 0 6"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ In this chapter, I will be discussing the mainline of the London. But before I do that, let's discuss a slight deviation first. As explained in the previous chapter, the move @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/pp3ppp/3bpn2/2pp4/3P1B2/4PN2/PPPN1PPP/R2QKB1R w KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Bg3  is not as accurate since Black develops the knight on d7 and gets the e5-break. Therefore, we need a different approach.   I have recommended the move  @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/pp3ppp/3bpn2/2pp4/3P1B2/4PN2/PPPN1PPP/R2QKB1R w KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Bb5+!?  in this position with the idea of 7. dxc5 and 8. c4. One might wonder, what is the point of including Bb5+? Well, in as you will see in some of the variations, including 6. Bb5+ allows White to damage Black's queenside structure with Bxc6-bxc6 and in the long run, the c6-pawn becomes a target. For example, after  6.Bb5+  Nc6  7.dxc5  Bxc5  8.c4  ,  White has the idea of going a3-b4-Bxc6-c5! and this inevitably fixes a weakness on c6, which can be exploited in the long run via Ne5 or Nd4 and Qa4 ideas. }
