[Black "5...Bd6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 Nf6 3. e3
{ We are delaying the development of the f3-knight for two reasons:   1@@EndBracket@@ The knight may develop to e2 in some positions.   2@@EndBracket@@ Sometimes White purposefully delays developing the g1-knight to gain queenside play. }
3... e6
{ Black keeps the bishop on c8. This is the classical response against London. Black's idea is to play ...Bd6-c5-Nc6-O-O, as you may have already realized: the move order can change! }
4. Nf3
{ The most popular move. This move order is key to remember since we have a surprise waiting after  4...Bd6 }
4... c5 5. Nbd2
{ Another important move order to remember. We will postpone c3 for a move or two since in some cases White can go for c2-c4 ideas and would not lose a tempo.   5.c3  I have mentioned this before, but it needs to be repeated since it is quite important. This move order allows Black to play  5...Bd6  6.Bg3  O-O  7.Nbd2  Qc7  8.Bd3  Where Black can develop the knight via  8...Nbd7=  and go for ...e5 next. }
5... Bd6
{ In this variation, the reader will understand why we delayed c3 further. } 6.
Bb5+ { Provoking ...Nc6. } 6... Nc6 7. dxc5 Bxc5 8. O-O O-O 9. c4
{ The point. Firstly, since White was going to play c4, c3 is a waste of time and secondly, it was important to include Bb5-Nc6 because in some cases White takes on c6 to put pressure on the pawn. }
9... e5 { The active response. } 10. Bg3
{ We will retreat for now and put pressure on the e5-pawn. } 10... e4
{ Only move. } 11. cxd5 Nb4
{ 11...exf3?!  would allow  12.dxc6  fxg2  13.Kxg2  Qb6  14.Ba4  bxc6  15.Nc4⩲  Followed by Ne5 next and the c6-pawn is lost. }
12. Ne5 Qe7
{ Only move yet again.  12...Nbxd5  is a bit too early.  13.Qc2  Attacking c5 and e3 at once.  13...Bxe3  Otherwise Black loses the pawn for free.  14.Nxe4  Bf4  15.Rfe1⩲  With a slightly better position due to active pieces. }
13. a3 Nbxd5 14. Nxe4 Nxe4 15. Qxd5 Nxg3 16. hxg3 Rd8 17. Qe4
{ White is technically a pawn up, but Black's double bishops and slightly more active pieces should suffice for equality. But playing this in a game is another thing! }
*

