[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "10) London Mainline"]
[Black "Introduction to 5...Qb6"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "rnb1kb1r/pp3ppp/1q2pn2/2pp4/3P1B2/4PN2/PPPN1PPP/R2QKB1R w KQkq - 0 6"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ This is an interesting move order. Black's plan is to insert ... Qb6 before playing ...Bd6 so that we cannot play Bb5+ anymore. In this case, we can simply defend the b2-pawn by going Rb1 and once Black goes ...Bd6, we will capture the c5-pawn and aim for a queenside expansion via b4-c4. Once this is done, White can complete the development on the kingside via Be2 and O-O.   Besides ...Bd6, Black has another interesting idea of ...cxd4 and ...Bd7 with the idea of ...Bb5. While it is not possible to avoid the trade of the light-squared bishops, we can use this time to gain space on the kingside via h4-h5, provoking ...h6. The pawn on h5 will then become an important resource that keeps the tension on the kingside, creating ideas like Rh3-Rg3 in the future. }
6. -- *

