[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "10) London Mainline"]
[Black "5...Qb6 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 Nf6 3. e3
{ We are delaying the development of the f3-knight for two reasons:   1@@EndBracket@@ The knight may develop to e2 in some positions.   2@@EndBracket@@ Sometimes White purposefully delays developing the g1-knight to gain queenside play. }
3... e6
{ Black keeps the bishop on c8. This is the classical response against London. Black's idea is to play ...Bd6-c5-Nc6-O-O, as you may have already realized: the move order can change! }
4. Nf3
{ The most popular move. This move order is key to remember since we have a surprise waiting after  4...Bd6 }
4... c5 5. Nbd2
{ Another important move order to remember. We will postpone c3 for a move or two since in some cases White can go for c2-c4 ideas and would not lose a tempo.   5.c3  I have mentioned this before, but it needs to be repeated since it is quite important. This move order allows Black to play  5...Bd6  6.Bg3  O-O  7.Nbd2  Qc7  8.Bd3  Where Black can develop the knight via  8...Nbd7=  and go for ...e5 next. }
5... Qb6
{ Attacking the b2-pawn immediately since White has not played c3 yet. } 6. Rb1
{ We didn't have any plans of long castling anyways. } 6... cxd4
{ 6...Nc6  7.c3  will transpose into the mainline London where only Black has downsides. Firstly, there is no ...Bd6 anymore. Secondly, there is no ...b6 anymore. }
7. exd4 Bd7
{ This idea is quite similar to French Advance. Black delays ...Nc6 and uses that to exchange the light-squared bishop. }
8. h4
{ The bishop will get exchanged, but we can gain some space on the kingside during this time. }
8... Bb5 9. Bxb5+ Qxb5 10. c3 Nc6 11. h5 { Threatening h6 next. } 11... h6
{ Logical. } 12. Ne5 Be7 13. Rh3
{ The king on e1 is stuck since castling on the queenside is not possible, therefore White's idea is to play Nd3 followed by Kf1-Kg1. Of course, ideas like Rg3 to create kingside attack is a bonus. }
13... O-O 14. Nd3 Rfd8 15. Kf1 Bd6 { Seems like a logical plan. } 16. Bxd6 Rxd6
17. Kg1
{ And White retains an advantage here. The plan should be to push f4-g4-g5 soon. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "10) London Mainline"]
[Black "Introduction to Mainline"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1bqkb1r/pp3ppp/2n1pn2/2pp4/3P1B2/2P1PN2/PP1N1PPP/R2QKB1R b KQkq - 0 6"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ We have finally arrived at the mainline of London. Being the most tested variation against the London, this demands an understanding of White's play as well as things to avoid. I will explain this in points.    1@@EndBracket@@ It is extremely vital that we control the e5-square and prevent the ...e5 break. This can be done by going Ne5 whenever there is a threat of ...e5 or when your development is complete.    2@@EndBracket@@ White should always answer ...Bd6 with Bg3.   3@@EndBracket@@ Generally speaking, ...Bxg3 is considered to be a bad decision since it opens up the h-file. Another reason is that when White goes Ne5-f4, the idea of g4-g5 becomes much more dangerous since White's king is not exposed thanks to the g2-pawn.   4@@EndBracket@@ After ...Bd6, Black can try to go for the ...e5 break in three different ways: A@@EndBracket@@ ...Qe7. B@@EndBracket@@ ...Qc7 and C@@EndBracket@@ ...Re8. With ...Qc7, White can simply grab the free pawn with dxc5. In ...Qe7 and ...Re8, we can stop ...e5 by going Ne5.   5@@EndBracket@@ If Black ever takes ...cxd4, then White should recapture with the e-pawn. The reason is simple, it opens up the e-file for White, which allows us to play Qe2 or Re1, controlling the e5-square further. It is also important to note that the idea of ...e5 becomes less desirable after ...cxd4 since Black will be left with an isolated pawn.   6@@EndBracket@@ When thinking long-term, it is important to understand the trades. It is completely okay to trade off the dark-square bishop, as long as Black does not get ...e5. The bishop on c8 is perhaps the biggest reason for Black's struggle. This bishop will remain passive for a long time, and we should avoid trading this piece unless we are getting material or other forms of compensation. }
6... -- *

