1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 Nf6 3. e3
{ We are delaying the development of the f3-knight for two reasons:   1@@EndBracket@@ The knight may develop to e2 in some positions.   2@@EndBracket@@ Sometimes White purposefully delays developing the g1-knight to gain queenside play. }
3... e6
{ Black keeps the bishop on c8. This is the classical response against London. Black's idea is to play ...Bd6-c5-Nc6-O-O, as you may have already realized: the move order can change! }
4. Nf3
{ The most popular move. This move order is key to remember since we have a surprise waiting after  4...Bd6 }
4... c5 5. Nbd2
{ Another important move order to remember. We will postpone c3 for a move or two since in some cases White can go for c2-c4 ideas and would not lose a tempo.   5.c3  I have mentioned this before, but it needs to be repeated since it is quite important. This move order allows Black to play  5...Bd6  6.Bg3  O-O  7.Nbd2  Qc7  8.Bd3  Where Black can develop the knight via  8...Nbd7=  and go for ...e5 next. }
5... Nc6 6. c3
{ This is the main setup of London. White's idea is to develop with Bd3 and O-O. If Black challenges the bishop via ...Bd6 we will simply tuck the bishop away with Bg3. One of the main points to remember in this position is to avoid ... e5 breakthrough as it generally equalizes the position for Black. This can be done via Ne5 in most cases. }
6... Nh5
{ This is a crucial move to remember. An instinctive move here would be to play Bg3, which would give Black a comfortable position after ...Nxg3. Therefore, White must act precisely. }
7. Bg5 f6 { Is another interesting idea. } 8. Bh4 g6
{ If Black does not play this, then ...f6 seems to be pointless. } 9. Bd3
{ Logical. } 9... cxd4
{ This is not necessary to take immediately, but Black has to at some stage which will transpose. }
10. cxd4
{ Generally speaking, White usually recaptures with the e-pawn. But doing so would allow ideas with ...Nf4. This also transposes into a worse version of the variation with @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp3ppp/2n1pn2/2pp4/3P1B2/2P1PN2/PP1N1PPP/R2QKB1R b KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6...cxd4  7.exd4  Nh5!?  , which will be discussed in the next chapter. }
10... Bd6
{ I personally think the bishop is better suited at e7 since it relieves the pin on the h4-f8 diagonal. However, this move cannot be ignored as it is extremely natural. }
11. O-O O-O 12. Rc1 { Getting the rook on an open file. } 12... Qe7 13. Ne1
{ The development is complete, so we can focus on improving the placement of our pieces. First of all, this move prevents any ideas with ...g5 as the h5-knight hangs and secondly, White's idea is to kick the knight with Be2 and offer the trade of the dark-squared bishops with Bg3. }
13... Bd7 14. Be2 Ng7 15. Bg3 Bxg3 16. hxg3
{ Mission accomplished. Now White has a slightly better position because of the superior bishop and Black's somewhat weak pawn structure on the kingside. }
16... Rac8 17. Nd3
{ Wiht a slight advantage. White should try for Nc5 ideas to put pressure on the b7-pawn. Another idea is to push g4 to restrict the g7-knight. }
