{ Black has managed to find some activity for the c8-bishop, at the cost of an IQP. }
13... Qd6 14. Qa4
{ White will always be slightly better in these positions because of the IQP. The reason for being worse isn't just the pawn, but the fact that Black has exchanged the dark-squared bishop, which is vital in these positions to control the outpost on d4 and eventually push ...d5-d4. Since this is not possible anymore, White will take complete control over d4 and make sure that the pawn remains isolated and weak for a long time. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "10) London Mainline"]
[Black "5...Nc6 with 6...cxd4 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 Nf6 3. e3
{ We are delaying the development of the f3-knight for two reasons:   1@@EndBracket@@ The knight may develop to e2 in some positions.   2@@EndBracket@@ Sometimes White purposefully delays developing the g1-knight to gain queenside play. }
3... e6
{ Black keeps the bishop on c8. This is the classical response against London. Black's idea is to play ...Bd6-c5-Nc6-O-O, as you may have already realized: the move order can change! }
4. Nf3
{ The most popular move. This move order is key to remember since we have a surprise waiting after  4...Bd6 }
4... c5 5. Nbd2
{ Another important move order to remember. We will postpone c3 for a move or two since in some cases White can go for c2-c4 ideas and would not lose a tempo.   5.c3  I have mentioned this before, but it needs to be repeated since it is quite important. This move order allows Black to play  5...Bd6  6.Bg3  O-O  7.Nbd2  Qc7  8.Bd3  Where Black can develop the knight via  8...Nbd7=  and go for ...e5 next. }
5... Nc6 6. c3
{ This is the main setup of London. White's idea is to develop with Bd3 and O-O. If Black challenges the bishop via ...Bd6 we will simply tuck the bishop away with Bg3. One of the main points to remember in this position is to avoid ... e5 breakthrough as it generally equalizes the position for Black. This can be done via Ne5 in most cases. }
6... cxd4
{ This is a much better version in comparison to  6...Nh5  since this eliminates the choice of recapturing with the c-pawn. }
7. exd4 Nh5 { The point. } 8. Be3
{ 8.Bg5  This is probably the appeal behind the idea of ...Nh5. We do not play this line anymore since we have already captured with exd4 and are giving away the important f4 square.  8...f6!?  9.Be3  Bd6  10.Bd3  Nf4  11.Bxf4  Bxf4  And the pawn on f6 only helps Black's idea of pushing either ...e5 or ...g5. This should be avoided. }
8... Bd6 9. Bd3
{ Simple developing move.  9.Ne5!?  is another interesting idea that can be investigated. }
9... Nf4
{ 9...O-O  10.O-O  f5  does not work because of  11.Ne5!  Nf6  12.Bf4⩲  And White gains control over e5.   10...Nf4  11.Bxf4  Bxf4  12.g3  Bd6  13.Re1  transposes to  10...Nf4  . }
10. Bxf4 Bxf4 11. g3 Bd6 12. O-O O-O 13. Re1
{ As you may have noticed already, it is much nicer to have the Black pawn on f7 instead of f6, I feel that it just creates fewer complications for White. }
13... Bd7
{ 13...f6  does not work now since White has an extra move.  14.b4!  And now ...e5 is not possible anymore. }
14. Rc1
{ With the idea of h4-a3 followed by c4. It might even be wise to tuck the bishop away with Bb1. }
