{ The second most popular move. Black once again intends to push ...e5 as quickly as possible, without dropping the pawn on c5 as we saw in the variation with 8...Qc7. }
9. Ne5 { Logical move, not allowing ... e5. } 9... cxd4 10. exd4 g6
{ The point. Black wants to play ...Nh5 next to put pressure on the g3-bishop and weakening White's control over the e5-square. }
11. Qe2 Nh5 12. O-O-O
{ The threat of ...Nxg3 does not pose a threat, so we can continue with development. It should be noted that when Black plays ...Nh5, it is better to avoid castling on the kingside since it makes ...Nxg3 more attractive. }
12... Qc7
{ 12...f6  will give White a better version in comparison to the mainline with 12.. Qc7.  13.Nxc6  bxc6  14.Bxd6  Qxd6  15.g3⩲  With the idea of f4 next. The e6-pawn remains weak. The knight on h5 is completely out of play and the bishop on c8 is far from being active. }
13. Nxc6
{ 13.Ndf3??  seems attractive but it allows a tactic with  13...Nxd4!-+  And Black wins a pawn by force. }
13... bxc6 14. Bxd6 Qxd6 15. Qe3
{ Keeping control of the c5-square. White can continue with g3-f4 next. The position is quite similar to 12... f6, but now Black's pawn on e6 is protected, which might be better, but the position still remains better for White. }
*

