[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 Nf6 3. e3
{ We are delaying the development of the f3-knight for two reasons:   1@@EndBracket@@ The knight may develop to e2 in some positions.   2@@EndBracket@@ Sometimes White purposefully delays developing the g1-knight to gain queenside play. }
3... e6
{ Black keeps the bishop on c8. This is the classical response against London. Black's idea is to play ...Bd6-c5-Nc6-O-O, as you may have already realized: the move order can change! }
4. Nf3
{ The most popular move. This move order is key to remember since we have a surprise waiting after  4...Bd6 }
4... c5 5. Nbd2
{ Another important move order to remember. We will postpone c3 for a move or two since in some cases White can go for c2-c4 ideas and would not lose a tempo.   5.c3  I have mentioned this before, but it needs to be repeated since it is quite important. This move order allows Black to play  5...Bd6  6.Bg3  O-O  7.Nbd2  Qc7  8.Bd3  Where Black can develop the knight via  8...Nbd7=  and go for ...e5 next. }
5... Nc6 6. c3
{ This is the main setup of London. White's idea is to develop with Bd3 and O-O. If Black challenges the bishop via ...Bd6 we will simply tuck the bishop away with Bg3. One of the main points to remember in this position is to avoid ... e5 breakthrough as it generally equalizes the position for Black. This can be done via Ne5 in most cases. }
6... Bd6
{ The most popular move. Black challenges the London Bishop and hopes to eliminate problems pertaining to the dark-squares. }
7. Bg3
{ The quiet retreat. We invite Black to exchange with ...Bxg3 as it allows us to get a better pawn structure with hxg3. This will be discussed a bit later. }
7... O-O 8. Bd3
{ Finally, we have arrived at the main position of London. Black's main idea in this position is to get the ...e5 breakthrough as quickly as possible. Of course, there are other ideas as well, which will be discussed soon. For clarity, Black's choices are: A@@EndBracket@@  8...Qc7  B@@EndBracket@@  8...Bxg3  C@@EndBracket@@  8...Re8  D@@EndBracket@@  8...Qe7  E@@EndBracket@@  8...g6  F@@EndBracket@@  8...b6 }
8... Qe7
{ The second most popular move. Black once again intends to push ...e5 as quickly as possible, without dropping the pawn on c5 as we saw in the variation with 8...Qc7. }
9. Ne5 { Logical move, not allowing ... e5. } 9... Nd7
{ The most popular move. The idea is obvious, Black intends to put further pressure on the e5-knight to push ...e5. }
10. Nxd7
{ It may not seem like it, but White is setting one of the most famous traps in the London. Black has to recapture with the Queen. }
10... Qxd7 { The right capture. Black has avoided mate... for now. } 11. O-O
{ Simple developing move.  11.dxc5  Bxc5  12.O-O⩲  can also be investigated further for variety. The idea here is to make a breakthrough in the next few moves either with a3-b4-c4 or e4 straight away. }
11... Bxg3
{ Makes the most sense since we have castled and no longer control the h-file.  11...e5??  blunders the pawn with  12.dxe5  Nxe5  13.Bxe5  Bxe5  14.Bxh7+  Kxh7  15.Qh5+±  With Qxe5 next. White is just a pawn up for no compensation. }
12. hxg3 Qe7
{ 12...e5  is once again a blunder because of  13.dxe5  Nxe5  14.Bxh7+±  with a free pawn. }
13. f4
{ Stopping ...e5 for good once again. In comparison to the previous variation, White has a much better version since the pawn on g3 allows ideas of Kf2-Rh1 where White has a strong attack alongside the h-file. Another advantage is that White can safely go for g4-g5 ideas without exposing the kingside. }
13... Bd7 14. g4 { Creating attacking chances on the kingside. } 14... f5
{ 14...Rac8  for example, would allow  15.g5!?  And sooner or later Black has to play ...f5 to protect the h7-pawn. The position will still not be closed because White has a second pawn on the g-file and can always push g4 if needed! I should mention that playing g5 is not necessary and White can always go for Qf3-Qh3 ideas to provoke ...f5. }
15. gxf5
{ 15.g5⩲  is also possible, but I prefer the text move more since it opens up the position. }
15... exf5 16. Qf3 Be6 17. Qh3
{ With the idea of Nf3 next. This can be followed with Kf2-Rh1 and perhaps g4!? at some stage to open up the kingside. White also has other ideas in this position such as the positional dxc5!? which isolates the d5-pawn and creates an outpost on d4. }
