1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 Nf6 3. e3
{ We are delaying the development of the f3-knight for two reasons:   1@@EndBracket@@ The knight may develop to e2 in some positions.   2@@EndBracket@@ Sometimes White purposefully delays developing the g1-knight to gain queenside play. }
3... e6
{ Black keeps the bishop on c8. This is the classical response against London. Black's idea is to play ...Bd6-c5-Nc6-O-O, as you may have already realized: the move order can change! }
4. Nf3
{ The most popular move. This move order is key to remember since we have a surprise waiting after  4...Bd6 }
4... c5 5. Nbd2
{ Another important move order to remember. We will postpone c3 for a move or two since in some cases White can go for c2-c4 ideas and would not lose a tempo.   5.c3  I have mentioned this before, but it needs to be repeated since it is quite important. This move order allows Black to play  5...Bd6  6.Bg3  O-O  7.Nbd2  Qc7  8.Bd3  Where Black can develop the knight via  8...Nbd7=  and go for ...e5 next. }
5... Nc6 6. c3
{ This is the main setup of London. White's idea is to develop with Bd3 and O-O. If Black challenges the bishop via ...Bd6 we will simply tuck the bishop away with Bg3. One of the main points to remember in this position is to avoid ... e5 breakthrough as it generally equalizes the position for Black. This can be done via Ne5 in most cases. }
6... Bd6
{ The most popular move. Black challenges the London Bishop and hopes to eliminate problems pertaining to the dark-squares. }
7. Bg3
{ The quiet retreat. We invite Black to exchange with ...Bxg3 as it allows us to get a better pawn structure with hxg3. This will be discussed a bit later. }
7... O-O 8. Bd3
{ Finally, we have arrived at the main position of London. Black's main idea in this position is to get the ...e5 breakthrough as quickly as possible. Of course, there are other ideas as well, which will be discussed soon. For clarity, Black's choices are: A@@EndBracket@@  8...Qc7  B@@EndBracket@@  8...Bxg3  C@@EndBracket@@  8...Re8  D@@EndBracket@@  8...Qe7  E@@EndBracket@@  8...g6  F@@EndBracket@@  8...b6 }
8... b6
{ The most popular move. Black gives up on the idea of ...e5 and focuses on regrouping the pieces via ... Bb7-Ne7-Ne4!?   8...Qc7?!  is just bad because of  9.dxc5!  Bxg3  10.hxg3± }
9. e4
{ Breaking the center. This move should be timed perfectly for the best results. The reader should note that by pushing ... b6 Black temporarily has weakened the c6-square, which makes capturing on e4 bad for Black. }
9... Be7 { The best move. } 10. e5 { Following on the idea behind e4. } 10...
Nh5 { Only move once again. } 11. Ng5 Bxg5 { Only move. } 12. Qxh5 g6
{ Only move. } 13. Qe2 cxd4
{ White has an attack on the kingside in any case, if Black does not take the pawn now, then there will be no compensation for the attack. Therefore, this is the only move here. }
14. h4 { Going for the kill. } 14... Be7 { Keeping the dark-squared bishop. }
15. h5 dxc3 16. bxc3 d4
{ Black is going for the same idea discussed in the variation with 14...Bxd2 but in this case Black has better control over the dark squares. }
17. c4
{ Once again, it is in our best interest to not open up any files.  17.hxg6  hxg6  18.Ne4!?→  seems interesting and can be investigated further. }
17... Nb4 { Only move. } 18. Be4 d3 19. Qg4 g5 { Only move. } 20. O-O
{ Luckily for us, not including the check allows for castling. } 20... Rb8 21.
h6 Bb7 { This is slightly inferior to the main move. } 22. Rab1
{ Going after the d3-pawn. The idea is to go Rb3-a3 next. } 22... Na6
{ Black maneuvers the knight to c5 to protect the d3-pawn where it wont be kicked anymore. }
23. Bf4 Nc5 24. Be3
{ With decent attacking chances. Black's position remains exposed. The pawn on g5 is a potential target. }
