[SetUp "1"]

{ In this chapter, we will be looking at Queen's Indian Structures @@StartBracket@@QID@@EndBracket@@. Black can play this move in two different ways, either @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pppppppp/5n2/8/3P1B2/8/PPP1PPPP/RN1QKBNR b KQkq - 2 2@@EndFEN@@  2...b6  or @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pppppppp/5n2/8/3P1B2/8/PPP1PPPP/RN1QKBNR b KQkq - 2 2@@EndFEN@@  2...e6  3.e3  b6  . I will explain the latter in a separate note.  In this case, I recommend @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/p1pppppp/1p3n2/8/3P1B2/8/PPP1PPPP/RN1QKBNR w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nc3!?  this move is relatively new with less than 100 games in the database. The idea is that after  3...Bb7  we will be going  4.f3!  with the idea of playing e4 next. This provokes  4...d5  , and we will push  5.e4  anyways to sacrifice the pawn for the sake of activity. The reason for selecting this repertoire is to firstly provide the student with fresh ideas and also to deny the QID structure altogether. }
3. -- *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "11) Queen's Indian Defense"]
[Black "2...b6 with 5...dxe4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4
{ This chapter is dedicated to the Queen's Indian setup. Black achieves this through ...e6-b6-Bb7-Be7-O-O and eventually Black throws ...c5. As a London player, one should avoid a direct transposition into any mainstream opening. I believe I have managed to do exactly that.   In this chapter, we will be looking at: A@@EndBracket@@  2...b6  B@@EndBracket@@  2...e6    2...b6 is direct, and will be a smaller chapter in comparison to 2... e6 where we will be looking at the idea of 3... b6 directly and 3... c5 before Black goes for ...b6. }
2... b6
{ This move is not as popular, but still possible when facing QID players. Black intends to get the bishop out quickly and delays the development of the f8-bishop. }
3. Nc3
{ Taking action Jobava-Rapport London System style. White intends to push e4 and take control of the center. This move is not as popular. Generally speaking, White goes for  3.e3  . }
3... Bb7 4. f3
{ Continuing the idea of getting e4 as quickly as possible. This move also provokes ...d5 which blocks the fianchetto bishop on b7. }
4... d5
{ 4...e6  This is also possible.  5.e4  d5  6.Nb5  directly transposing into the variations with 4... d5. }
5. e4 { We will push the pawn anyways for the sake of active play. } 5... dxe4
{ Capturing the pawn seems most logical. } 6. fxe4
{ Black should be careful here to not take the bait with ...Nxe4. } 6... Nxe4
{ Risky choice. } 7. Qf3 Nd6 8. Bb5+
{ If not for this move, the idea with 4. e4 would not be possible. The idea is to provoke ...c6 which blocks the bishop on b7. }
8... Nd7 { This will allow White to exchange the light-squared bishops. } 9.
Bc6 Bxc6 10. Qxc6
{ Black's pieces are paralyzed. White can continue to develop via O-O-O and Nf3. Black's king is far from getting safe. The knight on d7 and d6 remain passive. White's queen does a great job of controlling pretty much everything in the position. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "11) Queen's Indian Defense"]
[Black "2...b6 with 5...dxe4 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4
{ This chapter is dedicated to the Queen's Indian setup. Black achieves this through ...e6-b6-Bb7-Be7-O-O and eventually Black throws ...c5. As a London player, one should avoid a direct transposition into any mainstream opening. I believe I have managed to do exactly that.   In this chapter, we will be looking at: A@@EndBracket@@  2...b6  B@@EndBracket@@  2...e6    2...b6 is direct, and will be a smaller chapter in comparison to 2... e6 where we will be looking at the idea of 3... b6 directly and 3... c5 before Black goes for ...b6. }
2... b6
{ This move is not as popular, but still possible when facing QID players. Black intends to get the bishop out quickly and delays the development of the f8-bishop. }
3. Nc3
{ Taking action Jobava-Rapport London System style. White intends to push e4 and take control of the center. This move is not as popular. Generally speaking, White goes for  3.e3  . }
3... Bb7 4. f3
{ Continuing the idea of getting e4 as quickly as possible. This move also provokes ...d5 which blocks the fianchetto bishop on b7. }
4... d5
{ 4...e6  This is also possible.  5.e4  d5  6.Nb5  directly transposing into the variations with 4... d5. }
5. e4 { We will push the pawn anyways for the sake of active play. } 5... dxe4
{ Capturing the pawn seems most logical. } 6. fxe4
{ Black should be careful here to not take the bait with ...Nxe4. } 6... Nxe4
{ Risky choice. } 7. Qf3 Nd6 8. Bb5+
{ If not for this move, the idea with 4. e4 would not be possible. The idea is to provoke ...c6 which blocks the bishop on b7. }
8... c6
{ 8...Nxb5??  will drop an exchange.  9.Qxb7  Nxc3  10.Qxa8+-  with a winning position. }
9. Bd3
{ Mission accomplished. The bishop on b7 is now restricted by its own pawn. }
9... c5
{ Is also possible. The instinct would argue to play  10.Bb5+  in this position but Black can defend with  10...Nd7  since the idea of  11.Bc6  is not as strong anymore. }
10. Ne4 { Not allowing Black to get comfortable. } 10... Qd7 11. O-O-O
{ We are now threatening dxc5 and Bxd6. Both of them seem quite dangerous. Black's only chance of survival in this position is move the c-pawn. }
11... cxd4
{ I think this move is very risky. Black ignores the development of the pieces and focuses on material gain. }
12. Ne2 { Developing the knight and aiming to capture on d4. } 12... Nc6 13.
Bxd6 exd6 14. Bb5 { Pinning the queen and threatening Nxd4 once again. } 14...
O-O-O
{ Only move. The king does not seem safe on the queenside.  14...Be7  loses to  15.Nxd4  O-O  16.Bxc6  Bxc6  17.Nxc6  Qxc6  18.Nf6++-  winning the queen. }
15. Nxd4 Qc7 { Getting out of the pin. } 16. Bxc6 Bxc6 17. Rhe1
{ Protecting the e4-knight and threatening to take on c6 next. The bishop on c6 is vital to this position since it controls all the light squares, and this is exactly the reason why the bishop cannot move from c6 in this case.   17.Nxc6±  is also fine, but I prefer the main move order. }
17... Kb8
{ 17...Bb7??  loses to  18.Nb5+-  with capture on d6 to follow. White is completely winning. }
18. Nxc6+ Qxc6 19. Qxf7
{ White has recovered the lost pawn. Black's problems remain. The pawn on d6 is isolated. The bishop on f8 is still not developed. The light squares are extremely weak. White is clearly better. }
*

