[Black "2...b6 with 5...dxe4 #6"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4
{ This chapter is dedicated to the Queen's Indian setup. Black achieves this through ...e6-b6-Bb7-Be7-O-O and eventually Black throws ...c5. As a London player, one should avoid a direct transposition into any mainstream opening. I believe I have managed to do exactly that.   In this chapter, we will be looking at: A@@EndBracket@@  2...b6  B@@EndBracket@@  2...e6    2...b6 is direct, and will be a smaller chapter in comparison to 2... e6 where we will be looking at the idea of 3... b6 directly and 3... c5 before Black goes for ...b6. }
2... b6
{ This move is not as popular, but still possible when facing QID players. Black intends to get the bishop out quickly and delays the development of the f8-bishop. }
3. Nc3
{ Taking action Jobava-Rapport London System style. White intends to push e4 and take control of the center. This move is not as popular. Generally speaking, White goes for  3.e3  . }
3... Bb7 4. f3
{ Continuing the idea of getting e4 as quickly as possible. This move also provokes ...d5 which blocks the fianchetto bishop on b7. }
4... d5
{ 4...e6  This is also possible.  5.e4  d5  6.Nb5  directly transposing into the variations with 4... d5. }
5. e4 { We will push the pawn anyways for the sake of active play. } 5... dxe4
{ Capturing the pawn seems most logical. } 6. fxe4
{ Black should be careful here to not take the bait with ...Nxe4. } 6... Nxe4
{ Risky choice. } 7. Qf3 Nd6 8. Bb5+
{ If not for this move, the idea with 4. e4 would not be possible. The idea is to provoke ...c6 which blocks the bishop on b7. }
8... c6
{ 8...Nxb5??  will drop an exchange.  9.Qxb7  Nxc3  10.Qxa8+-  with a winning position. }
9. Bd3
{ Mission accomplished. The bishop on b7 is now restricted by its own pawn. }
9... g6
{ This has never been tried in practice. The structure only gives White an extra target with h4-h5 in the long run. }
10. O-O-O { Development first. } 10... Bg7 11. Qg3
{ Keeping the queen active and creating space for the knight. } 11... O-O 12.
h4 { Now that Black has castled. White can strike on the kingside. } 12... h5
{ Only move. } 13. Be5 { Challenging the only defender on the kingside. } 13...
Ba6 { Only move. } 14. Bxg7
{ 14.Bxg6!?  is another interesting move that can be investigated further. }
14... Kxg7 15. Qe5+ { Forcing Black to weaken the kingside by pushing ...f6. }
15... f6 16. Qg3 { Exploiting the weakness on g6. } 16... Bxd3 17. Qxd3 Nd7 18.
Nge2
{ White once again maintains a massive attack on the kingside. Right now, the threat of Nf4 needs to be dealt with. White does not necessarily need to rush with g4, and can focus on putting the pieces in the right squares prior. This can be done via Rg1-Nf4 and maybe then g4. There is another idea with Qf3 which seems quite interesting as it protects the g4-square and attacks the c6-pawn. }
