[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4
{ This chapter is dedicated to the Queen's Indian setup. Black achieves this through ...e6-b6-Bb7-Be7-O-O and eventually Black throws ...c5. As a London player, one should avoid a direct transposition into any mainstream opening. I believe I have managed to do exactly that.   In this chapter, we will be looking at: A@@EndBracket@@  2...b6  B@@EndBracket@@  2...e6    2...b6 is direct, and will be a smaller chapter in comparison to 2... e6 where we will be looking at the idea of 3... b6 directly and 3... c5 before Black goes for ...b6. }
2... b6
{ This move is not as popular, but still possible when facing QID players. Black intends to get the bishop out quickly and delays the development of the f8-bishop. }
3. Nc3
{ Taking action Jobava-Rapport London System style. White intends to push e4 and take control of the center. This move is not as popular. Generally speaking, White goes for  3.e3  . }
3... Bb7 4. f3
{ Continuing the idea of getting e4 as quickly as possible. This move also provokes ...d5 which blocks the fianchetto bishop on b7. }
4... d5
{ 4...e6  This is also possible.  5.e4  d5  6.Nb5  directly transposing into the variations with 4... d5. }
5. e4 { We will push the pawn anyways for the sake of active play. } 5... e6
{ This has been tried a few times by Black. However, we have a way to obtain a decent advantage. }
6. Nb5 { Provoking ... Na6 where the knight will be misplaced. } 6... Na6 7. e5
Nd7 8. Be3
{ Aiming for f4 to solidify the center and also to develop the knight on f3 where it will be most active. }
8... c5 9. f4
{ This is perhaps where the reader can understand the importance of including Nb5. The knight on a6 is completely out of play and restricts Black from kicking the knight with ...a6. }
9... Nab8 10. Nf3 a6 11. Nc3 Nc6 12. Ne2
{ Thematic idea of french. White keeps an eye on d4 and aims to further overprotect the pawn with c2-c3 push. }
12... Be7 13. c3 O-O 14. Ng3
{ The pawn on d4 is protected, so we can remove the knight to get our bishop out. This is a horrible version of French for Black. It seems like everything that could go wrong, has gone wrong. White's follow-up should be to go Bd3-O-O and look for either a breakthrough via f5 or creating further attacking chances with Ng5!? Either way, White's dominance in the center will remain for a long time. }
*

