[Black "2...b6 with 5...e6 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4
{ This chapter is dedicated to the Queen's Indian setup. Black achieves this through ...e6-b6-Bb7-Be7-O-O and eventually Black throws ...c5. As a London player, one should avoid a direct transposition into any mainstream opening. I believe I have managed to do exactly that.   In this chapter, we will be looking at: A@@EndBracket@@  2...b6  B@@EndBracket@@  2...e6    2...b6 is direct, and will be a smaller chapter in comparison to 2... e6 where we will be looking at the idea of 3... b6 directly and 3... c5 before Black goes for ...b6. }
2... b6
{ This move is not as popular, but still possible when facing QID players. Black intends to get the bishop out quickly and delays the development of the f8-bishop. }
3. Nc3
{ Taking action Jobava-Rapport London System style. White intends to push e4 and take control of the center. This move is not as popular. Generally speaking, White goes for  3.e3  . }
3... Bb7 4. f3
{ Continuing the idea of getting e4 as quickly as possible. This move also provokes ...d5 which blocks the fianchetto bishop on b7. }
4... d5
{ 4...e6  This is also possible.  5.e4  d5  6.Nb5  directly transposing into the variations with 4... d5. }
5. e4 { We will push the pawn anyways for the sake of active play. } 5... e6
{ This has been tried a few times by Black. However, we have a way to obtain a decent advantage. }
6. Nb5 { Provoking ... Na6 where the knight will be misplaced. } 6... Na6 7. e5
Nd7 8. Be3
{ Aiming for f4 to solidify the center and also to develop the knight on f3 where it will be most active. }
8... c6
{ Including this move only helps Black since the knight on b5 will not be able to recapture in time. }
9. Nc3 c5 10. f4 cxd4 11. Bxd4
{ The bishop on d4 is generally considered to be dubious, but only if the knight can kick it and gain a tempo. This isn't the case anymore. Black can always retreat with ...Nb8 as we will see in this line, but doing this wastes a crucial tempo. }
11... Nab8 12. Nf3 Nc6 13. Bb5
{ Offering the bishop for the sake of activity. White aims to exchange both bishops with knights since the nature of the position is closed. }
13... Nxd4 14. Nxd4 a6
{ 14...Be7?  This is a bit careless.  15.Qf3  O-O  16.O-O-O±  The development is complete. The idea should now be to capture the knight on d7 if Black allows it. If not, then bring the bishop back to d3 where it will be a valuable attacker. Eventually, Black will be forced to exchange this bishop via ...Nc5-Nxd3 which brings us to a similar position.   Black's bishops are blocked since the center is closed. We should make sure that the pawn on d5 remains on d5 in the next few moves @@StartBracket@@maybe even longer@@EndBracket@@. White can always play moves like f5!? which will bring substantial attacking possibilities. }
15. Bxd7+ Qxd7 16. Qd3 { Aiming to castle next. } 16... g6
{ Stopping f5 ideas in advance. } 17. O-O-O
{ Getting the king to safety.  17.g4!?  is quite interesting as well. I don't think theoretical knowledge is required in these positions so I would recommend players try it out in a game. The idea is to get f5 as quickly as possible, but of course - make sure that you castle first. }
17... h5 { Stopping the idea with g4. } 18. Kb1 O-O-O 19. Nce2
{ The position remains slightly better for White. This is because of the minor pieces. Black's bishop on b7 is permanently blocked on b7 and the bishop on f8 may have some squares, but is useless regardless. The idea is to go Ng1-Ngf3 where the knight can not only give the d4-knight an extra hand but also controls the e5-pawn. This is relevant if White decides to go for the g4-f5 break.   In an ideal world, White should try to exchange one of the knights with the f8-bishop. If this is achieved, then the position should be winning, but of course, this will not happen anytime soon. An important note here is that Black basically has no breakthroughs in the position since ...f6 and ...g5 breakthroughs would weaken Black's structure.   Therefore, White's approach should be slow. Moves such as g3,a3 would go a long way towards annoying your opponent and provoking something rash. In some lines, White also goes for a3-b4 ideas. This might be a bit too optimistic, but it is possible. }
*

