[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "11) Queen's Indian Defense"]
[Black "2...e6 with 3...c5 and 4...b6"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4
{ This chapter is dedicated to the Queen's Indian setup. Black achieves this through ...e6-b6-Bb7-Be7-O-O and eventually Black throws ...c5. As a London player, one should avoid a direct transposition into any mainstream opening. I believe I have managed to do exactly that.   In this chapter, we will be looking at: A@@EndBracket@@  2...b6  B@@EndBracket@@  2...e6    2...b6 is direct, and will be a smaller chapter in comparison to 2... e6 where we will be looking at the idea of 3... b6 directly and 3... c5 before Black goes for ...b6. }
2... e6 { This is the main move order for Queen's Indian players. } 3. e3 c5
{ This was my initial worry. But after analyzing a bit in depth, I realized that pretty much everything transposes into another chapter. }
4. Nf3 { Important. We are delaying c3 on purpose. } 4... b6
{ 4...Nc6  5.Nbd2  d5  6.c3  transposes to the 2. Bf4 Nf6 3. e3 Chapter.   4...d5  5.Nbd2  also transposes to 2. Bf4 Nf6 3. e3 Chapter.   4...Qb6  would transpose after  5.Nbd2  Qxb2  6.Rb1  to Chapter 15 here.  This move, 4... b6, may seem logical at first. But look again! We delayed c3 on purpose. Can you find out why? }
5. Nc3
{ The point. White exploits the exposed structure and aims to go either Nb5 or d5. Only one of those threats can be stopped. }
5... cxd4
{ This is a desperate attempt to complicate matters. So let's keep our approach simple.  5...Bb7  will just allow  6.Nb5!  Na6  7.Nd2±  With the idea of Nc4 next. The knight on b5 will forever keep the a6-knight misplaced. White is clearly better. }
6. Nxd4 { Once again we threaten Nb5 ideas. } 6... a6 { Only move. } 7. Qf3
{ Brilliant move. White forces Black to push ...d5 which blocks the view of the b7-bishop. }
7... d5 8. O-O-O { 8.Bxb8  Rxb8  9.Nc6  also simply wins the exchange. } 8...
Bb7 9. g4
{ White is close to winning, if not winning already. This is because firstly Black's development is horrific. Secondly, with the idea of g5-h4 next, Black would not be able to castle on the short side due to the attack. The king cannot escape to the queenside either because of the London bishop! }
