[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "12) King's Indian and Grünfeld Defense"]
[Black "Introduction to King's Indian Grünfeld Structure"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "rnbqkb1r/pppppp1p/5np1/8/3P1B2/8/PPP1PPPP/RN1QKBNR w KQkq - 0 3"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ In this chapter, I will be discussing the KID/Grunfeld setup. White's idea is quite simple and these moves don't necessarily have to be in the same order: Nf3-e3-h3-Be2-O-O-Bh2. The bishop on h2 might seem a bit passive, but it plays an important role in the position. I will explain this shortly.    If Black goes for ...d6 @@StartBracket@@KID@@EndBracket@@ setup, then the follow-up is to play either ...e5 or ...c5. In both cases, the h2-b8 diagonal becomes crucial to control. For example, if Black goes ...e5 then White keeps the option of dxe5-dxe5 and Nc4 in order to provoke ...e4, which opens up the diagonal for the London Bishop. If Black goes for the ...c5 break, we can simply play c3. During the middlegame, once White has castled, there are two main points that the user should keep in mind.   - Firstly, at some point, you should play a4 to restrict ...b5 ideas and also to go Na3-Nb5 to activate the knight.   - Secondly, White should refrain from going Nbd2 unless absolutely necessary. The reason is that Black generally plays ... Ne4 and it is wise to counter it with Nfd2. The reason is that firstly, we have the option of going f3-e4 to gain control in the center and secondly to play Bf3 which will exchange the fianchetto bishop on b7 and make it easier for us to play e4. }
3. -- *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "12) King's Indian and Grünfeld Defense"]
[Black "2...g6 with 4...d5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4 g6 3. Nf3 Bg7 4. e3
{ The quiet approach. In the past, both GM Le Quang Liem and GM Hans Niemann opted for  4.Nc3  in this position for their repertoire. I prefer this move because I believe this setup represents the spirit of the London.   White's idea is simple: develop the pieces, castle, push h3, and tuck the bishop away to h2 and patiently wait until your opponent complains endlessly about having to play against London. I would like to also mention that the benefit of playing this repertoire is not only embedded in its simple style, but also that Black's setup will eventually transpose into the mainline.   Black basically has two setups to choose here, and it all comes down to whether Black will play ...d6 or ...d5. The former makes more sense because it restricts the mobility of the London bishop along the h2-b8 diagonal. The latter ignores the elephant in the room since the bishop will pose endless problems along the h2-b8 diagonal. }
4... d5
{ This is possible if you are facing a Grunfeld player. I personally have never liked ... d5 for Black since it makes the London bishop only stronger. }
5. h3 c5 6. c3 Nc6 7. Be2
{ Delaying  7.Nbd2  for the moment, this is because if Black tries to go  7...Qb6  8.Qb3  the knight will be better placed on a3. We will go through this shortly. }
7... O-O 8. Nbd2 Nd7
{ This is another idea. Black wants to play ...Re8 followed by ...e5 breakthrough. }
9. O-O Re8 10. Nb3 { Putting pressure on the c5-pawn and provoking ...c4. }
10... c4
{ 10...cxd4  11.exd4  Would make ...e5 undesirable since Black will be left with an IQP. }
11. Nbd2 e5 12. dxe5 Ndxe5 13. Nd4
{ We see the point behind provoking ...c4. White has successfully acquired the outpost and intends to put pressure on the backward pawn on d5. The idea should be to go N2f3 next in order to exchange the knight and put our light-squared bishop on f3, where it attacks the d5-pawn. }
