1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4 g6 3. Nf3 Bg7 4. e3
{ The quiet approach. In the past, both GM Le Quang Liem and GM Hans Niemann opted for  4.Nc3  in this position for their repertoire. I prefer this move because I believe this setup represents the spirit of the London.   White's idea is simple: develop the pieces, castle, push h3, and tuck the bishop away to h2 and patiently wait until your opponent complains endlessly about having to play against London. I would like to also mention that the benefit of playing this repertoire is not only embedded in its simple style, but also that Black's setup will eventually transpose into the mainline.   Black basically has two setups to choose here, and it all comes down to whether Black will play ...d6 or ...d5. The former makes more sense because it restricts the mobility of the London bishop along the h2-b8 diagonal. The latter ignores the elephant in the room since the bishop will pose endless problems along the h2-b8 diagonal. }
4... d5
{ This is possible if you are facing a Grunfeld player. I personally have never liked ... d5 for Black since it makes the London bishop only stronger. }
5. h3 c5 6. c3 Nc6 7. Be2
{ Delaying  7.Nbd2  for the moment, this is because if Black tries to go  7...Qb6  8.Qb3  the knight will be better placed on a3. We will go through this shortly. }
7... Qb6 8. Qb3 c4 9. Qxb6
{ 9.Qa3  The reader could try this in a game if they feel confident, the only drawback is that Black now has a tactical resource  9...Bf8!  This is still quite holdable, but White is definitely in some trouble. However, in faster formats, I doubt if your opponent would be able to spot this. }
9... axb6
{ This is generally considered to be worse for White since Black gets ...b5-b4 push and can potentially damage White's queenside structure. However, in this scenario, White does have a slight pull because Black has already developed ...g6-Bg7 which helps White's case since Black's bishop no longer controls the f8-a3 diagonal which is one of the main reasons why the ...b5-b4 push is successful. }
10. O-O O-O { Does not really pose any problems. } 11. Nbd2 b5 12. a3
{ And now the ...b4 push is no longer available.  12...Bf5  is quite logical, but is in fact a worse move for Black because of  13.g4!?  and the bishop is forced to retreat.  13...Bd7  14.Kg2  White maintains a small edge in this position due to the dominating London bishop. It is also worth noting that Black is not able to play ...e5 anytime soon, therefore, White can continue expanding on the kingside.   This can be done in two ways: 1@@EndBracket@@ Bd1-Bc2-Re1-e4 2@@EndBracket@@ Bg3-Nh4-f4 @@StartBracket@@to stop any ...e5 ideas@@EndBracket@@ In both cases, White will retain a slight advantage. }
