{ We do not mind giving up the bishop in this scenario thanks to the ...f7-f6 push that restricts the g7-bishop and also weakens Black's defense on the kingside. }
6... O-O
{ This seems a bit more logical since Black is not giving attacking possibilities on the kingside at the moment. }
7. Bh4 { Intending g4 next to trap the knight. } 7... d6 8. Be2 f5 9. Nc3
{ Developing the knight and threatening Nd5 ideas. } 9... Nf6 10. Bxf6 Bxf6 11.
h4 { Launching the attack. } 11... d5 { Blocking the e3-e4 breakthrough. } 12.
Qd2 c6 13. Ne5
{ With a great position. White can play f4 in the next move to fix the pawn and break with h5 as soon as possible. }
