[White "12) King's Indian and Grünfeld Defense"]
[Black "2...g6 with 4...O-O and 6...Nc6 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4 g6 3. Nf3 Bg7 4. e3
{ The quiet approach. In the past, both GM Le Quang Liem and GM Hans Niemann opted for  4.Nc3  in this position for their repertoire. I prefer this move because I believe this setup represents the spirit of the London.   White's idea is simple: develop the pieces, castle, push h3, and tuck the bishop away to h2 and patiently wait until your opponent complains endlessly about having to play against London. I would like to also mention that the benefit of playing this repertoire is not only embedded in its simple style, but also that Black's setup will eventually transpose into the mainline.   Black basically has two setups to choose here, and it all comes down to whether Black will play ...d6 or ...d5. The former makes more sense because it restricts the mobility of the London bishop along the h2-b8 diagonal. The latter ignores the elephant in the room since the bishop will pose endless problems along the h2-b8 diagonal. }
4... O-O 5. Be2 d6 6. h3 Nc6
{ By blocking the c7-pawn, Black makes the intention clear - to go for the ...e5 break. Black can do this in two different ways - 1@@EndBracket@@ ...Nd7-e5-f5 or 2@@EndBracket@@ ...Ne4-e5-f5. Of course, there is a possibility of going ...e5 straight and then Black can decide where to place the f6-knight. }
7. O-O Nd7
{ Once again, Black threatens ...e5 and ... f5. In this case, you will see that Black's knight on d7 is not well placed either since it blocks the view of the c8-bishop. }
8. Bh2 { Always! } 8... e5 9. a4
{ This move might seem a bit strange but it has a positional idea. While Black is busy pushing ...f5, we will push a5 and either provoke Black to play ...a6 or push a6 ourselves. In both cases, White will be able to generaly queenside play due to the advanced pawn. }
9... a5
{ This is another possibility. We did not manage to push a5, but we are successful in provoking it. This opens up a semi-outpost for the knight on b1. }
10. Nc3 { Logical. } 10... f5 11. Nb5
{ This knight on b5 plays a very important role in generating queenside play. In particular, the c4-c5 breakthrough. Of course, it will be useful to include Rc1 in this plan. Black will try to scare you with ...g5 at some stage, but it is harmless as long as White breaks the queenside faster. }
11... e4 { This move seems good at first but allows a nice tactic. } 12. Ng5
{ Threatening Ne6 and opening up the possibility of Bc4+. } 12... Qxg5 13. Nxc7
Rb8 14. Bxd6
{ White does not care about the rook on f8. The knight on c7 is far superior. Technically speaking, White is down in material, but it is compensated in the form of superior pieces. }
14... Qf6 15. Nb5 Ra8 16. c4
{ With the idea of pushing c5 and Bc4. White has active pieces and controls the game. }
