[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4 g6 3. Nf3 Bg7 4. e3
{ The quiet approach. In the past, both GM Le Quang Liem and GM Hans Niemann opted for  4.Nc3  in this position for their repertoire. I prefer this move because I believe this setup represents the spirit of the London.   White's idea is simple: develop the pieces, castle, push h3, and tuck the bishop away to h2 and patiently wait until your opponent complains endlessly about having to play against London. I would like to also mention that the benefit of playing this repertoire is not only embedded in its simple style, but also that Black's setup will eventually transpose into the mainline.   Black basically has two setups to choose here, and it all comes down to whether Black will play ...d6 or ...d5. The former makes more sense because it restricts the mobility of the London bishop along the h2-b8 diagonal. The latter ignores the elephant in the room since the bishop will pose endless problems along the h2-b8 diagonal. }
4... O-O
{ 4...c5  for example, will transpose into the mainline eventually after  5.Be2  O-O  6.O-O  d6  7.h3  Nbd7  8.Bh2  with a direct transposition to the mainline with 4... O-O.   4...d6  5.h3  O-O  6.Be2  will transpose into the mainline. }
5. Be2 d6
{ This is a crucial idea to remember. Whenever Black pushes ...d6 we must respond with h3 to make space for the bishop to go to h2. This is because the pawn on d6 protects the e5-square, making ...Nh5 a threat. This idea can be compared to the mainstream Spanish position where the bishop sits on b3 and Black plays ...d6 to go ...Na5 and we respond with c3 or a3 to make space for the Spanish bishop.   5...c5  will transpose into the mainline after  6.c3  b6  7.O-O  Bb7  8.Nbd2  d6  9.h3  Nbd7  10.Bh2   5...d6  6.h3  would transpose into 4...d5 lines eventually. }
6. h3 Nbd7 7. Bh2
{ Safely tucking the bishop away. We are deviating from mainstream theory with castling, but once again - it will eventually transpose into the mainline when we castle. Black has three ideas in this position. 1@@EndBracket@@  7...c5  2@@EndBracket@@  7...Qe8  or 3@@EndBracket@@  7...Re8  with the idea of ...e5. }
7... Re8
{ This is a lot more sound compared to ...Qe8 as it does not lose a tempo. However, we should note that Black is not threatening ...e5 at the moment. }
8. O-O b6
{ Logical. Black intends to develop the bishop to b7 and protect the d8-queen in the process, making ...e5 possible.  8...e5?!  blunders the pawn away.  9.dxe5  dxe5  10.Nxe5⩲  And White is simply better. }
9. c4 Bb7 10. Nfd2
{ This might seem a bit strange at first, but this idea is used quite often in these positions. There are two reasons behind this: firstly, White wants to play Bf3 and exchange the bishop on b7. Secondly, this move is targeted towards ...Ne4 where White generally avoids trading the c3 knight with the e4-knight, simply because the knight on c3 provides more value to the position and once again, allows Bf3. }
10... e5 11. Nc3
{ Planning for d5 next. White could not play it immediately because of the breakthrough with ...b5! }
11... exd4 { Most precise. } 12. exd4 Nf8 13. Bf3 Bxf3 14. Nxf3 Ne4
{ If Black does not go for this, then White can continue normally with 16. Qd3. Black's problem in this position is lack of space, therefore, Black should exchange pieces when given the opportunity. }
15. Nxe4 Rxe4 16. Qd3 Re8
{ 16...Qe7?!  allows a nice tactic.  17.Ne5!?  Rh4  18.Nc6  Qe4  19.Qxe4  Rxe4  20.Rfe1⩲  White maintains a small edge thanks to our wonderful knight on c6. }
17. Rae1 Qd7 { Threatening the sneaky ...Qa4. } 18. b3
{ Not giving any counterplay. } 18... Rxe1
{ Logically speaking, Black should be going for the trade to solve the problem with space. But, the endgame only favors White further. It is a common principle of chess that one should consider while thinking of exchanging pieces - it's never about what is being exchanged, it's about what is left on the board. And yes, I am once again referencing the London bishop. }
19. Rxe1 Re8 20. Rxe8 Qxe8 21. Bf4
{ White maintains a small edge. This is largely due to the fact that Black has a 'bad' bishop on g7 and therefore is lacking control over the light squares. White can continue improving the position slowly via d5-Be3. It's also worth noting that Black shouldn't really be exchanging queens in this scenario since it only makes the structure on the queenside weaker. }
