{ This is a crucial idea to remember. Whenever Black pushes ...d6 we must respond with h3 to make space for the bishop to go to h2. This is because the pawn on d6 protects the e5-square, making ...Nh5 a threat. This idea can be compared to the mainstream Spanish position where the bishop sits on b3 and Black plays ...d6 to go ...Na5 and we respond with c3 or a3 to make space for the Spanish bishop.   5...c5  will transpose into the mainline after  6.c3  b6  7.O-O  Bb7  8.Nbd2  d6  9.h3  Nbd7  10.Bh2   5...d6  6.h3  would transpose into 4...d5 lines eventually. }
6. h3 Nbd7 7. Bh2
{ Safely tucking the bishop away. We are deviating from mainstream theory with castling, but once again - it will eventually transpose into the mainline when we castle. Black has three ideas in this position. 1@@EndBracket@@  7...c5  2@@EndBracket@@  7...Qe8  or 3@@EndBracket@@  7...Re8  with the idea of ...e5. }
7... c5
{ Most popular move. Black's idea is to either go for ...Qb6 or follow the normal plan with ...b6-Bb7. }
8. O-O
{ Generally, we would respond with c3. In this case, after  8.c3  Black has an extra possibility of  8...b5!?  and this is why I prefer to play 8. O-O instead. }
8... b6 9. a4 Bb7 10. c3 { Better late than never! } 10... Qc7
{ Is another choice, but Black has to play ...a6 at some point and it would inevitably transpose into the mainline. }
11. Re1
{ We are on purpose delaying the development of the b1-knight, this is because if Black tries to go ...Ne4 we can answer via Nfd2! }
11... Ne4 12. Nfd2 Nxd2 13. Nxd2 a6 14. Qb3
{ White has a very comfortable position. The idea is to eventually push d5 to block the b7-bishop and continue with e4-f4 ideas. Black once again is out of useful ideas, and this is generally never a good thing.   For example,  14...Rfe8  15.d5!  Nf6  16.e4⩲  followed by f4. I have mentioned this in the past, but it is worth noting how useful the h2-bishop really is to this position. It is not only contributing to the eventual e5-push, but also restricting ...e6-ideas from Black's side since it makes the d6-pawn weak. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "12) King's Indian and Grünfeld Defense"]
[Black "2...g6 with 4...O-O and 6...Nbd7 #13"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4 g6 3. Nf3 Bg7 4. e3
{ The quiet approach. In the past, both GM Le Quang Liem and GM Hans Niemann opted for  4.Nc3  in this position for their repertoire. I prefer this move because I believe this setup represents the spirit of the London.   White's idea is simple: develop the pieces, castle, push h3, and tuck the bishop away to h2 and patiently wait until your opponent complains endlessly about having to play against London. I would like to also mention that the benefit of playing this repertoire is not only embedded in its simple style, but also that Black's setup will eventually transpose into the mainline.   Black basically has two setups to choose here, and it all comes down to whether Black will play ...d6 or ...d5. The former makes more sense because it restricts the mobility of the London bishop along the h2-b8 diagonal. The latter ignores the elephant in the room since the bishop will pose endless problems along the h2-b8 diagonal. }
4... O-O
{ 4...c5  for example, will transpose into the mainline eventually after  5.Be2  O-O  6.O-O  d6  7.h3  Nbd7  8.Bh2  with a direct transposition to the mainline with 4... O-O.   4...d6  5.h3  O-O  6.Be2  will transpose into the mainline. }
5. Be2 d6
{ This is a crucial idea to remember. Whenever Black pushes ...d6 we must respond with h3 to make space for the bishop to go to h2. This is because the pawn on d6 protects the e5-square, making ...Nh5 a threat. This idea can be compared to the mainstream Spanish position where the bishop sits on b3 and Black plays ...d6 to go ...Na5 and we respond with c3 or a3 to make space for the Spanish bishop.   5...c5  will transpose into the mainline after  6.c3  b6  7.O-O  Bb7  8.Nbd2  d6  9.h3  Nbd7  10.Bh2   5...d6  6.h3  would transpose into 4...d5 lines eventually. }
6. h3 Nbd7 7. Bh2
{ Safely tucking the bishop away. We are deviating from mainstream theory with castling, but once again - it will eventually transpose into the mainline when we castle. Black has three ideas in this position. 1@@EndBracket@@  7...c5  2@@EndBracket@@  7...Qe8  or 3@@EndBracket@@  7...Re8  with the idea of ...e5. }
7... c5
{ Most popular move. Black's idea is to either go for ...Qb6 or follow the normal plan with ...b6-Bb7. }
8. O-O
{ Generally, we would respond with c3. In this case, after  8.c3  Black has an extra possibility of  8...b5!?  and this is why I prefer to play 8. O-O instead. }
8... b6 9. a4 Bb7 10. c3 { Better late than never! } 10... a6 11. Re1 Ra7
{ Opting for the 'Alekhine's Gun' via ...Qa8. } 12. c4
{ Key move. The idea is to block 'Alekhine's Gun' via d4-d5 push. On the other hand, a move like this is only possible because Black's rook is slightly misplaced on a7, which does not provide enough time to activate via ...Rc8. }
12... Qa8 { Is pointless in this case, since White can simply go for d5. } 13.
d5 { Making the whole maneouvre pointless. } 13... b5
{ Probably the best response, but White can reply with Nbd2. } 14. Nbd2 b4
{ 14...bxc4?!  allows  15.e4⩲  and White will eventually take on c4 and aim to push e5 when possible. }
15. Qc2
{ The queenside is completely blocked, and realistically only White can play on the kingside. I will not claim that White is better here, but such positions are generally considered as 'playing for two results'. White should go for Bd3-e4 ideas and look to expand on the kingside, perhaps via Ng5-f4 or Nh4-f4. Black on the other hand, has no real ideas... }
*

