[Black "Introduction to Benoni and Benko Structures"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "rnbqkb1r/pp1ppppp/5n2/2p5/3P1B2/8/PPP1PPPP/RN1QKBNR w KQkq - 0 3"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ In this chapter, we will discuss Benoni / Benko structures. Both of these openings have a dynamic reputation, and this chapter will reflect that. My recommendation is @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pp1ppppp/5n2/2p5/3P1B2/8/PPP1PPPP/RN1QKBNR w KQkq c6 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.d5  .  The idea is to go Nc3 followed by e4 to gain full control of the center.   After  3.d5  b5  @@StartBracket@@Benko@@EndBracket@@ I have recommended the ultra-sharp  4.e4!?  where we will sacrifice a pawn temporarily for massive activity. If Black goes @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pp1ppppp/5n2/2pP4/5B2/8/PPP1PPPP/RN1QKBNR b KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Qb6  then we will gladly sacrifice the b2-pawn by simply developing  4.Nc3  . If  4...Qxb2  then  5.Bd2  protecting the knight and going for e4-f4-Nf3-Bb5-O-O. The threat of e5 is extremely dangerous in such positions.   In the Benoni structure with  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pp1ppppp/5n2/2pP4/5B2/8/PPP1PPPP/RN1QKBNR b KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3...d6  4.Nc4  g6  , we will occupy the center with  5.e4  and develop normally via Nf3-O-O-a4. In this position, White does not need to play dynamic since Black's position is fundamentally worse due to less space. White simply just needs to protect the d5-pawn and create play against the d6-pawn, perhaps by going Nd2-Nc4-f4-e5. }
3. -- *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "13) Benoni and Benko Defense"]
[Black "3...b5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4 c5
{ The aggressive approach. This line has been trending recently and you should expect this move order regularly in your games. }
3. d5
{ This line was mentioned initially by FM Daniel Barrish on Chessable. I think that this move is objectively the best for this position. The reason is that firstly, we avoid the sharp line after the mainstream  3.e3  Qb6  followed by ...Qxb2, which was also mentioned and analyzed by myself in Agadmator's London Course.   Secondly, and perhaps a more important point is that this setup is a much better version compared to Benoni/Benko structures that arise after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  Nf6  2.c4  c5  3.d5  b5  or  3...e6  .  The benefit we have in comparison to the Benko/Benoni structure is that we have not committed c4, which is one of the main targets in Benko and this is why ...b5 is played. In this case, we will not be playing c4 at all and would rather go for Nc3-e4 ideas instead. }
3... b5
{ Is liked by the computer most. But I feel that practically this is not the best decision as Black ends up in sharp positions where precise play is required. }
4. e4
{ At the time of writing, this move only has 3 games where White has scored 2.5. Black needs to play extremely precisely in order to not end up in a worse position. }
4... Nxe4
{ The only realistic response.  4...Bb7  for example, immediately gives White a substantial advantage after  5.Bxb5  Nxe4  6.Ne2±  White is clearly better thanks to piece activity. The follow-up should be to go castle and Nbc3. }
5. Qf3
{ Kicking the knight away and aiming to take the b5-pawn.  5.Bxb5??  allowas  5...Qa5+-+ }
5... Nd6
{ Seems logical since Black wants to hold on to the pawn. White is spoilt for choices here. }
6. Bxd6 exd6 7. Bxb5
{ Seems the easiest. White did give up the bishop pair, but achieved a lot more in return. Apart from the ruptured pawn structure on d7 and d6, it should be noted that Black will struggle to develop the queenside pieces as a consequence of this. }
7... Be7 8. Ne2 O-O 9. Nd2 Na6 10. Bd3
{ With the idea of c4 next. I like this move because it makes the c8-bishop entirely useless. If White were to generate play on the kingside, it would be similar to having an extra piece in the position. }
*

