{ Kicking the knight away and aiming to take the b5-pawn.  5.Bxb5??  allowas  5...Qa5+-+ }
5... Qa5+ { Only move. } 6. Nd2 { Retreating the knight with } 6... Nf6
{ Is a little tricky, and we should be precise in the next few moves so that Black does not develop their pieces actively and just be a pawn up. }
7. Ne2 Bb7 8. c4 { Interesting idea aimed against restricting the b7-bishop. }
8... g6
{ 8...bxc4  is obviously wrong because of  9.Nc3!±  Protecting the d5-pawn and preparing the Nxc4 next. This idea is fairly common in Benko positions. }
9. Nc3 a6 { Is slightly worse. } 10. cxb5 axb5 11. Bxb5 Bg7 12. Nc4
{ Kicking the queen away. } 12... Qd8
{ Allows a nasty tactic that ends Black's hopes of survival. } 13. Nd6+ exd6
14. Bxd6 { Threatening Qe3+ next. } 14... Qa5
{ 14...Qb6?  allows  15.Qe3+  Kd8  16.Bxc5+-  followed by Bb6+. } 15. O-O
{ Development first. } 15... Kd8 16. Be5 Qb6
{ Only move. Here comes the beauty. } 17. Bc6
{ Obstructing the Queen's view. Black is dead lost. } 17... dxc6 18. Bxf6+
{ With a winning position. } *

