{ This line was mentioned initially by FM Daniel Barrish on Chessable. I think that this move is objectively the best for this position. The reason is that firstly, we avoid the sharp line after the mainstream  3.e3  Qb6  followed by ...Qxb2, which was also mentioned and analyzed by myself in Agadmator's London Course.   Secondly, and perhaps a more important point is that this setup is a much better version compared to Benoni/Benko structures that arise after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  Nf6  2.c4  c5  3.d5  b5  or  3...e6  .  The benefit we have in comparison to the Benko/Benoni structure is that we have not committed c4, which is one of the main targets in Benko and this is why ...b5 is played. In this case, we will not be playing c4 at all and would rather go for Nc3-e4 ideas instead. }
3... b5
{ Is liked by the computer most. But I feel that practically this is not the best decision as Black ends up in sharp positions where precise play is required. }
4. e4
{ At the time of writing, this move only has 3 games where White has scored 2.5. Black needs to play extremely precisely in order to not end up in a worse position. }
4... Nxe4
{ The only realistic response.  4...Bb7  for example, immediately gives White a substantial advantage after  5.Bxb5  Nxe4  6.Ne2±  White is clearly better thanks to piece activity. The follow-up should be to go castle and Nbc3. }
5. Qf3
{ Kicking the knight away and aiming to take the b5-pawn.  5.Bxb5??  allowas  5...Qa5+-+ }
5... Qa5+ { Only move. } 6. Nd2 { Retreating the knight with } 6... Nf6
{ Is a little tricky, and we should be precise in the next few moves so that Black does not develop their pieces actively and just be a pawn up. }
7. Ne2 Bb7 8. c4 { Interesting idea aimed against restricting the b7-bishop. }
8... g6
{ 8...bxc4  is obviously wrong because of  9.Nc3!±  Protecting the d5-pawn and preparing the Nxc4 next. This idea is fairly common in Benko positions. }
9. Nc3 a6 { Is slightly worse. } 10. cxb5 axb5 11. Bxb5 Bg7 12. Nc4
{ Kicking the queen away. } 12... Qa7 { Only move. } 13. h4
{ 13.O-O  is also fine, but I think including h4-h5 makes Black's position slightly more exposed, which gives White better chances of attack in the future. }
13... O-O { Is a bit optimistic. } 14. h5 e6
{ 14...Na6  can simply be met with  15.h6  Bh8  16.O-O±  and we have achieved what we wanted. The pawn on h6 will play a crucial role in any type of kingside attack in the future. }
15. Be5 Bxd5
{ 15...Nxd5  blunders immediately,  16.Bxg7  Kxg7  17.Nxd5  Bxd5  18.h6+  Kg8  19.Qf6+-  with a mate to follow. }
16. Qf4 Nxh5 { Only move once again. } 17. Rxh5 f6 18. Bd6 Bxc4
{ 18...gxh5  allows White to simplify with  19.Bxf8  Bxf8  20.Nxd5  exd5  21.Qf5!  Taking the d5-pawn sooner rather than later. White is completely winning. }
19. Rxc5 Bxb5 20. Bxf8 Bc6 21. Bd6
{ Of course we do not want to trade our stronger dark-squared Bishop for Black's weaker one. }
21... Na6 22. Rc4
{ The position has more or less calmed down, and White is up an exchange for no reasonable compensation. White should aim to push the b-pawn quickly and end Black's misery. }
