{ Logical retreat, Black wants to defend via ...Qf6. However, if this was the idea all along, then ...b4 was a bit unnecessary. }
9. Bd3
{ Developing move that is aimed against ...Qf6 since after Black takes on b2 White does not need to waste time moving the rook away and can rather just castle. }
9... Qf6
{ A bit unnecessary since nothing is provoking Black to play this. It is obvious that Black is struggling with development and therefore should focus on getting the pieces out as quickly as possible. }
10. Qe2 Bb7
{ 10...Qxb2?  is obviously a huge mistake for the reason mentioned in the previous note.  11.O-O+-  White is spoilt for attacking ideas and should begin immediately. Moves like f4-f5 will be extremely deadly since it not only creates attacking chances but also restricts Black from developing their kingside. }
11. c4 bxc3 12. Bxc3 Qd6 13. Be4 { Protecting the central pawn. } 13... f5
{ 13...Bxd5?  blunders away the position because of  14.Rd1!+-   A side note:  14.O-O-O  would not have worked since Black has  14...Qh6! }
14. Bf3 { 14.Bxf5  is also fine. } 14... Bxd5 15. O-O
{ Development is complete. White threatens Rad1 next. A more in-depth analysis of this line is provided here. }
