{ This line was mentioned initially by FM Daniel Barrish on Chessable. I think that this move is objectively the best for this position. The reason is that firstly, we avoid the sharp line after the mainstream  3.e3  Qb6  followed by ...Qxb2, which was also mentioned and analyzed by myself in Agadmator's London Course.   Secondly, and perhaps a more important point is that this setup is a much better version compared to Benoni/Benko structures that arise after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  Nf6  2.c4  c5  3.d5  b5  or  3...e6  .  The benefit we have in comparison to the Benko/Benoni structure is that we have not committed c4, which is one of the main targets in Benko and this is why ...b5 is played. In this case, we will not be playing c4 at all and would rather go for Nc3-e4 ideas instead. }
3... b5
{ Is liked by the computer most. But I feel that practically this is not the best decision as Black ends up in sharp positions where precise play is required. }
4. e4
{ At the time of writing, this move only has 3 games where White has scored 2.5. Black needs to play extremely precisely in order to not end up in a worse position. }
4... Nxe4
{ The only realistic response.  4...Bb7  for example, immediately gives White a substantial advantage after  5.Bxb5  Nxe4  6.Ne2±  White is clearly better thanks to piece activity. The follow-up should be to go castle and Nbc3. }
5. Qf3
{ Kicking the knight away and aiming to take the b5-pawn.  5.Bxb5??  allowas  5...Qa5+-+ }
5... Qa5+ { Only move. } 6. Nd2 Nxd2 7. Bxd2 b4
{ Is also possible, but quite unnecessary since in the next move we are playing a4 anyways to provoke b4. }
8. Nh3 { Activating the knight, and threatening Ng5 next. } 8... Qb6
{ Logical retreat, Black wants to defend via ...Qf6. However, if this was the idea all along, then ...b4 was a bit unnecessary. }
9. Bd3
{ Developing move that is aimed against ...Qf6 since after Black takes on b2 White does not need to waste time moving the rook away and can rather just castle. }
9... g6
{ Black has to develop, and this is the only way to get the king to safety. }
10. O-O Bg7 11. Rae1
{ In the famous book 'Sacrifice and Initiative' by GM Ivan Sokolov, he mentions that when attacking opponents territory, one should not worry about grabbing or saving unnecessary material. I believe this move is an example of that since White does not care about defending the b2-pawn and focuses on the big picture, which is to keep the initiative. }
11... O-O { What else? } 12. Rxe7
{ White is already in a dreamlike position. But let's go a bit further to make sure the advantage does not slip away anytime soon. }
12... Qf6 13. Qe2
{ Black is struggling with space, exchanging queens will only help our opponent. }
13... Ba6 14. Re1 Bxd3 15. Qxd3 Qxb2
{ Taking the pawn at this stage feels necessary to have compensation for White's strong initiative. If Black does not take now, White can just push b3 and continue with Ng5 and create attacking chances. }
16. Re8 Qxa2
{ Only move. Black has to take the pawn in order to develop the b8 knight via ...Na6. }
17. Rxf8+ Bxf8 18. Ng5 { The dance has begun. } 18... Na6
{ Seems logical as it develops the piece, but White is too fast here. } 19. Qf3
f5 20. d6
{ Only move. Otherwise Black escapes. The idea here is to not just attack the rook but also to make sure that Black's queen remains on the a2-g8 diagonal since Qd5+ is always going to be a deadly threat. }
20... Rc8 { Allows the crushing } 21. g4 h6 22. gxf5 gxf5 23. Qxf5 hxg5 24.
Qxd7 Rb8 25. Bxg5 { With a completely winning position. } *

