[White "13) Benoni and Benko Defense"]
[Black "3...e6 with 4...d6"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4 c5
{ The aggressive approach. This line has been trending recently and you should expect this move order regularly in your games. }
3. d5
{ This line was mentioned initially by FM Daniel Barrish on Chessable. I think that this move is objectively the best for this position. The reason is that firstly, we avoid the sharp line after the mainstream  3.e3  Qb6  followed by ...Qxb2, which was also mentioned and analyzed by myself in Agadmator's London Course.   Secondly, and perhaps a more important point is that this setup is a much better version compared to Benoni/Benko structures that arise after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  Nf6  2.c4  c5  3.d5  b5  or  3...e6  .  The benefit we have in comparison to the Benko/Benoni structure is that we have not committed c4, which is one of the main targets in Benko and this is why ...b5 is played. In this case, we will not be playing c4 at all and would rather go for Nc3-e4 ideas instead. }
3... e6
{ This can be expected from a Benoni player in hopes that White will play  4.c4  and transpose. I should mention that the computer screams  4.c4  is the best choice for White in this position, but I feel that London players do not need to study Benoni as it is a different ballpark, therefore, I have recommended 4. Nc3 instead for a simpler position. I should mention that if the reader has studied Benoni with the Bf4 system, then 4. c4 should be the primary choice since it would save time. }
4. Nc3 d6
{ Inserting ... d6 before taking on d4 is a slight error since it allows White to go for e4. }
5. e4 exd5 6. Nxd5
{ 6.exd5  With the idea of Nf3-Bc4-O-O-h3 is a great way to play this position as well. }
6... Nxd5 7. Qxd5 Nc6
{ In this position, ...d6 is already committed. If Black had gone for the more 'precise' option instead, Black would have been able to play ...Qf6! }
8. Ne2 { Protecting the f4-bishop and aiming to go Nc3 next. } 8... Be6 9. Qd2
Be7 10. Nc3 { The a2-pawn is protected. White is ready to castle. } 10... Bf6
{ 10...O-O  11.O-O-O⩲  will give White a decent advantage because of the d5-square. And since White will control the center, the flank attack with f3-h4-h5 will be deadly. }
11. O-O-O { 11.Rd1!?  is also possible. } 11... Qa5 12. a3 O-O-O
{ Saving the pawn. } 13. Nd5 Qxd2+ 14. Rxd2 Be5 15. Bg5
{ A clever prophylactic move. White realizes that Black will have to give up the e6-bishop at some stage to eliminate the monstrous d5-knight, and prepares for this by provoking Black's pawns to a darker square and weakening the light ones where the f1-bishop will dominate. }
15... f6 16. Be3 Bd4 17. Bxd4 Nxd4 18. Bc4 Rhe8 19. Rhd1 Bxd5 20. Bxd5
{ White's bishop is clearly superior to the knight, and Black does have a potential weakness on d6 that can be exploited at a later stage. At the moment, White should aim to expand on the kingside in hopes of creating a second weakness on the board, but there is absolutely no rush to do this. }
