[White "13) Benoni and Benko Defense"]
[Black "3...Qb6 with 4...Qxb2 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4 c5
{ The aggressive approach. This line has been trending recently and you should expect this move order regularly in your games. }
3. d5
{ This line was mentioned initially by FM Daniel Barrish on Chessable. I think that this move is objectively the best for this position. The reason is that firstly, we avoid the sharp line after the mainstream  3.e3  Qb6  followed by ...Qxb2, which was also mentioned and analyzed by myself in Agadmator's London Course.   Secondly, and perhaps a more important point is that this setup is a much better version compared to Benoni/Benko structures that arise after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  Nf6  2.c4  c5  3.d5  b5  or  3...e6  .  The benefit we have in comparison to the Benko/Benoni structure is that we have not committed c4, which is one of the main targets in Benko and this is why ...b5 is played. In this case, we will not be playing c4 at all and would rather go for Nc3-e4 ideas instead. }
3... Qb6
{ Finally. If your opponent goes for this, it is possible that they were expecting 3.e3 Qb6 variation and want to continue in the same fashion. After looking through the lines carefully, this seems to be extremely dangerous for Black in practice. }
4. Nc3 Qxb2 { Biting the bait. } 5. Bd2
{ This is a transposition to the Vaganian gambit from the Trompowsky which arises via the move order: @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  Nf6  2.Bg5  c5  3.d5  Qb6  4.c3  Qxb2  5.Bd2  . }
5... Qb6
{ Clever move. Black waits to commit between ...g6 and ...e6 and also avoids the trap with Rb1-Nb5 which would end the game instantly. }
6. e4 { Threatening e5. } 6... d6 7. f4
{ Once again, e5 is something to worry about. } 7... e6 { Also makes sense. }
8. Nf3 exd5 { Seems appealing at first, but allows a nice resource. } 9. e5
dxe5 10. fxe5 Ne4 11. Nxd5 Qd8 { Everything has been forced so far. } 12. c4
{ Securing the d5-square permanently.  12.Bc4  Was going to be my first choice initially, but I avoided this because it ends up in a position where White's chances to win are slim. I have given the line which posed a problem for context.  I should mention that this sequence is pretty much forced from Black's side, so if you would like to try it out for a game or two - there is basically no downside.   12...Nc6  13.O-O  Be6  14.Be1  Qd7  15.Qd3  O-O-O  16.Rd1  Nd4  17.Bh4  Bxd5  18.Bxd5  Qxd5  19.c4  Qd7  20.Qxe4  Be7  21.e6  Nxf3+  22.Qxf3  Qxe6  23.Rfe1  Bxh4  24.Rxe6  fxe6  25.Rxd8+  Rxd8=  And Black should be able to equalize with ease. Although White is basically playing for two results here. }
12... Nc6
{ 12...Be6  will transpose after  13.Bd3  Nxd2  14.Qxd2  Nc6  15.O-O  to the mainline. }
13. Bd3 Nxd2 14. Qxd2 Be6 15. O-O Bxd5
{ Seems logical, but Black ends up in huge trouble. } 16. cxd5 Qxd5 17. Qc2
{ Preparing for Rad1. } 17... Be7 18. Rad1
{ Black's king cannot castle on either side due to the discovered check. }
18... c4 19. Bxh7 { Spoiling the kingside castling plans. } 19... Qc5+ 20. Kh1
Rd8 21. e6
{ Thematic. White breaks through Black's defensive line with a sacrifice. }
21... Rxd1 22. Rxd1
{ I will stop here. Black has to move or give up the f7-pawn, which will allow Bg6+ and force Black's king to move to an undesirable f8-square. White's domination on the light squares in unmatched, and this is a big reason why Black's position is nearly lost. }
