Qe1 Ne7
{ This is another way to protect h6.  20...Rh8  21.Qh4  Kg7  Seems logical. White should try to be precise here to get a decent advantage.  22.Rd1!  Creating an x-ray over the queen. White's threat is now to go Bf4.  22...Qe7   22...Nd4  23.Be3  Preparing for Nxd4.  23...Nxf3+  24.gxf3  Rag8  Black prepares for the Qg3+ with a trick of their own.  25.Kf2!  Let's get out of the pin, there is no rush!  25...Qa4  Most precise. So White has to counter in a precise manner to get a winning position.  26.Rxd6  Qxc2+  27.Bd2  Qb2  28.e5!  White attempts to divert the queens attention away from the d2-bishop.  28...Qxe5  29.Qg4+  And now ...Kf8 is not possible because of Rd8+ and Rxg8, since the d2-bishop is no longer attacked, White is winning.  29...Kh7  30.Qh5+-  Once again, Black is in big trouble and will lose material or the game very soon.  23.Bf4  Ne5  Seemed quite logical. And I really like White's follow-up here. If the reader would like to pause and try to find the move, it is highly recommended.  24.Nd2!  The idea is to go Nb1-Nc3-Nd5 where the knight will be a monster.  24...Rab8  25.Nb1  Rb4  26.Nc3  Rc4  27.Nd5  Qd8  28.Re1+-  With the idea of Re3-Rg3+. Black's position is on the verge of collapse thanks to the exposed king and a complete lack of coordination. }
21. Qh4 Ng8 22. g4 { Let's not waste any time and strike. } 22... Qe7 23. g5
Rae8 { Pretty much forced. } 24. Qh5
{ Clever move. White anticipates ... Qxe4 and removes the Queen from h4 to have a free move once Black captures the pawn. }
24... Qxe4 25. gxf6 { The point. Black is completely lost now. } 25... Qc4
{ 25...Qe2??  stopping Ng5+  26.Bxh6!+-  The game is over. } 26. Rf2
{ Only move that wins. White's idea is to go Rg2-Rg6! } 26... Rb8 27. h3
{ Creating a square for the king on h2. } 27... Rb1+ 28. Kh2
{ Apart from Rg2, White also has a threat of going Bxh6 soon. White is completely winning. }
