[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4 c5
{ The aggressive approach. This line has been trending recently and you should expect this move order regularly in your games. }
3. d5
{ This line was mentioned initially by FM Daniel Barrish on Chessable. I think that this move is objectively the best for this position. The reason is that firstly, we avoid the sharp line after the mainstream  3.e3  Qb6  followed by ...Qxb2, which was also mentioned and analyzed by myself in Agadmator's London Course.   Secondly, and perhaps a more important point is that this setup is a much better version compared to Benoni/Benko structures that arise after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  Nf6  2.c4  c5  3.d5  b5  or  3...e6  .  The benefit we have in comparison to the Benko/Benoni structure is that we have not committed c4, which is one of the main targets in Benko and this is why ...b5 is played. In this case, we will not be playing c4 at all and would rather go for Nc3-e4 ideas instead. }
3... Qb6
{ Finally. If your opponent goes for this, it is possible that they were expecting 3.e3 Qb6 variation and want to continue in the same fashion. After looking through the lines carefully, this seems to be extremely dangerous for Black in practice. }
4. Nc3 Qxb2 { Biting the bait. } 5. Bd2
{ This is a transposition to the Vaganian gambit from the Trompowsky which arises via the move order: @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  Nf6  2.Bg5  c5  3.d5  Qb6  4.c3  Qxb2  5.Bd2  . }
5... Qb6
{ Clever move. Black waits to commit between ...g6 and ...e6 and also avoids the trap with Rb1-Nb5 which would end the game instantly. }
6. e4 { Threatening e5. } 6... d6 7. f4
{ Once again, e5 is something to worry about. } 7... Qd8
{ The most clever move. Black does not commit anything but at the same time prevents White from playing e5.  7...Nbd7  is too committal. Black has managed to stop e5 for now, but at the cost of blocking the c8-bishop.  8.Nf3  Qc7  9.Qe2+-  and e5 is inevitable, giving White a winning position. }
8. a4
{ Clever idea. White overprotects the b5-square in case Bb5+ followed by e5 is needed.  8.Bc4?!  would allow  8...e6  and now Bb5+ is less useful. For example,  9.Bb5+?!  Bd7  10.dxe6  fxe6  11.e5  Bxb5!  Now the crucial axb5 move is no longer possible.  12.Nxb5  dxe5  13.fxe5  Ne4∓  and Black has solved their problems. }
8... e6 { In this case, does not work. } 9. Bb5+
{ An important intermezzo before capturing on e6 so that Black is forced to damage their pawn structure. }
9... Bd7 10. dxe6 fxe6 11. e5 { Breaking the center. } 11... dxe5 12. fxe5 Bxb5
13. axb5 { That does not give away the e4-square. } 13... Nd5 14. Qg4
{ With a completely crushing game ahead. } *

