8. a4
{ Clever idea. White overprotects the b5-square in case Bb5+ followed by e5 is needed.  8.Bc4?!  would allow  8...e6  and now Bb5+ is less useful. For example,  9.Bb5+?!  Bd7  10.dxe6  fxe6  11.e5  Bxb5!  Now the crucial axb5 move is no longer possible.  12.Nxb5  dxe5  13.fxe5  Ne4∓  and Black has solved their problems. }
8... a6
{ Stopping any Bb5+ ideas. However, this move does come with a grain of salt. Black is now unable to castle long since the queenside is going to be exposed. }
9. Bc4
{ Important move order aimed against ...e6, in which case, the g1-knight is better placed on e2 where it can either go Nec3-Nd5 or Ng3 and launch a kingside attack. }
9... e6 10. Nge2 Be7 11. O-O O-O 12. Ng3
{ With the intention of Nh5 at some stage. } 12... exd5
{ Black has to take sooner or later to develop the b8-knight. } 13. Nxd5 Nc6
14. Ra3 { Bringing another piece to the party. } 14... Kh8
{ Black moves the king away from any potential checks and aims to develop via ...Bg4.  14...Be6?  will end up badly because of  15.f5  Bxd5  16.Bxd5!  Nxd5  17.exd5  Ne5  18.Nh5+-  followed by Rg3 with a crushing attack. }
15. Nxe7
{ Positionally speaking, this move makes no sense as we are basically exchanging our strongest piece with our opponents' weakest piece. However, White cannot really afford to think positionally anymore since Black's pieces are getting activated and time is running out. Therefore, by making this exchange White intends to play Bd5 and go for Bxc6 or provoke ...Nxd5. The reader will notice that in both cases, we land in an opposite color bishop middlegame.   Generally speaking, opposite-colored bishops are often seen as 'drawish' since the absolute version of them @@StartBracket@@with no other pieces on the board@@EndBracket@@ are exactly that. However, in middlegames, this is completely different. In fact, opposite-colored bishops favor the attacker since the bishop cannot be challenged by its opponent, it is almost like playing or attacking with an extra piece. This is the reason behind Nxe7. }
15... Qxe7
{ 15...Nxe7  will just be losing after  16.f5!+-  followed by Nh5 next. } 16.
Bd5 Be6 { For example, will end badly for Black. } 17. Bxc6 bxc6 18. f5 Bc4 19.
Re1
{ With the idea of Rf3-Bc3 and perhaps Rf4-Rh4-Nh5 to carry the attack forward. Note that the c3-bishop remains unchallenged in this scenario, which is a good example of why opposite coloured bishops favour the attacker in the middlegame. }
