1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4 c5
{ The aggressive approach. This line has been trending recently and you should expect this move order regularly in your games. }
3. d5
{ This line was mentioned initially by FM Daniel Barrish on Chessable. I think that this move is objectively the best for this position. The reason is that firstly, we avoid the sharp line after the mainstream  3.e3  Qb6  followed by ...Qxb2, which was also mentioned and analyzed by myself in Agadmator's London Course.   Secondly, and perhaps a more important point is that this setup is a much better version compared to Benoni/Benko structures that arise after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  Nf6  2.c4  c5  3.d5  b5  or  3...e6  .  The benefit we have in comparison to the Benko/Benoni structure is that we have not committed c4, which is one of the main targets in Benko and this is why ...b5 is played. In this case, we will not be playing c4 at all and would rather go for Nc3-e4 ideas instead. }
3... d6
{ The most popular move. Honestly, this seems extremely passive for someone who plays ...c5 on move 2 against the London. Regardless, it's important to know the approach from White's side.   3...g6  This is also a candidate move, however, this would transpose soon into 3... d6.  4.Nc3  Bg7  5.e4  d6  6.Nf3  directly  transposes into the variation with 3... d6. }
4. Nc3
{ As mentioned previously, we refrain from playing c2-c4 in these cases because it gives Black an easier target with ...a6-b5 and also restricts our light-squared bishop to go to b5 or c4 where it has proven to be useful in the previous variations. }
4... e5
{ This is the most popular setup for Black which seems to have scored quite well in the past. However, the idea that I am going to suggest is perhaps the safest and gives White a slight advantage from the start.   4...e6  transposes after  5.e4  to 3... e6 variation. }
5. Bg5 Be7 6. Bxf6
{ This seems a bit counterproductive, but it makes sense. To understand this capture, White must first address that this position is similar to an Old Indian or King's Indian setup, with one major difference. The pawn is on c5 instead of c7. This I believe changes the face of the position since Black's knight is now unable to go ...Nd7-Nc5.   Secondly, having the pawn on c5 makes d6 a potential target in the future. Finally, Black's kingside attack will not be as dangerous because White can simply reroute via Nd2-Nc4 and create problems on the queenside much faster than Black. }
6... Bxf6 7. e4 O-O 8. Nf3 g6
{ Seems to be the only plan for Black. The idea is to go ...Bg7 and aim for ...f5 as quickly as possible. }
9. a4
{ This move has two ideas:   1@@EndBracket@@ We push a5-a6 once the knight on b8 has moved, provoking ...b6. This will allow White to go Bb5-Bc6 followed by Nb5 ideas to put pressure on the a7-pawn.   2@@EndBracket@@ We push a5 and provoke ...a6 from Black. This will allow White to go Nd2-Nc4-Ra3-Rb3-Rb6 to put pressure on the d6-pawn. This can also be followed up with Qb1-b4 so that if Black takes on b4 we can recapture with the queen. }
9... Bg7 10. Nd2 Nd7 11. a5 a6 12. Bd3 f5 13. Qe2
{ Delaying castling for now since we might end up going long and go for h4-h5 ideas. }
13... Qc7 14. Ra3 Nf6 { Has to be played at some stage. } 15. Nc4 Rb8 16. f3
{ 16...Nd7  can be met with  17.Na4!  Rf7  18.O-O  Kh8  19.Rb3±  With the idea of Nab6 and keeping the pressure on the d6-pawn. }
