[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "14) Dutch Defense"]
[Black "Introduction to Dutch"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/ppppp1pp/8/5p2/3P4/8/PPP1PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 2"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ In this chapter, we will focus on Dutch. There are a number of different ways to play as White, but to keep it aligned with London, I have recommended @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppppp1pp/8/5p2/3P4/8/PPP1PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Bf4  .  After 2. Bf4, Black has two different setups to choose from. 1@@EndBracket@@  ...g6-Bg7 @@StartBracket@@Leningrad@@EndBracket@@ and 2@@EndBracket@@  ... e6-d5-Nf6 @@StartBracket@@Stonewall@@EndBracket@@.    In the Leningrad setup, we can go for the immediate h4! with the threat of h5. This is extremely bad for Black and it is very likely that White will get a lethal attack on the kingside. In the Stonewall setup, the bishop on f4 is fantastic since it controls the h2-b8 diagonal. The plan is to play Nf3-c4-h3-Be2 and O-O. Once White has castled, it is time to develop the queenside.   Generally speaking, White goes for c3 in London setups, but since Black has not played ...c5. We can go for c4 instead and develop the knight via Nc3 where White maintains a comfortable advantage. }
2. -- *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "14) Dutch Defense"]
[Black "2...g6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5
{ The Dutch. This is a long-term rival of The London System since this is the only 'viable' setup that does not allow a proper London setup. The lines inside the Dutch are always unconventional due to the nature of the opening, therefore, the reader should be prepared for this.   This is not limited to this repertoire. I have played against Dutch and employed it a few times as Black and the positions are always tricky. However, I believe I have found a simple yet active approach against this where we will keep the London bishop on its favorite square on f4. }
2. Bf4
{ Keeping in tune with the repertoire. Before entering the variations, the reader should understand the setups that Black can employ against this. I will explain this in points:   1@@EndBracket@@ The setup with ...e6. In this case, Black will develop normally via ...Be7-O-O and eventually get the bishop out with ...b6-Bb7 and not push ...d5 and rather go for ...d6 instead. The other setup is the 'Stonewall' dutch with ... e6-d5. This setup is dubious for Black since our London bishop is already out.   2@@EndBracket@@ The setup with ...g6. In this setup, Black aims to go ... Bg7-O-O-d6-Nbd7 and eventually go for the ...e5 push. The approach against this is going to be sharp. We are not allowing this setup to complete and in most cases would strike with h4-h5 at the first opportunity.  3@@EndBracket@@ The setup with ... d6. This is the tricky one. Not because of the lines, but rather the transpositions that come with it. The flexible nature of this setup allows Black to choose between ... e6 and ...g6 and this is what can be complicated. However, the reader should keep in mind that this is going to transpose one or the other.   Let's dig in! }
2... g6
{ This is just bad and the reason should be obvious from the note in the previous move. }
3. h4
{ At the time of writing, there is only one published game in this position. This is absolutely crazy! }
3... Nf6 4. h5 { We do not care about the pawn. Bring the king out! } 4... Nxh5
{ I am only mentioning this move since it requires White to be precise for the next 2-3 moves.  4...Bg7  Makes little sense since White can simply push  5.h6±  And the bishop is forced to retreat, delaying Black's hopes of castling. }
5. Rxh5 gxh5 6. e4 { Threatening mate in one. } 6... d6 7. Qxh5+ Kd7 8. Bc4
{ Controlling the important ...e6 defense after Qxf5+. } 8... c6
{ Only move.  8...e6  allows  9.exf5!+-  followed by fxe6+. Black is dead lost. }
9. Nc3 { Simple development. } 9... Kc7
{ Getting the king away from danger, but not really. } 10. e5 Nd7
{ 10...d5?  loses to  11.e6+  Kb6  12.Na4+  Ka5  13.Bd2+  Kxa4  14.Qe2+-  with a mate to follow. }
11. Nf3 Nb6 12. Bf7 e6 { Intending to push ...d5. } 13. g4
{ Breaking the structure once again. } 13... dxe5
{ 13...fxg4?  loses to  14.exd6  Bxd6  15.Nb5+!+-  with Qc5+ to follow. } 14.
Nxe5
{ Keeping the dark-squared bishop as it is much more important than the h8-rook. }
14... Bd6 15. O-O-O
{ With a clear winning position. White simply has way too many attacking threats that are deadly. Black's passive pieces do not help either. White can continue with gxf5-Rg1 and gain access to the 7th rank. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "14) Dutch Defense"]
[Black "2...g6 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5
{ The Dutch. This is a long-term rival of The London System since this is the only 'viable' setup that does not allow a proper London setup. The lines inside the Dutch are always unconventional due to the nature of the opening, therefore, the reader should be prepared for this.   This is not limited to this repertoire. I have played against Dutch and employed it a few times as Black and the positions are always tricky. However, I believe I have found a simple yet active approach against this where we will keep the London bishop on its favorite square on f4. }
2. Bf4
{ Keeping in tune with the repertoire. Before entering the variations, the reader should understand the setups that Black can employ against this. I will explain this in points:   1@@EndBracket@@ The setup with ...e6. In this case, Black will develop normally via ...Be7-O-O and eventually get the bishop out with ...b6-Bb7 and not push ...d5 and rather go for ...d6 instead. The other setup is the 'Stonewall' dutch with ... e6-d5. This setup is dubious for Black since our London bishop is already out.   2@@EndBracket@@ The setup with ...g6. In this setup, Black aims to go ... Bg7-O-O-d6-Nbd7 and eventually go for the ...e5 push. The approach against this is going to be sharp. We are not allowing this setup to complete and in most cases would strike with h4-h5 at the first opportunity.  3@@EndBracket@@ The setup with ... d6. This is the tricky one. Not because of the lines, but rather the transpositions that come with it. The flexible nature of this setup allows Black to choose between ... e6 and ...g6 and this is what can be complicated. However, the reader should keep in mind that this is going to transpose one or the other.   Let's dig in! }
2... g6
{ This is just bad and the reason should be obvious from the note in the previous move. }
3. h4
{ At the time of writing, there is only one published game in this position. This is absolutely crazy! }
3... Bg7 4. h5
{ We will put immediate pressure on the kingside. The knight on g8 cannot move because of h6! Therefore, Black is already in deep trouble. }
4... d6 5. Nc3 { Threatening to break the center with e4. } 5... Nc6 6. Nf3
{ Defending the pawn and once again, threatening e4. } 6... Nxd4
{ This seems to be the only move that tests White.  6...Nf6  as mentioned earlier, developing the knight allows White to play  7.h6!  Bf8  8.e3±  With a nearly winning position. The idea should be to try and open up the center. For example, if Black tries to play ...e6 then we should strike with d5! }
7. Nxd4 e5 8. Bg5
{ Important resource. We will sacrifice the bishop to deflect the queens attention away from the c7-pawn. }
8... Qxg5 9. Ndb5 Qd8 10. Nd5 { With a winning position. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "14) Dutch Defense"]
[Black "2...Nf6 with 3...g6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5
{ The Dutch. This is a long-term rival of The London System since this is the only 'viable' setup that does not allow a proper London setup. The lines inside the Dutch are always unconventional due to the nature of the opening, therefore, the reader should be prepared for this.   This is not limited to this repertoire. I have played against Dutch and employed it a few times as Black and the positions are always tricky. However, I believe I have found a simple yet active approach against this where we will keep the London bishop on its favorite square on f4. }
2. Bf4
{ Keeping in tune with the repertoire. Before entering the variations, the reader should understand the setups that Black can employ against this. I will explain this in points:   1@@EndBracket@@ The setup with ...e6. In this case, Black will develop normally via ...Be7-O-O and eventually get the bishop out with ...b6-Bb7 and not push ...d5 and rather go for ...d6 instead. The other setup is the 'Stonewall' dutch with ... e6-d5. This setup is dubious for Black since our London bishop is already out.   2@@EndBracket@@ The setup with ...g6. In this setup, Black aims to go ... Bg7-O-O-d6-Nbd7 and eventually go for the ...e5 push. The approach against this is going to be sharp. We are not allowing this setup to complete and in most cases would strike with h4-h5 at the first opportunity.  3@@EndBracket@@ The setup with ... d6. This is the tricky one. Not because of the lines, but rather the transpositions that come with it. The flexible nature of this setup allows Black to choose between ... e6 and ...g6 and this is what can be complicated. However, the reader should keep in mind that this is going to transpose one or the other.   Let's dig in! }
2... Nf6
{ 2...e6  I realize that it is far too early for clickables. But this line will transpose into the ...e6 setup mentioned on move 3. The direct transposition arises after:  3.e3  d5  4.Nf3  Nf6  5.c4  Please refer to the variation with 2...Nf6 3.e3 e6 to go further into this variation. }
3. e3 g6
{ This makes more sense than 2...g6 since the knight on f6 already protects the h5-square. However, it does not stop us from launching an attack. }
4. h4 h6
{ The difference. If not for this move, then we can push h5 anyways as we have seen in the previous variation. }
5. Nc3
{ Getting the knight into action. We are purposefully delaying the development of the g1-knight for the moment because it restricts the view of the d1-queen. }
5... d6 6. Qf3 c6
{ This was tried in the game Sjugirov,S @@StartBracket@@2650@@EndBracket@@ vs Nepomniachtchi,I @@StartBracket@@2729@@EndBracket@@ 2017 1/2-1/ 2. The idea is to get the queen out to a5 to create queenside play. }
7. Bc4
{ This move pretty much refutes ...c6 since the bishop on c4 can defend on the queenside as well as keep the pressure along the a2-g8 diagonal. }
7... d5 8. Bd3
{ Bringing the bishop back to d3 where it can remain active. Since now ...d5 is committed, Black has basically no queenside attacking chances as there is no time! Right now, we are threatening Qg3. }
8... Be6 9. h5 { We have seen this motif before. } 9... g5
{ Is also possible. } 10. Be5
{ Keeping the pressure.  10.Bxb8  looks tempting but allows for  10...g4  11.Qf4  Qxb8  12.Bxf5⩲  and even though the position is still better, I prefer the main move. }
10... Qc8 11. Bxf6 exf6 12. Nge2
{ White will win the pawn anyways via Ng3-Nxf5. } *

