[Round "?"]
[White "14) Dutch Defense"]
[Black "2...Nf6 with 3...e6 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5
{ The Dutch. This is a long-term rival of The London System since this is the only 'viable' setup that does not allow a proper London setup. The lines inside the Dutch are always unconventional due to the nature of the opening, therefore, the reader should be prepared for this.   This is not limited to this repertoire. I have played against Dutch and employed it a few times as Black and the positions are always tricky. However, I believe I have found a simple yet active approach against this where we will keep the London bishop on its favorite square on f4. }
2. Bf4
{ Keeping in tune with the repertoire. Before entering the variations, the reader should understand the setups that Black can employ against this. I will explain this in points:   1@@EndBracket@@ The setup with ...e6. In this case, Black will develop normally via ...Be7-O-O and eventually get the bishop out with ...b6-Bb7 and not push ...d5 and rather go for ...d6 instead. The other setup is the 'Stonewall' dutch with ... e6-d5. This setup is dubious for Black since our London bishop is already out.   2@@EndBracket@@ The setup with ...g6. In this setup, Black aims to go ... Bg7-O-O-d6-Nbd7 and eventually go for the ...e5 push. The approach against this is going to be sharp. We are not allowing this setup to complete and in most cases would strike with h4-h5 at the first opportunity.  3@@EndBracket@@ The setup with ... d6. This is the tricky one. Not because of the lines, but rather the transpositions that come with it. The flexible nature of this setup allows Black to choose between ... e6 and ...g6 and this is what can be complicated. However, the reader should keep in mind that this is going to transpose one or the other.   Let's dig in! }
2... Nf6
{ 2...e6  I realize that it is far too early for clickables. But this line will transpose into the ...e6 setup mentioned on move 3. The direct transposition arises after:  3.e3  d5  4.Nf3  Nf6  5.c4  Please refer to the variation with 2...Nf6 3.e3 e6 to go further into this variation. }
3. e3 e6
{ The solid option. This is the main setup inside the Dutch. If Black has committed ...e6, then it is logical to assume that ... g6 is out of the picture. Therefore, we can continue the development of the g1-knight. }
4. Nf3 d5 { The Stonewall Dutch. } 5. c4 c6 6. Nc3
{ The main setup. There are plenty of games in the database on this position. The computer seems to despise Black's position. I do not feel any different. The reason is that White's London bishop is not locked on c1 and is in play. It seems entirely pointless to create weaknesses along the dark-squares and giving this bishop so much power. }
6... Be7
{ The most popular move. This dives into the heart of the Dutch System. Black's idea is to go ... Ne4 and g5, and it makes sense to to keep the bishop on e7 as opposed to d6 where it can simply be exchanged.   Upon thorough investigation, I have understood one key element - the Stonewall Dutch largely works with fear. The setup with ...g5 can seem a bit scary but if White develops the pieces and follows basic principles, the advantage is fairly easy to attain. }
7. Bd3 O-O 8. h3 Ne4 9. O-O Nd7
{ 9...g5  10.Bh2  Nd7  11.Rc1  transposes to the mainline with 9... Nd7. } 10.
Rc1 { Simple and strong. } 10... g5
{ This might seem a bit scary at first, but remain calm and keep control of the central square on e5. Don't forget that flank attacks usually work if the center is either closed or in control of the person launching the attack. Therefore, as long as White keeps control of e5, there will simply be no attack! }
11. Bh2 Qe8
{ Getting the queen to the attack. Stay calm!  11...h5  might be a little too ambitious.  12.Ne5!  And the h5-pawn is targeted. The attack is simply not there! }
12. Ne2 { Logical. White intends to go Ne5 next and kick the knight with f3. }
12... Qh5 13. Ne5 Nxe5 14. Bxe5
{ White's bishop on e5 is a monster. The queen on h5 seems to be misplaced as there are no pieces to help with the attack. White can potentially go for f4 ideas and completely demolish all hopes of an attack. }
*

