Rc1 { Simple and strong. } 10... Ndf6 { Getting the knight into play. } 11. Ne2
{ Once again, this idea is quite key in these positions. We simply do not allow Black to take on c3 and bring the other knight to e4. }
11... Bd7 12. Qb3 { Attacking the b7-pawn. } 12... Qb6 13. Qc2
{ Clever retreat. We can now launch a queenside advance with a tempo! } 13...
Be8 14. c5 Qd8 15. b4
