{ Extremely important to remember. White wants to exchange the e4-knight with the f3-knight so that the knight on b1 can develop to c3 and help create queenside play with Nb5 ideas. }
9... Nxd2 10. Qxd2 d6 11. Nc3 Nd7 { Logical. } 12. Bh2 Qe8 13. b4
{ This is where we see the importance of the knight on c3. White will threaten a4-a5 and c5 at the same time and Black is unable to play ...a5 because of Nb5! }
13... Qg6 14. f3 a5 { In this case does not work because of } 15. Nb5 Bd8
{ 15...Rac8  drops the pawn with  16.bxa5+- } 16. c5 dxc5 17. bxc5 bxc5 18.
Nxc7 Bxc7 19. Bxc7
{ White has a clear advantage thanks to the double-bishops and the dominance on the dark-squars as a result of it. }
