[Black "Introduction to 1...e6"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppp1ppp/4p3/8/3P4/8/PPP1PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 2"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ The last two chapters are dedicated to first move sidelines. We will start with 1...e6 since it is relatively popular and can be tricky for London players. The idea is that after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppp1ppp/4p3/8/3P4/8/PPP1PPPP/RNBQKBNR w - - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  2.Bf4  Black wants to play  2...c5  and in this case we do not have  3.d5  anymore.   However, there is a drawback of pushing ...e6 too early. Black's bishop on c8 can no longer activate itself on f5 or g4 anymore.  I have recommended @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppp1ppp/4p3/8/3P4/8/PPP1PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Bf4  c5  3.e3  in this chapter where the focus is solely on  3...Qb6  .  Please note that majority of the lines here will transpose. For example, if Black goes @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1p1ppp/4p3/2p5/3P1B2/4P3/PPP2PPP/RN1QKBNR b KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Nf6  then after  4.Nf3  we have a direct transposition to Chapter 11 @@StartBracket@@QID@@EndBracket@@.  Instead of 3... Nf6,  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1p1ppp/4p3/2p5/3P1B2/4P3/PPP2PPP/RN1QKBNR b KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3...d5  also transposes after  4.Nf3  Nf6  5.Nbd2  to Chapter 10 @@StartBracket@@London Mainline@@EndBracket@@.  Therefore, @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1p1ppp/4p3/2p5/3P1B2/4P3/PPP2PPP/RN1QKBNR b KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Qb6  is the critical line that does not transpose. However, our response remains similar. We can simply go  4.Nf3  and allow  4...Qxb2  , after which we can develop with  5.Nbd2  .  This is a very similar position to Chapter 2 @@StartBracket@@6... Qxb2@@EndBracket@@ and White's ideas are fairly similar. In simple terms, White should play Bd3 to play e4 followed by O-O. White gets dynamic play throughout the game thanks to superior development and Black's uncastled king. }
