[Black "Introduction to Sidelines"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/3P4/8/PPP1PPPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ In this chapter, we will deal with first-move sidelines, in particular: 1... c6, 1... g6, 1... c5, 1... b6 and 1... e5. Since there are five different choices, I will explain the approach point by point.   1@@EndBracket@@  1...e5  - Englund Gambit. In this variation, simply take the pawn and defend with Nf3. If Black is persistent to recover the pawn via ...Nc6 and ...Qe7 then we will gladly give up the pawn because Black's queen on e7 is severely misplaced. If Black does not do that, then of course - you have an extra pawn!   2@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/3P4/8/PPP1PPPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1...b6  - Owen's Defense. I have recommended  2.e4  - acquiring the center. It is important to remember that after  2...Bb7  White should be playing 3. Bd3 and not 3. Nc3 because of ...e6 and ...Bb4 idea. Once  3.Bd3  is played, White can focus on castling the king via Nf3-O-O. White controls the center and is way ahead in development, giving a substantial advantage early in the game.   3@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/3P4/8/PPP1PPPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1...c6  - Caro-Kann/Slav. I have recommended  2.Nf3  which transposes after  2...d5  3.Bf4  Nf6  3.e3  to Chapter 7 @@StartBracket@@Slav Defense@@EndBracket@@  4@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/3P4/8/PPP1PPPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1...c5  - Benoni/Old Indian. In this variation, I recommend  2.d5  which already seems quite similar to Chapter 13 @@StartBracket@@Benoni / Benko@@EndBracket@@. The main focus there is  2...e5  which is the Old Indian where White gets a great position after  3.e4  .  The reason is that Black's pawn on c5 now is misplaced, that square is generally reserved for the knight. Furthermore, the c5-pawn also makes the d6-pawn a target in the future, maybe via the f4-exf4-Bxf4 idea.   5@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/3P4/8/PPP1PPPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1...g6  - Modern.  In this variation, I spent a considerable amount of time trying to make 2.Bf4 work, but I was not happy with the result. I decided to go with  2.e4  ,  transposing into Modern. Inside the Modern, I propose the setup with Nf3-h3-Bd3-O-O-c3, keeping our control in the center which provides a lasting advantage. }
