1. d4 e5
{ The Englund Gambit. If your opponent plays this, it is confirmed that they hate the London. So, mission already accomplished! }
2. dxe5 Nc6 3. Nf3 { Simply protecting the pawn. } 3... f6
{ Black tries to provoke an exchange for rapid development. } 4. e4
{ A very strong move! White changes the game into a version of 1. e4 where Black has weakened the f7 point, which is the most vulnerable point, and the light square diagonal around it. }
4... fxe5 5. Bc4
{ White has returned back the pawn, but the current position is very dangerous for Black, with threats like Ng5 to address.  5...Nf6  for example would be met by  6.Ng5  . It isn't going to be easy for Black to continue with his development. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "16) Other First Moves Sidelines"]
[Black "1...e5, the Englund Gambit #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 e5
{ The Englund Gambit. If your opponent plays this, it is confirmed that they hate the London. So, mission already accomplished! }
2. dxe5 Nc6 3. Nf3 { Simply protecting the pawn. } 3... d5
{ An attempt to develop Black's queenside pieces quickly. This line rose to popularity for a short time thanks to GM Andrew Tang. }
4. Bf4 { Developing a piece and overprotecting e5. } 4... Nge7
{ The typical path for any Knight trying to recapture a pawn on e5 after a gambit against 1. d4. }
5. e3 Ng6 6. Bg3
{ e5 is well protected for now and Black cannot add further pressure on e5 as any ...Qe7 would be met by Qxd5. }
6... Be7 7. Nc3
{ With the kingside development almost complete, White develops a piece on the Queenside. The intended location of White's King remains flexible. }
7... Be6 8. Qd2
{ Intending to add pressure on d5. White can either O-O-O or O-O depending on his/her taste and Black's intentions. }
*

