[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "16) Other First Moves Sidelines"]
[Black "1...b6, the Owen's Defense #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 b6
{ The Owen's Defense. This is another dubious setup for White that can simply be punished by taking control of the center. }
2. e4
{ 2.Bf4  This is also possible, I believe the majority of the lines will transpose into QID chapter. For example, if Black goes  2...Bb7  3.Nc3  Nf6  4.f3  is a direct transposition. But if our opponent is giving us the center... why not take it? }
2... Bb7 3. Bd3
{ This move is relatively important to understand. White delays Nc3 on purpose so that Black is unable to go ...e6 and ...Bb4. }
3... e6 4. Nf3 c5
{ This is probably the most challenging line since Black wishes to transpose into a Sicilian hybrid. This is possible if we castle in this position and Black takes on d4. Of course, this is very unnecessary. }
5. d5
{ A positional sacrifice. Black obviously has to take as otherwise White can fix it by going c4 and the bishop on b7 will forever be a bad piece. }
5... exd5 6. exd5 Bxd5 7. Nc3 Be6
{ Only move.  7...Bb7??  Keeping the bishop on the a8-h1 diagonal seems reasonable at first, but Black is completely lost here.  8.Bf4  Nf6  9.Nb5+-  Threatening Nc7 and Nd6+. Black is lost. }
8. Bf4 { Keeping the pieces active. White is now threatening Nb5. } 8... a6
{ 8...Nc6  gives up the exchange with  9.Ba6+-  and Bb7 to follow. } 9. Qe2
{ Preparing to castle long. } 9... Nf6 10. O-O-O Be7 11. Ne5
{ A very strong move. The idea is to carry the attack with g4-g5 in the next few moves. }
11... O-O
{ 11...d6  does not work in this case because of  12.Bc4!  O-O  13.Bxe6  fxe6  14.Nc4+-  and the pawns are starting to fall off. }
12. g4 { With a completely winning position. } *

