[White "16) Other First Moves Sidelines"]
[Black "1...c5 "]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 c5
{ This will most likely transpose into Benko/Benoni chapter the moment Black plays ...Nf6.  1...c6  Black tries to force the Caro-Kann. Not today!  2.Nf3  d5  3.Bf4  Nf6  4.e3  transposes to the Slav Chapter. }
2. d5 e5
{ The Old-Indian. I like to think of this setup as a worse version of the King's Indian since Black's pawn is poorly placed on c5. This not only allows White a simpler breakthrough on the queenside but also prevents Black from going ...Nd7-Nc5 which is an ideal square for the knight.   2...Nf6  transposes after  3.Bf4 }
3. e4 d6 4. Nc3 { Simple developing move. } 4... Be7
{ This is the main idea behind this opening. Black wants to go ...Bg5 and eliminate the dark-squared bishop. }
5. Nf3 { Developing the knight and preventing ...Bg5. } 5... Nf6 6. a4
{ Expanding on the queenside. } 6... O-O 7. Nd2
{ Thematic. This is one of the ways White takes advantage of the pawn on ...c5. The idea is to go Nc4 to fix the queenside, and to attack the kingside. }
7... Ne8 { Clever move. Black anticipates Nc4 and hints at ...Bg5 ideas. } 8.
h4
{ Simply not allowing it. Pushing h4, in this case, does not only equate to White launching an attack since the pawn on h4 does a perfect job of stopping ...Bg5. }
8... Na6 9. Nc4 Nb4 10. Ne3
{ With a great position. White is dominating on both sides of the board. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "16) Other First Moves Sidelines"]
[Black "1...g6, the Modern Defense #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 g6
{ The Modern Defense. After a thorough analysis of  2.Bf4  , I have concluded that going with  2.e4  is far easier to learn. }
2. e4
{ The problem in  2.Bf4  seems to be that Black delays the development of the g8-knight and eventually goes to h6 or e7. The move order is  2...Bg7  3.e3  d6  4.Nf3  Nd7  5.h3  e5  6.Bh2  and now  6...Qe7  followed by ...Nh6 in the next move. The position is not bad for White, but it involves going into unnecessary complications. }
2... Bg7 3. Nf3 { Simple and effective. } 3... c6
{ The second most popular move. This move is aimed against White's plan of going Bc4 by threatening ... d5, but this was never our intention anyways. }
4. h3
{ Simple prophylactic move. It is clear that Black will be pushing ...d5 or ...d6 and h3 is a useful move in both scenarios since it prevents ...Bg4. }
4... d5
{ I think this move is a bit committal for Black. This setup should be compared to the variation that arises after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  g6  2.e4  Bg7  3.Nc3  c6  4.f4  d5  5.e5  .  As you can see, in this setup Black's bishop has more room on the light squares, and more importantly, we have committed f4 which allows the g8-knight to develop via ...h5 and ...Nh6. }
5. e5 { Taking control of the center. } 5... Nh6
{ 5...h5?  is simply not possible anymore since White's pawn is on f2 and can create pressure along the c1-h6 diagonal.  6.Bd3  Nh6  7.O-O  O-O  8.Bf4+-  with the idea of  Qd2  next.   5...f6  6.Bf4  The London bishop is alive even in non-London positions!  6...fxe5  7.dxe5  Nh6  8.Qd2  Nf7  9.Nc3  transposes to 5...Nh6.   6...Nh6  7.Qd2  also transposes to 5...Nh6 }
6. Bf4
{ Essentially provoking ...f6 as otherwise the knight on h6 will have no place to go. }
6... f6 7. Qd2 Nf7 8. Nc3 O-O 9. O-O-O fxe5 10. dxe5
{ White has tremendous attacking possibilities on the kingside. The idea of h4-h5 immediately seems very dangerous. Black on the other hand has little to no play on the queenside. }
*

