1. d4 g6
{ The Modern Defense. After a thorough analysis of  2.Bf4  , I have concluded that going with  2.e4  is far easier to learn. }
2. e4
{ The problem in  2.Bf4  seems to be that Black delays the development of the g8-knight and eventually goes to h6 or e7. The move order is  2...Bg7  3.e3  d6  4.Nf3  Nd7  5.h3  e5  6.Bh2  and now  6...Qe7  followed by ...Nh6 in the next move. The position is not bad for White, but it involves going into unnecessary complications. }
2... Bg7 3. Nf3 { Simple and effective. } 3... c6
{ The second most popular move. This move is aimed against White's plan of going Bc4 by threatening ... d5, but this was never our intention anyways. }
4. h3
{ Simple prophylactic move. It is clear that Black will be pushing ...d5 or ...d6 and h3 is a useful move in both scenarios since it prevents ...Bg4. }
4... d6
{ This is the so called smart move order to not allow us to play Bc4. To be honest, I feel that Bc4 even now is completely fine for White. However, there is a better setup. }
5. Bd3 { Simple developing move. } 5... Nd7 6. O-O e5
{ 6...Ngf6  this variation will transpose the moment Black plays ...e5, which is inevitable.  7.c3  O-O  8.Be3  e5  9.Nbd2  transposes to 6...e5. }
7. c3 { Keeping control over the center. } 7... Ne7
{ Black keeps the option of ...f5 alive. } 8. a4
{ Thematic. The idea is to firstly prevent ...b5 advance from Black and secondly to gain space on the queenside. }
8... O-O 9. dxe5
{ I believe this is an important move to remember. Black's knight on e7 makes it clear that there will be either ...f5 or ...d5 break in order to break the center. This move essentially stops both. Of course, ...d5 is impossible when Black recaptures with the pawn, and ...f5 is also stopped because of Bc4+ ideas. }
9... dxe5 10. Be3 Qc7 11. Nbd2
{ With a fantastic position. White's pieces are much better placed. The idea of expanding on the queenside via a5-b4 is very much alive. The threat of ...f5 is neutralized. A simple plan could be to go a5-b4-Qc2  @@StartBracket@@does not have to be in this order@@EndBracket@@. }
