1. d4 g6
{ The Modern Defense. After a thorough analysis of  2.Bf4  , I have concluded that going with  2.e4  is far easier to learn. }
2. e4
{ The problem in  2.Bf4  seems to be that Black delays the development of the g8-knight and eventually goes to h6 or e7. The move order is  2...Bg7  3.e3  d6  4.Nf3  Nd7  5.h3  e5  6.Bh2  and now  6...Qe7  followed by ...Nh6 in the next move. The position is not bad for White, but it involves going into unnecessary complications. }
2... Bg7 3. Nf3 { Simple and effective. } 3... d6
{ The most popular move. Black intends to go ...Nf6 in the next move now that e5 is dealt with.  3...c5  The third most popular move. In this case, we can simply transpose into Old Benoni structures.  4.d5  d6  5.Nc3  Nf6  6.a4  with a direct transposition to 1... c5. }
4. h3
{ To be honest, there is more than one way to play this position where White maintains a comfortable advantage. I chose this move to keep it aligned with the repertoire. The idea is once again, to prevent ...Bg4. }
4... Nf6 5. Bd3
{ This position is quite similar to 3... c6 with one key difference - the pawn is still on c7. This allows Black an extra option of going ...Nc6. }
5... O-O 6. O-O Nc6 7. c3 { The center is ours! } 7... e5 8. Re1 Re8
{ 8...h6  would allow  9.Be3  Re8  10.Nbd2± } 9. Nbd2
{ Developing the knight with the idea of going Nf1-Ng3. } 9... Bd7
{ This is not the best move in the position, but I chose to include this to show what happens if Black decides to wait. }
10. Nf1 Qe7 11. Ng3 a5 12. Be3
{ The bishop is out, so the problem is solved. The idea now is to go Qd2 next. One important idea I'd like to mention is the possibility of going d5 and continuing with c4-c5. So, it is also possible to prepare for this break and to go Rac1 after Qd2.   The knight on g3 plays an important role in this position. Firstly, it protects the e4-pawn. Secondly, it prevents Black from going ...Nh5 which is a fairly common way to play this position as Black. }
