[SetUp "1"]

{ The following idea is not objectively the best, but I found it to be quite useful in practical games. Black has done all the right things so far. The pieces seem active and the London Bishop is exchanged. Kamsky is known to be one of the best players of London and moves like these display just how well he understands these positions. White to play. }
17. Bb5
{ A very interesting move. White is simply placing the bishop on b5 in order to provoke ...a6. If Black doesn't then the b5-bishop seems rather annoying. }
17... a6 18. Bf1 { Mission accomplished! } 18... Rfe8 19. Qa3
{ Now we see the idea behind the Bb5 maneuver. White simply wants to push a5 and perhaps create a potential target on b7, not to mention the idea of b4-b5 seems quite pleasant. }
19... e5 20. dxe5 Ncxe5 21. a5
{ With a slightly better position due to our superior queenside pawn structure. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
