[SetUp "1"]

{ This is a fairly common position in the London with over 400 games in the database. The position arises from the move order @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.Bf4  Nf6  3.e3  c5  4.c3  in the course, I have recommended 4. Nf3  4...Nc6  5.Nd2  cxd4  5.exd4  Bf5  7.Ngf3  e6  8.Qb3  Qc8  .  White's most popular choice here is a common principle that aims to get rid of Black's active bishop on f5. }
9. Nh4 Be4
{ 9...Bg6?!  This is a worse move in comparison to ...Be4 since White can now capture with the 'less active' knight on h4.  10.Nxg6  hxg6  11.Bd3±  And White has a clearly better position. }
10. Nxe4 Nxe4 11. Nf3 { Bringing the knight back into action. } 11... Bd6 12.
Bxd6 Nxd6 13. Bd3
{ The idea is to go Qc2-Qe2 next and to put pressure on the kingside. However, should Black decide to go long castling then ideas like a4-a5 will be quite dangerous. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
