[Black "Carlsen, Magnus vs. Akobian, Varuzhan, 2017"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r2qrbk1/1b1n1pp1/pp1ppn1p/8/P2P4/2PB1N1P/1P1NQPPB/R3R1K1 w - - 0 15"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ This position might seem similar at first, but there is a minor difference here. Black's bishop is no longer on g7 and has better control over the d6-square. We should also be careful of the ...e5 push. How should White continue? }
15. Nc4
{ 15.a5?  is not as effective because of  15...b5  16.c4  e5∓  And White has to make precise moves to not lose immediately. }
15... Qc7 16. Ne3
{ Mission accomplished. The knight is much better placed on e3. The idea of  16...e5  can simply be met with a quiet move like  17.Nd2  since moves like ...e4 do not pose a threat and only weaken the position further. If Black chooses to do nothing, I quiet like the idea of going Nd2 anyways followed by f3-Ne4 to centralize the other knight as well as put pressure on the d6-pawn. }
16... Nd5 17. Nxd5 Bxd5
{ In this position, White went for the normal-looking move  18.Bxa6??  where Black could have simply recaptured  18...Rxa6  19.Qxa6  Bc4!  with a winning position. }
18. Nd2
{ White keeps the advantage. The idea is once again to either go Nc4-Ne3 or Ne4 straight depending on the position. }
