[SetUp "1"]

{ This is a great position to demonstrate the benefit of having different minor pieces. In this case, it is clear that something needs to exchange because of threats like ...Nxe5 or maybe even ...Nxd4. White has three exchanges possible: 1@@EndBracket@@  9.Nxd7  2@@EndBracket@@  9.Bxc6  3@@EndBracket@@  9.Nxc6  . Can you identify the exchange that is least advantageous to White? }
9. Nxd7
{ 9.Bxc6!  is also fine.  9...Bxc6  10.O-O⩲  White is now simply better because the knight on e5 cannot be challenged by the c6-bishop. Therefore, White's slight advantage will remain for a long time.   9.Nxc6?!  This does not lead to a bad position, but it goes against principles.  9...Bxc6  10.a4!?  White a decent position. However, I feel that it is always better to keep pieces that cannot be exchanged easily. Perhaps the main reason behind this is to keep as many pieces as possible, since Black generally struggles with space in London positions. }
9... Qxd7 10. c3 e6 11. O-O a6 12. Bd3
{ And yet again, White is slightly better in this position because the active bishop on d3 cannot be challenged. }
12... Bd6 13. Bg5
{ This is not entirely necessary, but I prefer keeping the double bishop advantage for now. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Thematic Ideas "]
[Black "Nihal, Sarin vs. Liang, Awonder, 2022"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r2q1rk1/p1n2ppp/1p1bpn2/2pp4/3P4/4PNB1/PPPNQPPP/R4RK1 w - - 0 11"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ In this example, Nihal made a small error which equalized the position. How could he keep the tension? }
11. Bh4
{ Keeping the bishops alive and threatening e4 or c4 ideas.  11.c3?!  happened in the game.  11...Bxg3  12.hxg3  Nce8=  Followed by ...Nd6. Black is quite comfortable here. }
11... cxd4
{ 11...Rc8  can be met with  12.c4!?  and Black needs to be quite precise. }
12. Nxd4
{ Followed by c4 next. The pin on f6 poses practical problems for Black. Moves like ...Be7 are also unpleasant because of Nc6! }
