[SetUp "1"]

{ This example is fairly simple. White to play and win @@StartBracket@@almost@@EndBracket@@. }
11. dxc5 Qxc5 12. Qxb7 { Grabbing the free pawn. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Thematic Ideas "]
[Black "Nihal, Sarin vs. Tang, Andrew, 2020"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r4rk1/pp3ppp/2b1pn2/2q1N3/4B3/2P3P1/PP2QPP1/R3K2R w KQ - 0 16"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ White is faced with a difficult question: should he take with the knight or bishop? }
16. Bxc6
{ 16.Nxc6  was played in the game. The computer seems to favor Bxc6, but I feel what Nihal played is also quite challenging for Black.  16...bxc6  17.Bf3  Keeping the pressure on c6. }
16... bxc6 17. O-O-O
{ This example might be a little confusing since I have been repeating throughout this chapter that it is important to have different minor pieces. However, in this case - there is more at stake. Firstly, the knight on e5 is far superior to the bishop on f3. Secondly, this allows White to have g4-g5 ideas since the e5-knight blocks the queen's view. Finally @@StartBracket@@and perhaps the most important point@@EndBracket@@, the imbalance is already present on the board in the form of an isolated pawn. Therefore, it seems more logical to stick with the basics and exchange the 'less active' piece. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
