[SetUp "1"]

{ The position is symmetrical, Black has control over the c-file. How should White continue? }
17. Ba6
{ Taking the c8-square so Black is not able to double up on the c-file. } 17...
Rc7 18. Rbc1 Rxc1 19. Rxc1 Qd6 20. Nd4
{ And White enjoys a slight advantage because of the c-file. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Thematic Ideas "]
[Black "Sadhwani, Raunak vs. Ghazarian, Kirk, 2021"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1q2rk1/1p1nbpp1/p1n1p2p/3p4/3P1B2/2PB1N1P/PPQ2PP1/R3R1K1 w - - 0 15"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ White is already much better. The bishops on d3 and f4 are in full control of their respective diagonals. Additionally, Black's queen on c8 and the knight on d7 are misplaced at the moment. We have seen examples where Black must challenge the London bishop via ...Bd6 and this is may be the best approach. However, in this position, playing ...Nd7 is a serious mistake since Black's king is now left with no defenders. White to play. }
15. Qd2 { Threatening Bxh6 next. I will call this motif 'The London Gift'. }
15... Re8 16. Bxh6 gxh6 17. Qxh6 Nf8 18. Ng5
{ Bringing the knight into action. Black is completely lost. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Thematic Ideas "]
[Black "Sadhwani, Raunak vs. Jaracz, Pawel, 2022"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "rnbq1rk1/p4ppp/1p1bpn2/2pp4/3P1B2/2PBPN2/PP1N1PPP/R2QK2R w KQ - 0 8"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ Black just played ...b6 to develop the c8-bishop. This move temporarily creates a weakness along the h1-a8 diagonal. How should White exploit this? }
8. Bxd6 Qxd6 9. e4
{ Correct! I should also mention that this motif is mentioned in the mainline of London n a slightly different position. }
9... Qc6 { Strange move. But this does not make any difference for White. } 10.
e5 Ne4 11. Qe2
{ Provoking the knight to take on d2. which is not possible because of Bxh7+. Black probably has to play ...Bb7 instead after which we can simply castle. This is a classic good bishop vs bad bishop scenario. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Thematic Ideas "]
[Black "Sadhwani, Raunak vs. Kezin, Roman, 2022"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1bq1rk1/pp1n1pbp/2n3p1/2ppp3/3P1B2/2P1PN1P/PP1NBPP1/R2Q1RK1 w - - 0 10"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ Black has just pushed ...e5. We have seen examples where the drawback of this move is shown. How should White continue? }
10. dxe5 Ndxe5 11. Nxe5 Nxe5 12. Nf3
{ Offering to trade the knight so that our bishop can go to f3 where it will put pressure on the d5-pawn. }
12... Nc4
{ 12...Nxf3+  13.Bxf3  Be6  14.Qb3±  Followed by Rfd1-Rd2-Rad1 and the d5-pawn will fall. }
13. Bxc4 dxc4 14. Bd6 { Winning the pawn. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Thematic Ideas "]
[Black "Sadhwani, Raunak vs. Levine, Joseph, 2022"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r2qk2r/pppn1ppp/3bpn2/3p1b2/2PP1B2/2N1PN2/PP3PPP/R2QKB1R w KQkq - 0 7"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ Black incorrectly played ...Bd6 in this example. How can we punish this move? }
7. Bxd6 cxd6 8. cxd5 Nxd5 9. Nxd5 exd5 { Creating a long-term weakness. } 10.
Bd3 Qa5+ 11. Qd2 Qxd2+ 12. Kxd2 Bxd3 13. Kxd3
{ We have reached an endgame where only White has chances to win. The doubled d-pawns will be a huge problem for Black. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Thematic Ideas "]
[Black "Sadhwani, Raunak vs. Molina, Rob, 2022"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "rnbqk2r/pp3ppp/4pn2/2pp4/3P1P2/5N2/PPPN1PPP/R2QKB1R w KQkq - 0 7"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ This is an opening example that heavily influences the middlegame. Black has pushed ...c5. White has to choose whether to take the pawn on c5 or maintain the pawn on d4 by going c3 and recapturing with the c-pawn. How should White continue? }
7. dxc5
{ 7.c3  is not wrong, but it wastes unnecessary time for White. The problem is that after  7...cxd4?!  Which is not the best move in this position, Black should instead go for castling or Qc7.  8.Nxd4  Is the best response since recapturing with the d-pawn makes it isolated and a potential target for Black in the future. Therefore, if we have the chance to take the pawn away - we should do it immediately. }
7... Qa5 8. Bd3 { Development first. } 8... Nbd7 9. O-O Nxc5
{ Threatening to play ...Qb4 next. A move such as  10.g3  is completely viable here, but Raunak found a much better way to retain his advantage. }
10. Nb3 { Taking away Black's most active piece. } 10... Qc7 11. Nxc5 Qxc5 12.
c3
{ With a great position. The idea should be to go Qe2-Rfe1-Rad1. The follow-up after that can be to either go g3-h4 or something more concrete such as h3-g4 in order to launch a kingside attack via f5 or g5. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Thematic Ideas "]
[Black "Sadhwani, Raunak vs. Wagner, Dennis,2022 "]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "rnq3k1/pp3pp1/3rpn1p/2pp1b2/3P4/1QP1PN2/PP1NBPPP/R4RK1 w - - 0 12"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ How could White take advantage of Black's misplaced pieces? } 12. dxc5
{ Precise. The queen cannot recapture because of the b7-pawn, so Black is forced to move the rook.   12.Qa3!?  Happened in the game.  12...Nbd7  13.Rac1⩲  White keeps the tension on the c-file and will go for c4 in the next few moves to open up the position. }
12... Rc6 13. Nd4 { 13.c4  is also completely fine. } 13... Rxc5 14. Nxf5 exf5
15. Rfd1
{ Rerouting the rook to focus on the d5-pawn. I should mention that it is not completely necessary to only play against this pawn and White should also be looking for an opportunity to push c4!? at the right moment to activate the e2-bishop. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Thematic Ideas "]
[Black "Sadhwani, Raunak vs. Wu, Christopher, 2022"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r3kb1r/pp3ppp/1qn1pn2/2pp3b/3P1B2/1QP1PN1P/PP1N1PP1/R3KB1R w KQkq - 0 9"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ This position is fairly similar to Slav which comes from the move order @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.c4  c6  3.Nf3  Nf6  4.e3  Bg4  5.h3  Bh5  6.Nc3  e6  7.Qb3  Qb6  . The big difference is that our dark @@StartBracket@@London@@EndBracket@@ bishop is out. In both scenarios, White can go for the same idea. }
9. Nh4
{ Thematic. The point is to push g4 next and capture the g6-bishop to create an imbalance.  9.Qxb6  Is another @@StartBracket@@quite popular@@EndBracket@@ way to go.  9...axb6  10.Bb5  Taking control of the outpost and aiming for Ne5 next. Black has to play  10...Nd7  And here we can go for  11.a4!?  And White maintains a superior endgame. There are different ways to proceed:   1@@EndBracket@@ dxc5-e4 immediately   2@@EndBracket@@ O-O-Rfe1 and then look for e4 ideas.   3@@EndBracket@@ O-O-g4-h4 to gain space on the kingside. }
9... Be7
{ 9...c4  is a thematic idea to provoke Qxb6, but since our knight is already on h4 - Black cannot go ...Bg6 anymore. So we can simply retreat with  10.Qc2⩲  With the idea of g4 next. }
10. g4 Bg6 11. Nxg6 hxg6 12. Bg2
{ With a slight advantage thanks to the double bishops.  12.dxc5!?  is also interesting since after  12...Bxc5  13.Bg2⩲  The position is more open in comparison to the game, and provides a better chance of c4 breakthrough. This does not need to be immediate, White can always go for O-O and maybe something along the lines of g5 and h4 to better prepare for the c4 break since the knight on f6 is not centralized. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Thematic Ideas "]
[Black "Carlsen, Magnus vs. Ding Liren, 2020"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1b1k2r/pp3ppp/1qn1pn2/3p4/3N1P2/2PB4/PPQ2PPP/RN2K2R w KQkq - 0 10"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ This example is between World no.1 & 2. The reader should already be able to identify that White has a superior pawn structure. However, there is tension in the center because of the d4-knight. How did Magnus retain his advantage? }
10. Nf3
{ Thematic. Magnus retreats the knight and keeps control over the e5 square so that Black is not able open up the position. }
10... O-O 11. O-O Bd7 12. Nbd2 Rac8 { Threatening ...Nb4. } 13. a3 { Simple. }
13... Rfd8 14. Rfe1
{ Activating the rook and gaining more control over the e5-square. } 14... h6
15. Ne5
{ 15.Nb3  is liked by the computer. The idea is to go Nbd4 and to try for the f5-push. }
15... Nxe5
{ This feels logical, but is in fact a mistake.  15...Ne7  with the idea of ...Bb5 was perhaps better. But White nevertheless maintains a slightly better position due to central superiority. }
16. fxe5 Ne8 17. Nf3
{ With a close to winning position. The problem is that Black cannot play ...Bb5 anymore because of  18.Bh7+  followed by  19.a4  to kick the bishop away. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Thematic Ideas "]
[Black "Carlsen, Magnus vs. Ding Liren, 2020"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "rn1q1rk1/pbp1bppp/1p2pn2/3p2B1/3P4/3BPN2/PPPNQPPP/R3K2R w KQ - 0 9"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ This example demonstrates the need for ...Nbd7. Since Blac has not played this move yet, how did Magnus take advantage? }
9. Bxf6 Bxf6 10. h4
{ Threatening Ng5 next. This will inevitably provoke ...h6 that provides a hook for a future kingside attack. }
10... Nd7 11. Ng5 h6 12. f4
{ 12.Nh7  Re8  13.Nxf6+  Nxf6  14.g4±  is also perfectly fine. } 12... c5 13.
c3 Be7 14. g4 { With a deadly attack to follow. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Thematic Ideas "]
[Black "Carlsen, Magnus vs. Ghaem Maghami, Ehsan, 2016"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r3k2r/pp1b1ppp/2nqpn2/1Bpp4/3P4/2P1PNP1/PP1N1PP1/R2QK2R w KQkq - 0 10"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ The London Bishop is exchanged, and White does not have control over the e5-square. White to play. }
10. Bxc6 Bxc6
{ It should be mentioned that  10...bxc6  changes the idea since we can also put pressure on the c5-square. This can be done with  11.Nb3  Ne4  12.Nfd2  Nxd2  13.Qxd2  cxd4  14.cxd4±  With a great position thanks to Black's bad bishop and the outpost on c5. }
11. Ne5 { Grabbing the e5-square. } 11... Qc7 12. Qf3
{ Getting the queen into action.  12.g4  is also fine. } 12... h6 13. Qf4
{ Protecting the knight and threatening dxc5. } 13... Qe7 14. g4 Nh7 15. Qg3
{ With a very comfortable game. Black should obviously not castle on the kingside, and going O-O-O does not seem very pleasant either. }
