1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 d5 3. Bf4 c5 4. e3 Nc6 5. Nbd2
{ 5.c3  is of course not right because of  5...Qb6  6.Qb3  c4  7.Qc2  Bf5!  where Black has a great position. }
5... Qb6 6. dxc5 Qxb2 7. Rb1 Qc3
{ Other queen moves are also possible, but less played. The queen on c3 is generally considered to be best because it prevents the c2-c4 breakthrough. }
8. Bb5 g6
{ The modern approach. The most popular move in this position is  8...e6  instead. }
9. e4 dxe4
{ 9...Bg7?  ignoring the pawn break is not smart for Black. This is because of  10.Be5!  Qxc5?  11.Bd4+-  and ...Qd6 would allow e5. If the queen moves to a3, then we can simply capture exd5. }
10. Be5 Qa5
{ 10...Qxc5?  allows White to gain a crucial tempo.  11.Bxf6  exf6  12.Nxe4  Qe7  13.O-O  +-  with Re1 to follow. It should be noted that Black cannot move the f8-bishop because of Nd6+ which would disrupt Black's castling. }
11. O-O exf3
{ 11...Bg7?  simply loses to  12.Nc4!  and the queen is out of good squares.  12...Qd8  13.Qxd8+  Kxd8  14.Rfd1+  Ke8  15.Nd4+-  with a winning position. }
12. Bxc6+
{ This is the mainline in the theoretical chapters, but we have also proposed two other alternatives to choose from. They are:  12.Qxf3  and  12.Nc4  . }
12... bxc6 13. Qxf3 Nd5 14. Bxh8 Qxd2 15. c4 f6 16. Rfe1
{ This is the first deviation from the theoretical chapters. The recommendation in the course is  16.Rfd1!?  instead. }
16... Kf7 17. cxd5 Qxd5
{ 17...cxd5?!  allows White to take advantage with:  18.Qb3±  threatening Rd1. }
18. Qc3 Be6 19. Qe3 Bf5 20. Rbd1 Qxa2
{ Perhaps the first inaccuracy by Wesley.  20...Qe6  was more precise in this case. }
21. h3 { Threatening g4 next. } 21... h5 22. Qf3 Kg8
{ This is where things started to go wrong for Wesley.  22...Qa4  was perhaps a bit more precise since it does not allow g4.   22...Rc8?  would just allow  23.g4!  hxg4  24.hxg4  Be6  25.g5±  and the bishop on h8 finds freedom. }
23. g4 hxg4 24. hxg4 Bc2 25. Rd7 Kxh8
{ A big mistake that allows a nice tactic.   25...Qc4  is the best move according to the engine. The idea is that after  26.Rexe7  Bxe7  27.Rxe7  Black has  27...Rd8!  28.Bxf6  Rd3=  and Black manages to escape! }
26. Rexe7 Qa1+
{ 26...Bxe7  does not help because of  27.Rxe7+-  and now White has the threat of Qxf6 and Qh3+. Black is not in time to save both. }
27. Kh2 g5 28. Qxc6 Rb8 29. Qc7 Qb1 30. Rd8 Rxd8 31. Qxd8 Kg8 32. Re8 *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
