[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Le, Quang Liem vs. Shankland, Samuel, Saint Louis (blitz) 2021"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Bf4 c5 4. e3 Nc6 5. Nbd2 Qb6 6. dxc5 Qxb2 7. Rb1 Qc3 8.
Bb5 g6 9. e4
{ With White's lead in development, it is natural to try and open up the position. }
9... a6 { 9...dxe4  10.Be5  Qa5  11.O-O  goes into the mainline. } 10. Bxc6+
bxc6 11. Be3 { Protecting the c5-pawn and preparing to play Bd4. } 11... dxe4
12. Bd4 Qa5 13. O-O { A sacrifice in accordance with the mainline. } 13... Bh6
{ This move deviates from the theoretical chapters where I have analyzed  13...exf3  . Now, White is simply winning! }
14. Nc4 Qd8 15. Nfe5 O-O
{ An attempt to defend the c6-pawn with  15...Bd7  also loses after  16.Nxd7  16...Qxd7  17.Nb6+- }
16. Nb6 { The rook is now trapped. } 16... Be6 17. Nxa8
{ 17.Nxc6  was perhaps a bit quicker.  17...Qc7  18.Bxf6  Qxc6  19.Bxe7+-  And one of the rooks will fall. }
17... Qxa8
{ White is completely winning here, but the rest of the game is topsy-turvy, as it is a blitz game. }
18. Rb6 { 18.c3+-  With the idea of Qa4 was much simpler. } 18... Nd5
{ A very strong counter-resource, exploiting the fact that after } 19. Rxc6 Bg7
{ The White Rook is trapped. } 20. Rxe6 fxe6
{ The position is still better for White, but hard to play - especially in blitz. White still managed to win somehow! }
21. Qg4
{ 21.Ng4⩲  Despite the blunder, White still retains a slightly better position due to the better pawn structure. }
21... Nf4 { Now White has some concrete problems to solve. } 22. c6 h5 23. Qg5
{ 23.Qd1  Rd8  White loses a piece here. } 23... Ne2+ 24. Kh1 Nxd4 25. Nxg6
Nxc6 26. Nxf8 Qxf8 27. Qxh5 { After a mess, we are still in a mess... } 27...
Nd4 28. Qd1 Qf4 29. c3 Nf5 30. g3
{ For now, White just pushes Black's pieces back. } 30... Qe5 31. Qe2 Qd5 32.
Rd1 Qc6 33. Rd8+ Kf7 34. Kg1 { White's King safety has stablized for now. }
34... Qxc3 35. Qxe4 Bd4 36. Qe2
{ White's King is safe and it is Black's King who is in danger now. } 36... Kf6
37. Rf8+ Kg7 38. Rd8 Kf6 39. Rf8+ Kg7 40. Rb8
{ White doesn't want to repeat as the position is practically easier to play as White. }
40... Kf6 41. Rb3 Qc7 42. Qxa6
{ An important pawn, as this helps create a dangerous outside passed pawn. }
42... Qc2 43. Rf3 Kg5 44. Qxe6
{ Now Black's position is falling apart completely. } 44... Bf6 45. h4+ Kg6 46.
Rf4 Qc1+ 47. Kh2 Qc2 48. Qe4
{ The position has been clarified after a lot of complexities. Black is forced to trade the Queen now. White has too many pawns. }
48... Qxe4 49. Rxe4 Nd6 50. Rb4 Bc3 51. Rb3 Bd4 52. Kg2 e5 53. a4 Ne4 54. f3
Nc5 55. Rb4 Nd3 56. Rc4 Ne1+ 57. Kh3 Nxf3 58. a5 e4 59. Kg2 Kf5 60. a6 Be3 61.
Rc7 Ne1+ 62. Kf1
{ This game had a lot of topsy-turvy moments, characteristic of a blitz game. However, White was winning after just 15 moves, which shows how dangerous the variation can be for Black! }
