[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Berkes, Ferenc vs. Forcen Esteban, Daniel, Online 2020"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Bf4 c5 4. e3 Nc6 5. Nbd2 Qb6 6. dxc5 Qxb2 7. Rb1 Qc3 8.
Bb5 e6 9. O-O Be7 10. e4 O-O 11. e5 Nd7 12. Nb3 Qb4 13. Nfd4 Nxd4 14. Nxd4 Qxc5
15. Re1 Rd8
{ In the theoretical chapter, I have mentioned  15...a6  .  The idea of ...Rd8 is a bit slow in this position, and White correctly punishes this inaccuracy. }
16. h4
{ When in doubt - push the h-pawn! White plans to push h5 and provoke ...h6 which makes the idea of Qg4-Rb3-Rg3 much more dangerous. }
16... Bxh4 17. Rb3
{ White makes use of the opening up of the h-file. With Black's Queenside pieces frozen on the Queenside, White's attack is quite dangerous. }
17... Nf8 18. Rh3 Be7 19. Bd3
{ Black's position is already looking quite scary. } 19... g6
{ An understandable defensive move. However, this also weakens all the dark squares around Black's King. }
20. Nf3
{ Jumping directly into it. The idea is not just focussed on the g5 square, but also on the weakened f6 and h6 squares. The White Knight can access it from g4. }
20... Bd7 21. Bg5
{ 21.Nh2+-  With the idea of Ng4. This was slightly stronger. } 21... Bxg5 22.
Nxg5 Qb4 23. Ree3 { The other rook joins the party. } 23... Qf4 24. Rhg3
{ Defending g5 and threatening Rg4 since the queen will be trapped! } 24... Qh4
25. Qf3 Be8 26. Bb5 { Classic 'removing the defender'. } 26... Bxb5 27. Qxf7+
{ And White won the game in a few moves. } 27... Kh8 28. Qf6+ Kg8 29. Rh3 Qxh3
30. Rxh3 Rd7 31. Rf3
{ A very strong game by White! showing how easy it is to lose as Black with the slightest inaccuracy. }
