[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Hauchard, Arnaud vs. Sarana, Alexey, Online 2021"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 d5 3. Bf4 c5 4. e3 Nc6 5. Nbd2 Qb6 6. dxc5 Qxb2 7. Rb1 Qa3 8.
Bb5 g6 9. Ne5 Qxc5 10. c4 Bg7 11. Qa4 dxc4 12. Bxc4 a6 13. Bxf7+
{ A very understandable move in a blitz game. In the theoretical chapter, I have proposed an improvement over this move:  13.Nb3!  However, just going over these examples increases our cache of patterns in our memory. This enhances our strategic understanding and tactical arsenal. }
13... Kf8 14. Nxc6 Qxc6
{ Black misses the equalizer. The position is now clearly better for White thanks to the weakness on c6.  14...Bd7!  was much stronger, but how many people would play this in a blitz game? }
15. Qxc6 bxc6 16. Bc4
{ Black's pawn structure is a mess. Black's pieces are woefully under-coordinated. }
16... Nd5 17. Bg3 Be6
{ This just blunders a piece. The position was quite bad for Black anyways, but Black could have resisted much better. }
18. e4 Nc3 19. Bxe6 Nxb1 20. Nxb1
{ White has a completely winning position now. } 20... Bd4 21. Ke2
{ Centralizing the king, one of the basic principles of endgame play. } 21...
c5 22. Nd2 { The Knight heads towards the outpost on c4. } 22... Kg7 23. Bd5
{ The White Bishops ensure that the Black Rooks can never get on the b-file. }
23... Ra7 24. Nc4 Re8 25. Rb1
{ Taking control of the b-file, after ensuring that the Black Rooks cannot challenge the White Rook. }
25... e6 26. Bc6 Rf8 27. f3 a5 28. a4
{ Preventing any hint of counterplay and fixing the a-pawn. } 28... Bc3 29. Bf2
Bb4 30. Rxb4 { It is time to finish! } 30... axb4 31. Bxc5
{ White has gone into an endgame with an outside a-passer. This pawn also has some kind of a fast track toward promotion, with White's minor pieces escorting it. The White King takes care of Black's b-pawn quite easily. }
31... Rc8 { Trying to fight on, eliminating the light-squared Bishop. } 32.
Bxa7 Rxc6 33. Bd4+ Kg8 34. Kd3
{ The White king is too close and the Black king is too far. } 34... b3 35. a5
e5 36. Bxe5 Rc5 37. Bd4 Rb5 38. a6
{ It is quite trendy to play on these days without resigning, but this position is too hopeless even for today's times. This game shows how this variation is so much easier to play as White practically. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
