[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Tabatabaei, Mohammad Amin vs. Narayanan, Srinath, Chess.com 2021"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 d5 3. Bf4 c5 4. e3 Nc6 5. Nbd2 Qb6 6. dxc5 Qxc5 7. c4
{ In the course, I recommend  7.a3  before going c4. However, in terms of thematic play, this reaches a setup similar to that of the course. }
7... g6 8. Rc1 Bg7 9. a3
{ We reach a similar position to the course, but White has committed Rc1, which not only wastes a tempo but also allows ...Qa5 which blocks the b4 break. }
9... dxc4
{ 9...Qa5=  Stopping b4. This would have equalized the game. If I had studied the London LTR before this game, I would have certainly been able to find this! realizing how dangerous the ideas with b4, c5 are. }
10. Bxc4 Qb6 11. b4
{ Planning Qb3 soon to attack the f7-pawn. White's position seems fantastic now! }
11... O-O
{ Black missed his chance.  11...Nh5⩲  Although after O-O, the position is still slightly better for White, but by removing the London Bishop, Black's pieces have more freedom since the dark squares are not available. }
12. h3
{ A typical prophylactic move in the London. Now ...Nh5 is not a threat anymore. }
12... Bf5 13. O-O
{ I initially evaluated this position as okay for Black. However, pretty soon I started to struggle to make a move. }
13... Rac8 14. Qb3 h6 15. g4
{ A typical motif in London, especially in this structure where Black suffers from lack of space. Expanding on the kingside and restricting Black any activity. }
15... Bd7 16. Rfd1 h5 { Trying to hit out against the pressure. } 17. g5
{ 17.Ng5+-  should also be winning. } 17... Ne8 18. Kg2 e5 19. Bg3 Nd6
{ I managed to get some pieces out, but the problems and the pressure remain. }
20. Bd5 { Making use of the outpost. } 20... a5 21. Nc4 Nxc4 22. Bxc4 axb4
{ The pressure became unbearable and I start to lose the plot completely. } 23.
Rxd7 Na5 { The point. Trying to trade some pieces. } 24. Bxf7+ Kh8 25. Qxb4
{ Simple and concrete. White doesn't care about the rook and instead wins everything else on the board. }
25... Qxb4 26. axb4 Rxc1 27. bxa5
{ White has two minor pieces for the rook. Black's pieces are uncoordinated and all the pawns are weak. }
27... e4 28. Nh4 Ra8 29. Nxg6+ Kh7 30. Nh4 Rxa5
{ The position was so disgusting that I couldn't bear to look at it anymore and resigned. An excellent example of the pressure that can arise in a typical London system position. }
*

