[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4 d5 3. e3 c5 4. Nf3 Nc6 5. Nbd2 Qb6 6. dxc5 Qxc5 7. a3 Bg4 8.
c4 e5 9. Bg5 Ne4
{ This is the deviation from the theory where I mention  9...e4  as the best response. }
10. b4 { Removing the queen to take the pawn on d5. } 10... Qb6
{ 10...Qd6  does not help much either because of  11.cxd5  Qxd5  12.Bc4  Qxd2+!  13.Nxd2  Bxd1  14.Nxe4±  With a great position thanks to actively placed pieces. }
11. cxd5 Nxg5 12. dxc6 bxc6 13. Be2 Nxf3+ 14. Bxf3 Bxf3 15. Qxf3
{ The position has liquidated, but White is now close to winning because of the weak pawn on c6. }
15... Rd8 16. Rc1 Rd5
{ Black tries to defend the c6-pawn for now, but cannot hold on to it for too long. }
17. Nc4 Qd8 18. O-O Be7 19. Na5
{ The inevitable moment arises and the c6-pawn falls. } 19... c5 20. Nc6 Qd7
21. Nxe7
{ Forcing Black to move his King, and rendering him unable to castle. } 21...
Kxe7 22. bxc5
{ 22.Rxc5  Rxc5  23.bxc5+-  was a bit more precise since Black does not have an active rook on the open file anymore. The little nuggets of technique! }
22... Rc8 23. Qe4 g6 24. Qb4 Qc6
{ The c5-pawn falls. However, Black's King is still endgangered and there are other pawns on the board. }
25. Rfd1
{ 25.Qh4++-  Followed by Qxh7 would have kept the advantage. Black will not have time to take on a3. }
25... Rxd1+ 26. Rxd1 Qxc5 27. Qh4+ Ke6 28. Qxh7 Qc2
{ 28...Qxa3  29.Qh3+  f5  Would have resisted better, but the position looks quite dangerous with the Black King exposed. Stockfish evaluates it as equal, but the human evaluation index would be spooked at the position of the Black's King. }
29. Qh3+ Kf6 30. Qf3+ Kg7 31. h4
{ White emerges a pawn up from all the mess. The Black king looks safer, but isn't yet totally risk-free. }
31... e4 32. Qg4 Rc7 33. Rd4 { Threatening to go up by two pawns. } 33... Qc1+
34. Kh2 Qxa3
{ Black finally takes this pawn, but it is probably too little too late. } 35.
Qxe4 Qc5 36. Rd5 Qc6 37. Qe5+ Kh7 38. Rd8
{ And in the end, the king also falls! } 38... f6 39. Qd4
{ Black's position collapses. There is no defense against Rd6 which would hit the f6 pawn. The Black king loses all its pawn cover.  Although this was a blitz game with a lot of mistakes, it showed us instructive moments where White's technique could have been better.   It is also quite possible to train and make better decisions even with limited time. @@StartFEN@@7r/p2qkppp/8/2prp3/1P6/P3PQ2/5PPP/2R2RK1 w - - 0 22@@EndFEN@@  22.Rxc5  was an example of that decision. }
