[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Le, Quang Liem vs. Gevorgyan, Maria, Chess.com 2020"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 c5 3. e3 Nf6 4. Nd2 Nc6 5. Ngf3 Bf5 6. Bb5 Qb6 7. c4 a6
{ This wastes a crucial tempo. Black should have played  7...e6  instead to focus on kingside development. }
8. Bxc6+ bxc6 9. Qa4
{ 9.dxc5!  Qxc5  10.O-O  Would have kept a substantial advantage. The c6-pawn will be taken sooner or later! }
9... Bd3
{ Temporarily blocks castling but the bishop can be kicked away!  9...cxd4!  this was better. Since after  10.O-O!  is perhaps stronger. But hard to play over the board. However, we do have a line with a similar theme in our repertoire. Studying such patterns makes finding such ideas easier.  10...dxe3  11.Bxe3  Qb7  12.Rac1=∞  With compensation. White can still put pressure on the c6-pawn.   10.exd4  is natural, but Black gets a good position now, after  10...dxc4  11.Nxc4  Qb5⩱  Black is already much better! }
10. Ne5 { Evicting the Bishop from d3 and attacking the c6 pawn as well. }
10... dxc4 11. Ndxc4 Bxc4 12. Qxc4 { Attacking both f7 and c5 at once. } 12...
cxd4
{ This is almost suicidal.  12...e6  would have certainly resisted better.  13.dxc5  Bxc5  14.O-O  White has a completely better position due to Black's pawn structure, but Black can still keep the game on. }
13. Qxf7+ { White blasts the Black King's cover open. } 13... Kd8 14. O-O
{ The Black King is exposed and Black's pieces are undeveloped and woefully uncoordinated. White has won the game straight out of the opening. }
14... c5 15. exd4 cxd4 16. Rac1
{ White goes after Black's King, with half of Black's pieces not even developed yet! }
16... Rc8 17. Bd2 e6 18. Rxc8+ Kxc8 19. Rc1+ Kb8
{ The Black King has managed to move away from the center, but is not safer in any way! }
20. Bf4 { Threatening to setup a discovered attack. } 20... Bd6 21. Qxe6 Rd8
22. Nc6+ { The finish. White just starts to collect material. } 22... Qxc6 23.
Rxc6 Bxf4 24. Rb6+ Ka7 25. Rxa6+ Kb7 26. Qc6+ Kb8 27. Ra8#
{ The pressure created by the Bishop on the a4-e8 diagonal is quite unpleasant and effective. It is not totally surprising that Black's position disintegrated so quickly. }
