[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Tristan, Leonardo vs. Melkumyan, Hrant, Chess.com 2022"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ 1.d4  d5  2.Bf4  Nf6  3.e3  c5  4.Nf3  Nc6  5.Nbd2  cxd4  6.exd4  Bg4  7.c3  e6  We reach this position from London through this move-order. }
1... c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. Bf4 Nf6 5. Nf3 Nc6 6. Nbd2 Bg4 7. c3 e6 8. Qb3
Qc8 9. Bd3
{ Once again, this opening transposes to London as we saw in the previous game. }
9... Be7 10. O-O O-O 11. Rae1
{ This is one of the typical ways to play with White in this structure. Although we play  11.Rfe1  in the theory part, the ideas and themes in this structure are similar. }
11... a6 12. Ne5 { The ideal place for the Knight in this setup. } 12... Bh5
13. Qc2 Bg6 14. Re3
{ Essentially gives up the advantage. In this case, White can simply take the bishop on g6 and create a potential hook.   14.Nxg6!  hxg6  15.Nf3±  With a clearly better position. The follow-up should be to play h4 sometime soon and maybe g3-Kg2-Rh1-h5 ideas. If White had studied this London LTR, they would have trained in this concept! }
14... Bxd3
{ 14...Nxe5!  15.dxe5  Nh5⩱  This only works because White's bishop has nowhere to go! }
15. Qxd3 g6 16. Bg5
{ Creating pressure on the kingside. An effective, direct method in a blitz game. }
16... Qc7 { Preventing the e3 rook from moving. } 17. Rfe1
{ Overprotecting e5 and freeing the e3 rook. } 17... Rfe8
{ Preparing ...Nxe5 by defending e7. } 18. Rf3 Nxe5
{ Black has to trade this knight to release some of the pressure. } 19. dxe5
Nd7 20. Bxe7 Rxe7 21. Qd4
{ At the end of the complications, White has a strong pawn on e5, which helps gain space on the kingside. The f6 knight has been kicked away. }
21... Rc8 22. Qh4 Nf8 23. Rf4
{ Keeping an eye on f7 and freeing the f3 square for the knight. } 23... Qd8
24. Nf3 Rec7
{ Black tries to trade some of the heavy pieces to release the pressure, and also prepares some counter play on the queenside. }
25. Qh6 Rc4 26. Nd4
{ Politely refusing the offer to trade, but at the cost of one of the attacking pieces being deflected away. }
26... b5
{ A natural way to try and get counter-play on the Queenside.  26...Qb6!  Would have been quite strong, forcing White to trade the rook or give up material.  27.Nb3   27.Re2  Rxc3-+  23...Rxf4  28.Qxf4  Rc4⇆  White's knight is misplaced and White's initiative is quelled. }
27. a3
{ An effective defensive move, stopping Black's counter-play on the queenside. }
27... Rb8 28. h4 { White's attack is faster! } 28... a5 29. h5 b4 30. axb4 axb4
31. Re3
{ Defending c3 and bringing another piece into the attack. Black is strongly outnumbered on the kingside. Black's counter-play on the kingside isn't fast enough. }
31... bxc3 32. bxc3 Rbc8
{ 32...Rb1+  wouldn't help much as the white king hides away safely on h2.  33.Kh2  The king is quite safe here. }
33. Rh3 Rxc3 { Black manages to break through on the queenside, but.... } 34.
hxg6
{ Black isn't fast enough. Black won a pawn by breaking through on the queenside. But White breaks through to Black's king. }
34... Rxh3 35. gxf7+
{ With this key intermezzo, Black's kingside defense falls. } 35... Kh8 36.
Qxh3 Qg5 37. Rg4
{ Breaking through and getting towards Black's king via the g-file. } 37...
Rc1+ 38. Kh2 Qxe5+ 39. f4
{ Attacking the queen and threatening Rg8. Black has to give up the queen. }
39... Qg7 40. Rxg7 Kxg7
{ White is just a queen up with a pawn on f7. Black understandably resigned. The game did contain a few mistakes but also illustrated well how dangerous White's initiative is on the kingside in this setup. }
