[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Duda, Jan Krzysztof vs. Cori, Jorge Moise, Online 2021"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 Nf6 3. e3 c5 4. Nd2 Nc6 5. Ngf3 cxd4 6. exd4 Bf5 7. Bb5 Qb6 8.
c4 a6
{ This is a very natural move to make as Black in this position, considering the pressure on this diagonal. However, it turns out to be an immediate inaccuracy.   8...dxc4  9.a4  Bd3  10.Ne5  Is the direction of our theory chapter, which was also played in the recent Caruana-Abdusattorov game from the Olympiad. }
9. Bxc6+ bxc6 10. Qb3
{ 10.O-O!  Was perhaps a bit more precise since the b2-pawn cannot be taken.  10...e6  11.Ne5  Be7  12.c5!  With a winning position due to the weakness of the c6-pawn and Black's light square bishop.   10...Qxb2  11.Qa4  Qb7  12.Rab1!  This is the point which was perhaps difficult to foresee from far.  12...Bxb1  13.Rxb1  Qc8   13...Qd7  14.Ne5+-  Black's King's defense falls apart.  14.Rb6+-  Black's king is indefensible because Black cannot get the Queen to d7, due to White's knight coming to e5. }
10... Nd7
{ An important defensive move! the e5-square is very important, with White's prospects of Ne5 and the Black pawn on c6. }
11. O-O e6 12. c5
{ White's idea is similar to the variation we saw with 10. O-O, but it is not as effective with the Black Knight on d7. }
12... Qxb3 13. axb3
{ This is a practically better endgame for White due to the weakness of Black's queenside pawns. Also, the White's bishop is quite useful on f4, not letting any Black piece come on to b8. Black is not able to cover this with either ...e5 or bring a bishop in between. }
13... Bd3 14. Rfe1 Be7 15. Re3 Bb5
{ The Black's bishop is holding together Black's queenside. However, the bishop is not stable on b5. }
16. Nb1
{ A strong idea, getting into the heart of the position instantly and targetting the b5-bishop. }
16... O-O 17. Nc3 Rfe8 18. g4
{ An useful move that simply gains space. This also helps create a second front. With Black doomed to passivity on the queenside, Duda starts to create a parallel target on the kingside. }
18... h6 19. h4 Nf8 20. Bg3
{ Anticipating Ng6 and preventing any counter-play related ideas linked towards that. }
20... f6
{ Black tries to release some pressure with some pawn breaks, but this only weakens Black's position further. However, this is understandable. With the Black pieces unable to move, Black's position is quite difficult to play, similar to my game against Tabatabei. }
21. b4 { Improving White's position further. } 21... g5 22. Ra5
{ Preparing to take concrete action. White threatens Nxb5 followed by Rea3. }
22... gxh4 23. Nxh4 Bc4 { The only move. Black cannot let White take Nxb5. }
24. Na4 Bd8 25. Nb6
{ Quite effective and powerful! If the White pawn comes to b6, it would be unstoppable as the White's dark square bishop guides it toward promotion. }
25... Bb5
{ The immense pressure provokes a blunder, much like my game against Tabatabei. }
26. Rxb5 axb5
{ 26...Bxb6  doesn't help as White can capture with the Rook.  27.Rxb6+- } 27.
Nxa8 f5 28. Nxf5
{ Duda doesn't leave a chance to show his tactical brilliance. } 28... Bg5
{ Black attacks both the White rook and the knight, but White can counter with }
29. Nc7 Bxe3 30. Nxe8 { White's knight is attacked, but so is Black's bishop. }
30... Bd2 31. Nfd6 Bxb4 32. Bf4
{ White emerges a piece up after the concrete lines. Black understandably resigns. }
