[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Aronian, Levon vs. Erigaisi, Arjun Kumar, Tata Steel India (blitz) 2021"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4 d5 3. e3 Bf5 4. Bd3 Bxd3 5. cxd3
{ An important idea! I learned the effectiveness of this cxd3 structure and the pressure it can create for Black primarily from this game. }
5... e6 6. Qb3
{ In the course, I have recommended  6.Nc3  followed by Qb3 afterward. However, this is also an effective test practically. }
6... b6
{ Black commits an inaccuracy right away. Committing b6 weakens Black's queenside, which can be used by White later to create pressure.   6...Qc8  was better, not committing on the queenside. However, this is not a very natural move to make in a blitz game. }
7. Nc3 Bd6 8. Bg3
{ A practically inconvenient chess from Black's perspective. This does not simplify the position and keeps Black guessing.  8.Bxd6  Qxd6  9.Nf3  Is mentioned in Chapter 8 where White gets a slightly better position. }
8... c6
{ An useful move to defend against any Nb5-related ideas. But this makes it difficult for Black to move the b8-knight. }
9. Nf3 Bxg3
{ In order to develop the b8-knight, but this opens up the h-file. } 10. hxg3
Nbd7 11. e4
{ Thematic idea. White does not necessarily want to play e5, but can also wait and keep the tension in the center. }
11... h6 12. Rh4
{ White has a clear line of play because of the open h-file. It isn't easy for Black to find something similar. }
12... Qe7 13. e5 Nh7 14. O-O-O Nhf8 15. Kb1
{ For now, White waits and improves the position. Black doesn't have any major weaknesses, but Black's moves do not flow either. }
15... Ng6 16. Rh5 Qd8 17. Rdh1
{ Preparing to increase pressure on the h-file. White'll look to continue with g4-g5. }
17... b5
{ Arjun tries to create counter-play on the Queenside against the pressure on the h-file, but Black's attack doesn't have the same kind of hook to play against. White on the other hand has the h6-pawn. }
18. Ne2 { Covering the f4-square so White can start pushing g4-g5. } 18... Qb6
19. g4 O-O-O 20. g5
{ White gets the breakthrough and crashes into the kingside. } 20... hxg5 21.
Nxg5 Rxh5 22. Rxh5 Rf8 23. Rh7
{ Black's kingside is falling apart, from a practical perspective. } 23...
Ngxe5
{ Desperate measures from Arjun. Although Black gets three pawns in return as compensation, Black's kingside is too weakened, and the White knight has a very strong outpost on c5. }
24. dxe5 Qxf2 25. Qc2 Nxe5 26. Nf3
{ Weakening the c6-point so White can crash through on the queenside now. }
26... Nxf3 27. gxf3
{ 27.Qxc6+  directly doesn't work, as after  27...Kd8  The e2-knight is hanging and White doesn't have a finish just yet. }
27... Kb7 28. a3
{ White can take his time, as Black's position is filled with weaknesses. }
28... Qxf3 29. Nd4 Qf1+ 30. Ka2 Rc8 31. Nb3
{ The c5-knight will be worth more than 5 pawns. } 31... Qg1 32. Qc3
{ Threatening to play Pac-man on the kingside. } 32... c5 33. Rxg7 Qf2 34. d4
cxd4 35. Na5+ Kb8 36. Qb4 { White's queen crashes towards Black's king. } 36...
d3 37. Qd6+ Ka8 38. Qd7
{ White's attack crashes through and mate is inevitable. The London rises to the occasion and helps White win another important must-win game in the playoff! }
