[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Matlakov, Maxim vs. Bykov, Oleg, Sochi 2018"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4 c5 3. d5 Qb6 4. Nc3 Qxb2 5. Bd2 Qb6 6. e4 d6 7. f4 Qd8 8. Nf3
{ A natural developing move, which could potentially transpose into the theory chapter after 8... a6.   8.a4  is the move mentioned in the theoretical chapter. }
8... e6 { An understandable move, but this directly runs into trouble. } 9.
Bb5+ Bd7 10. dxe6
{ The point. This weakens Black's e6 pawn and there is a concrete way to take advantage of this. }
10... fxe6 11. Bd3
{ White had played perfectly until this point but commits a minor inaccuracy. White still keeps a pretty healthy advantage, nevertheless.   11.Ng5!  Simply kills the game.  11...Bxb5  12.Nxb5  Qd7  13.e5+-  This is a very powerful idea that is not easy to see as a human. White goes straight for Black's King. The Knight on f6 is King's best protector, and White takes it out of its defensive post.   13.Nxe6  is natural for a human being, but  13...Na6!  Defends everything and it is White who is in trouble! }
11... Nc6 12. e5 { Taking out Black's best defensive piece. } 12... dxe5 13.
fxe5 Ng4 { The knight looks active for the moment. } 14. Qe2
{ Black's knight on g4 will become the source of Black's problems as it is disconnected away from the rest of Black's pieces. }
14... Be7 15. O-O
{ White opened the f-file up with fxe5. Black's g4-Knight is vulnerable and the king is quite unsafe. }
15... Qc7
{ Trying to run with the king towards the other side.  15...O-O  16.Qe4  White threatens the knight on g4 and the pawn on h7. Black has no way to defend both. Black loses at least a piece. }
16. Nb5 Qb6 17. c4
{ A very strong move, preventing any ...c4 related counter-play from Black. This kills the activity of Black's pieces and makes his position very difficult. }
17... a6 18. Nd6+ Bxd6 19. exd6
{ Black is completely exposed on the dark squares as well, now. } 19... O-O-O
20. Rab1 Qa7 { The queen on a7 symbolizes Black's position. } 21. h3 Nh6 22.
Bxh6
{ White clears out one potential source of counter-play before moving on for the kill on the queenside. Specifically, the b7-point. }
22... gxh6 23. Be4 Rdf8 24. Rb2 Qb8 25. Qd2
{ There is no need to allow any counter-play :@@EndBracket@@ } 25... Rf6 26.
Rfb1
{ Now White moves in for the finish and Black has absolutely no counter-play. }
26... e5 27. Rxb7 { White's attack crashes through. } 27... Qxd6 28. Qxd6
{ The simplest. White wins the Rook by force. Black understandably, resigns. A powerful game by White!  28.Qxd6  Rxd6  29.Bxc6  Bxc6  30.Rb8++-  White wins the Rook by force. }
