[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Gareyev, Timur vs. Posthuma, Joshua G, Chicago 2022"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4 c5 3. d5 b5 4. e4
{ I love this variation. This is potentially one of the most potent lines in this repertoire. }
4... Nxe4 5. Qf3 Qa5+ 6. Nd2 Nxd2 7. Bxd2 Qb6 8. Nh3
{ Although this isn't the move recommended in the repertoire, White's position is practically easier to play, and Timur Gareev can afford these liberties in this position.  8.a4!  Is recommended in the course. }
8... Bb7 9. c4
{ This is also quite interesting since Black cannot capture on c4. } 9... b4
{ A very natural move that turns out to be a big mistake. Black just takes away the b4 square from the knight, and doesn't make his development problems any easier.   9...bxc4  10.Bxc4  White is just allowed to develop with a tempo.  10...e6  11.O-O+-  White's activity is simply too dominating.   9...Na6  was a better move. But of course, this move is not easy to find! This is such an unnatural move. Black ignores White's move and goes towards activity, with ...Nb4. }
10. Bd3 Qf6 11. Qe2 Qxb2 12. O-O
{ Although White is two pawns down, White has completed his development, while Black has gone around the board hunting pawns with his queen. We all know what this leads to. }
12... d6 13. a3
{ With a lead in development, one upon up lines, even if it is far from the king! }
13... a5 14. Rab1 Qe5 15. Qd1
{ Trying to find a way towards Black's king and also leaving open the e-file for White's rook. }
15... g6 16. Re1 Qg7 { Black's queen symbolizes Black's position. } 17. axb4
axb4 18. Bc1 Qg8
{ Black queen's misery doesn't seem to get any lesser :@@EndBracket@@ } 19. Bb2
Nd7 20. Ra1
{ There is no need to get materialistic. With Black's heavy pieces tucked away on the kingside, White's pieces have a freeway toward Black's king. }
20... Rb8 21. Qe2
{ Ensuring that Black isn't able to free his position and improve his pieces with ...Bg7. }
21... h6 22. Nf4 Kd8 23. Bxg6 { It's time to go for the finish. } 23... fxg6
24. Ne6+ Kc8 25. Ra7 Nb6 26. Be5
{ Beautiful move, opening the way towards Black's king. } 26... Ra8 27. Qa2
dxe5 28. Qa5 Rxa7 29. Qxb6
{ There is no good way to defend for Black as White not only threatens Qc7+, but also Qd8+. }
29... Qxe6 30. Qxe6+
{ Black resigned as Black has not just lost his queen, but also loses a rook by force on the next move. Black was greedy and materialistic neglecting development. This is a good illustration of what happens when Black plays this way. The line with 4. e4 is a good way to get activity and initiative for a pawn sacrifice.   30.Qxe6+  Kd8  31.Qb6+  Wins the a7-rook.   30...Kc7  31.Qxe5+  wins the h8 rook. }
