[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Duda, Jan Krzysztof vs. Giri, Anish, Oslo 2022"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 g6 3. Bf4 Bg7 4. e3 O-O 5. Be2 d6 6. h3 Nc6 7. O-O Ne4 8. Bh2
e5 9. c3 a5
{ Black deviates from the course.  9...f5  10.Bd3  is the line in the course, after which Black is under pressure in the center. }
10. Qc2
{ 10.Bd3  is possible in this position as well, with the same idea as in the course.  10...Ng5  11.Nxg5  Qxg5  12.f4⩲  With a slight advantage due to a better center.  12...Qe7  13.fxe5  dxe5  14.a4⩲  With a slight advantage due to a better center, similar to the lines in the course. White intends to continue with Nd2,Nf3 followed by Qc2, Rae1.   10...f5  can lead to a position where White can force Black to have a bad pawn structure with  11.dxe5  dxe5  12.Bxe4  fxe4  13.Qxd8  Rxd8  14.Ng5⩲  leads to a position where Black loses a pawn by force. }
10... Ng5 11. Nbd2 f5 12. dxe5
{ 12.Nxg5  Qxg5  13.f4  Was much better since after  13...Qe7  14.fxe5  dxe5  15.a4  The London bishop is coming into play! This is an effective concept which is pretty thematic against this setup. }
12... dxe5 13. Rad1 Kh8 14. Bb5 { Exerting pressure on e5. } 14... Na7 15. Bc4
Nxf3+ 16. Nxf3 Qe7 17. a4 e4
{ This move is generally considered to be bad because it opens up the London bishop. }
18. Nd4 Be5 19. Bxe5+ Qxe5
{ The London bishop is exchanged, but Black's problems are far from over. } 20.
Qb3
{ A natural move, making it difficult for Black to develop the c8-bishop.   20.b4!  Is quite strong as well. With Black's pieces struggling to develop, White can afford to improve his position and gain space. }
20... b6
{ With this move, the Black knight can come on to c6. The future of this knight on the rim is truly dim. }
21. Rd2 Bd7 22. Rfd1 Rae8
{ 22...Nc6  Would be a good attempt to solve some of Black's problems, improving the worst piece.  23.Bd5  23...Qf6  24.Nxc6  Bxc6  25.Bxc6  Qxc6  26.Rd7  Although the material is equal, Black's king is exposed, and Black's pieces have no scope for activity. }
23. Ne2
{ With the Rooks lined up on the d-file, it is time to force their entry in. }
23... Bc8 24. Bf7 { Step two of the operation. } 24... Re7 25. Rd8
{ And the rook is in! } 25... Rxd8
{ 25...Qg7  would have been more resistant but after  26.Bc4±  Black's position is still terrible, primarily due to the exclusion of the a7-knight and poor king safety. }
26. Rxd8+ Kg7 27. Rg8+ Kh6 28. Nf4 Qf6 29. Bxg6
{ A very strong and concrete move, ripping open Black king's defense. This is what Anish potentially underestimated. }
29... hxg6 30. Rxg6+ Qxg6 31. Nxg6 Kxg6 32. Qg8+ Kf6 33. h4
{ The culmination of the combination. It turns out that Black's minor pieces are so far off on the other side that the White queen combined with the h-pawn is unstoppable. }
33... Be6 34. Qg5+ Kf7 35. h5 Kf8 36. h6 Bg8
{ The bishop joins to help, but it is only the rook and the bishop playing with the a7-knight excluded. }
37. Qxf5+
{ With the elimination of the f5-pawn, the g-passer also joins the attacking force. }
37... Ke8 38. g4 Bh7 39. Qf6 Rf7 40. Qh8+ Kd7 41. Qd4+ Ke8 42. Qe5+ Kd7 43.
Qd5+ Ke7 44. Qb7 { White finally decides to euthanize the a7-knight. } 44...
Kf6 45. Qxa7 Kg5 46. Qa8 Kxg4
{ Black has eliminated one passer, but the h-passer still remains. } 47. Qe8
Rf6 48. Qd7+ Bf5 49. Qxc7
{ White collects more material as Black still cannot take the h6-pawn. } 49...
Kf3 { 49...Rxh6  50.Qf4++-  wins everything. } 50. Kf1
{ Going for the checkmate!  50.h7  also wins. } 50... Bh3+ 51. Ke1
{ The h-pawn is getting promoted and White threatens checkmate. Anish finally throws in the towel. }
