[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Caruana, Fabiano vs. Kovalev, Vladislav, Chess.com 2022"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 g6 3. Bf4 Bg7 4. e3 O-O 5. Nbd2 d6 6. h3 Nfd7 7. c3 e5 8. Bh2
Nc6 9. a4
{ It is always useful for White to gain space on the Queenside this way against the King's Indian setups. White's position is solid and Black's Knight on d7 blocks the c8 Bishop from developing. So White can choose to wait. }
9... Qe7 10. Be2 e4
{ This looks like an active move, but the pawn can also become a weakness. It was well-protected on e5. }
11. Ng1
{ The London Bishop is now open. The Knight has gone back, but it is temporary. It can activate itself by going Bc4-Ne2. }
11... Nf6 12. a5 a6 13. Bc4
{ The Bishop goes to a better square, clearing the way for the Knight to go to f4. }
13... h5 14. Ne2 h4 15. Nf4
{ The Knight is not just well-placed but also threatens to jump to g6. } 15...
Bf5 16. O-O Qd7 17. Nd5
{ Softening the e4-pawn by removing the f6-Knight which is defending the pawn. }
17... Rfe8 18. Nxf6+ Bxf6 19. Bd5 Re7 20. f3
{ An effective way to break the e-pawn and open up the f-file. } 20... exf3 21.
Qxf3
{ All the Black's pieces on the f-file come under fire now. White threatens e4. }
21... Bg5 22. Bf4
{ Eliminating the dark square Bishop which is an important defensive piece. Without the dark-square Bishop, Black's Kingside is filled with weaknesses and entry points. }
22... Bxf4 23. Qxf4 Be6 24. Ne4 { Moving in for the finish. } 24... Bxd5 25.
Nf6+ Kg7 26. Nxd7 Rxd7 27. e4 Bc4 28. Qf6+ Kg8 29. Rf4
{ Black has not just lost the Queen, but is also about to get mated. This game is an excellent illustration of how effective White's solid London setup is against the King's Indian setup and how to exploit Black's weaknesses when Black overextends their activity. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Nihal, Sarin vs. Georgiev, Kiril, Riga 2021"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Bf4 c5 4. e3 Nc6 5. Nbd2 e6 6. c3 Bd6 7. Bg3 O-O 8. Bd3
b6 9. e4
{ This move is just gaining popularity. Back in 2021, a strong grandmaster close to 2600 wasn't quite familiar with it. }
9... Be7 10. e5 Nh5 11. Ng5 Bxg5 12. Qxh5 g6 13. Qe2 Be7
{ The first deviation from the course and already a big mistake. White retains his initiative, but with equal material, instead of being a pawn down.   13...cxd4  is the best move, but even for a strong grandmaster, this is far from obvious. It gets really scary after  14.h4  When one looks at his position without Stockfish! }
14. Nf3 cxd4 15. Bb5
{ 15.Nxd4  Nxd4  16.cxd4±  Was also fine for White. White simply regains the pawn. White's attack with h4-h5 is still dangerous and Black has no Queenside counter-play. }
15... Qc7 16. cxd4
{ It was a bit more accurate to trade this Knight so as to eliminate potential sources of counter-play with the Knight. However, Nihal choses a more peaceful, albeit no less effective way to conversion. }
16... Nb4 17. O-O
{ White has a significant strategic advantage, so advancing the h-pawn and mating down the h-file isn't the only way of converting the advantage here. }
17... Bd7
{ 17...Qc2  18.Qe3  Ba6  Would have resisted better, but during the game, over the board, it isn't easy to se where the Queen goes after  19.Rfc1  If the Queen takes on b2 with 19...Qxb2, then after 20.Rcb1 wins some material after Rxb4. It doesn't look appealing to take the Queen to e4 either. }
18. Rac1 Bxb5 19. Qxb5
{ Black has managed to trade the 'bad bishop' but that isn't the only problem in Black's position. }
19... Qb7 20. a3 a6 21. Qe2 Nc6 22. h4
{ The dark squares on Black's Kingside is filled with entry points, and Nihal makes the first step towards that. }
22... Rfc8 23. Bf4 { In accodance with the plan. } 23... Na5 24. Bg5 b5 25. Bf6
{ The Bishop has infiltrated the camp in Black's King. It is time to signal to the other pieces to get in. }
25... Bf8 26. h5 Rxc1 27. Rxc1 Rc8 28. Re1
{ It is in White's interest to retain one Rook even at the cost of conceding the c-file. White's Rook might be required to finish off the attack. }
28... Rc4 29. hxg6 fxg6
{ It is a bit of a frying pan into the fire kind of situation, and ...fxg6 weakens the e6-pawn.   29...hxg6  30.Qe3  was hardly better as Black is set to get mated down the h-file on either h7 or h8. }
30. Ng5 Qd7 31. Qg4 Rc6 32. Re3
{ With Black tied down to defend the other weaknesses, the Rook moves in for the finish. }
32... h5 33. Qe2 Qc8 34. Kh2
{ A very useful prophylactic move. The White King is safely tucked away on h2. Black's pieces will never be able to get there. }
34... Rc1 35. Rh3
{ White simply threatens to invade down the h-file with Rxh5. } 35... Nc6 36.
Qd3
{ There is no way to defend the g6-pawn as 35...Nc6 cut the connection between the Queen and Rook, rendering ...Qc2 impossible. Black resigned here. This game is an excellent illustration of the dangers in this position for Black. }
