[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Tari, Aryan vs. Koneru, Humpy, Chess24 2021"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Bf4 e6 4. e3 c5 5. Nbd2 Nc6 6. c3 Bd6 7. Bg3 O-O 8. Bd3
b6 9. e4
{ As mentioned in the notes to the Nihal-Georgiev game, as of 2021, even strong grandmasters close to 2600 aren't so well aware of this move! }
9... dxe4 10. Nxe4 Nxe4 11. Bxe4 Bb7 12. dxc5 Bxc5 13. Qa4 Rc8 14. Rd1 Qe7
{ 14...Qe8??  would lose the game on the spot after.  15.Bxh7+!  Kxh7  16.Qh4+  Kg6  17.Qg5+  Kh7  18.Qh5+  Kg8  19.Ng5+-  All the escape from the Black King is sealed shut. }
15. O-O a5
{ The first deviation from the course. A logical move, addressing White's immediate threat - b4.   15...Rfd8  is the move in the course, although it doesn't solve Black's problems completely either. }
16. a3 Rfd8 17. Rxd8+
{ 17.Rfe1±  is slightly stronger than the game continuation. Black is under so much pressure that moving any piece seems to lose some material! }
17... Nxd8 18. Rd1 b5 19. Qc2 f5
{ An understandable move, trying to blow off some pressure. However, this always weakens the e6 and the e5 square. }
20. Bxb7 Qxb7 21. Qe2 { Black's position is paralyzed. } 21... h6 22. Ne5 Nc6
{ Black collapses under the pressure and blunders. } 23. Nd3
{ Attacking both the c5-bishop and the e6-pawn simultaneously. } 23... Bf8 24.
Qxe6+ Kh8 25. Ne5
{ White is not just winning two pawns, but Black's King is seriously endangered. With the White Queen on e6, White has found a way to enter into Black's position. }
25... Nxe5 26. Bxe5 Qc6 27. Qxf5
{ White collects his second pawn, whilst the initiative still rages on. } 27...
Re8 28. h4 Qc5 29. Bxg7+ Kxg7 30. Rd7+
{ Black has to lose her Queen in order to save herself from checkmate. The position is hopeless. It was amazing how quickly Black's position disintegrated with seemingly normal moves!   30.Rd7+  Qe7  31.Rxe7+  Rxe7  32.Qxb5  White is up by a Queen and four pawns. Black understandably resigned. }
*

