[Black "Grover, Sahaj vs. Ritviz, Parab, 22nd Dubai Open 2022"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 Nc6
{ The Chigorin Setup. Black's idea behind this is to go ... Bg4-Qd7-O-O-O and try to launch a kingside attack. It should be noted that against the early 2.Bf4, this setup is quite useless simply because we have not committed Nf3, making the whole setup behind ...Bg4 pointless. }
3. e3 Nf6 { Preparing for ...Bg4. } 4. Nc3
{ A strange move, but the idea is consistent - to delay Nf3. } 4... Bf5
{ 4...Bg4?!  This move does not work anymore because of a strong resource.  5.f3!  Bf5  6.g4  Bg6  7.h4!  threatening h5 next, so Black has to make room for the bishop.  7...h6  7...h5 would have met with 8.g5 and Black's knight is forced to retreat to g8 to avoid losing the d5-pawn.  8.Bd3  Bxd3  9.Qxd3⩲  with the idea of O-O-O and Nge2. White has a much better position since Black wasted a few moves developing the light-squared bishop, which gave White substantial kingside play. }
5. Bd3 Bxd3 6. cxd3
{ The position is quite similar to Chapter 8 - the 3...Bf5 variation. The one difference is that Black's knight is now in misplaced on c6. }
6... e6 7. Nf3 Bd6 8. Bg3 { Typical retreat. } 8... O-O 9. Qb3 a6 10. Bh4
{ Getting the bishop out of the way to castle. The exchange with ...Bxg3-hxg3 is less ideal once we have castled short since we do not have control over the h-file. }
10... b5
{ The first mistake. During post-game analysis, my opponent mentioned that he played this move because he could not find a plan for Black and decided to gain space on the queenside to generate play.   10...Rb8  is a bit less committal. But after  11.Rc1  White keeps a very comfortable position. It is still not clear what Black's plan will be in the next few moves. }
11. O-O Be7 12. Rac1
{ Taking control over the semi-open file, targeting the c7-pawn. } 12... Nd7
13. Bg3
{ This seems logical at first, but taking the bishop was far superior:  13.Bxe7  Nxe7  14.a4  c6  15.Qa3⩲  .  During the game, I did not realize the potential of this move. White simply aims to push b2-b4 to fix the weakness on c6. The follow-up could be to go Nd2-Nb3-Nc5 - but of course, White is in no rush to do this and can also play quiet moves. }
13... Na5 14. Qd1 c5 { Finally, Black breaks open the position. } 15. b4
{ Maybe not the best response, but quite effective regardless.   15.dxc5  Bxc5  16.e4⩲  was perhaps superior. }
15... cxd4
{ 15...cxb4?  does not work because of  16.Nxd5  exd5  17.Bc7  Qe8  18.Bxa5+-  and Black's pawn structure is broken. Soon enough, White should be able to capture either the b4 or d5-pawn. }
16. Nb1 Nb7
{ 16...Bxb4?!  would allow  17.Bc7  Qe7  18.a3±  and White wins a piece. } 17.
Nxd4 Bd6 18. f4
{ During the game this felt extremely strong because of the potential f4-f5 break. However, Black is able to equalise the position with correct play.   18.Bxd6  Nxd6  19.Nd2⩲  was much stronger. White still controls the c-file and can also generate play on the kingside via f4-Qg4-N2f3. }
18... Qf6
{ 18...Rc8  was a bit stronger.  19.a3  Rxc1  20.Qxc1  Qa8=  with the idea of ...Rc8. }
19. Rc6
{ This move seemed extremely strong during the game since the threat of f5 is very real now. But, Black could have equalized here. }
19... Bxb4
{ A fatal mistake under time pressure.   19...Rfc8  20.Qc2  Nb6!  protecting the c8-rook. I had missed this move during the game. Black's next move should be to go ...Nd8 and soon enough should be able to exchange the c6-rook. }
20. f5
{ Even though this move seems to be extremely strong, I missed the winning move.  20.Rc7!  Nbc5  21.Nc6+-  And the bishop on b4 is trapped! }
20... Qe7
{ The final mistake.   20...Qd8  was the only way to continue the game.  21.Qg4  Nf6  22.Qh3→  White still maintains a massive attack on the kingside, but with correct play Black should be able to hold this position. }
21. Rc7 Nd8 22. f6 gxf6 23. Bh4 *

